                     "meta_value": {
                        "__cdata": "a:10:{i:1582566805206;s:1021:\"42 USC 666(a)(7), 45CFR302.70(a)(7), Iowa Code 252B.9(3)(j) and 441 IAC 95.12(252B) provide for the enforcement of child support obligations through credit reporting. “Credit reporting” is an enforcement tool in which ICAR reports the amount of a <span style=\"color: red;\">case\'s</span> IV-D delinquency to credit agencies (credit agencies are also called consumer reporting agencies or credit bureaus). This information is reported on the payor’s credit history when the payor’s total <span style=\"color: red;\">case</span> IV-D delinquency is <span style=\"color: red;\">equal to or greater than $1,001</span>.\n\nA wide range of entities use a person’s credit history for different purposes. Some examples include:\n<ul>\n \t<li>Financial institutions review the credit history when considering the payor for loans and credit.</li>\n \t<li>Some employers review credit histories when making hiring decisions.</li>\n \t<li>Insurance companies review credit histories to determine rates.</li>\n \t<li>Etc.</li>\n</ul>\";i:1582566835968;s:1621:\"Payors may use the information below to request credit reports, dispute information on their credit report, request a fraud alert, or place a security freeze on their report.\n\n<b>Equifax Credit Information Services, Inc.</b>\nPO Box 740241\nAtlanta, GA 30374\n\nPhone: 1-800-685-1111\nWebsite: <a href=\"http://www.equifax.com/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\"><b>www.equifax.com</b></a>\n\n<b>Payors can dispute information on their credit report 1 of 3 ways:</b>\n<ol>\n \t<li style=\"list-style-type: none;\">\n<ol>\n \t<li><b>Online</b> - Initiate a dispute online at <a href=\"https://www.ai.equifax.com/CreditInvestigation/home.action\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\"><b>http://www.ai.equifax.com/CreditInvestigation/home.action</b></a></li>\n</ol>\n</li>\n</ol>\n&nbsp;\n<ol>\n \t<li><b>Mail</b> - To dispute by mail, please mail the dispute to this address:Equifax Information Services, LLC.\nPO Box 740256\nAtlanta, GA 30348</li>\n \t<li><b>Phone</b> - 1-866-349-5191; select option 5</li>\n</ol>\nDisputes by telephone are not automated. To submit a dispute via telephone the payor must select option 5 for a customer service agent.\n\n<b>TransUnion</b>\n\nPhone#: 800-916-8800\nMailing address:\nTrans Union LLC\nConsumer Dispute Center\nPO Box 2000\nChester, PA 19016\nOnline: <a href=\"https://dispute.transunion.com/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\"><b>https://dispute.transunion.com</b></a>\n\n<b>Experian</b>\n\nPhone #: 866-200-6020\nMailing address:\nExperian\nPO Box 4500\nAllen, TX 75013\nOnline: <a href=\"http://www.experian.com/acrdispute\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\"><b>www.experian.com/acrdispute</b></a>\";i:1582566838231;s:1451:\"When a payor calls to inquire about a credit reporting referral, ask the payor:\n<ol>\n \t<li>Which credit agency is reporting the delinquency?</li>\n \t<li>What does the entry on the payor’s credit report state?</li>\n \t<li>What are the dates for the referral on the credit report?</li>\n</ol>\nReview the CRREPORT screen and the narratives to determine if CSRU reported the information to the credit reporting agency. If not, explain that credit reporting agencies receive referrals from many different sources (e.g. clerk of court records, other states, etc.) Tell the payor he/she may file a consumer credit dispute <span style=\"color: red;\">directly</span> with the credit agency.\n\nWhen the referral did come from CSRU, explain that we send updated balance information to the credit agencies every month, <span style=\"color: red;\">for the prior month</span>. The payor may file a consumer credit dispute with the credit agency <span style=\"color: red;\">if they do not agree with the information which was reported</span>.\n\nUsing the \"CRA\" process code when searching for narratives may assist you in quickly finding credit reporting narratives (if the “CRA” process code was used when the narratives were created).\n\nIf you have questions when you receive a call from the payor, please send an e-mail to <a href=\"mailto:CSRUPolicy-CreditReporting@dhs.state.ia.us\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\"><b>CSRU Policy - Credit Reporting</b></a>.\";i:1582566838630;s:4865:\"<b>Q.</b> The <i>Notice of Proposed Release to Consumer Reporting Agencies</i> has been sent to the payor and the case no longer meets credit reporting criteria. How do I stop the payor’s case information from being reported to the credit agencies?\n<b>A.</b>\n<ol>\n \t<li>When ICAR <b>has not sent</b> a payor’s case information to the credit reporting agencies <span style=\"color: red;\">(payor is noticed, not certified):</span>\n<ul>\n \t<li>Do not do anything to stop the payor’s information from being reported to the credit agencies when the payor’s case no longer meets credit reporting criteria.</li>\n \t<li>ICAR runs the case through the credit reporting program on the 4th Friday of the month, starting the month after we send the <i>Notice of Proposed Release</i> to Consumer Reporting Agencies to the payor. When the case no longer matches the credit reporting criteria (i.e. the payor\'s <span style=\"color: red;\">case IV-D balance is below $1,001</span>), ICAR does not send the case to the credit agencies.</li>\n</ul>\nFor example, on <span style=\"color: red;\">6/14/19</span> we send the payor the <i>Notice of Proposed Release to Consumer Reporting Agencies</i>. The payor makes a payment on <span style=\"color: red;\">6/30/19</span> and the payor’s <span style=\"color: red;\">case</span> IV-D balance is now <span style=\"color: red;\">below $1,001</span>. ICAR reviews the credit reporting screen the 4th Friday of <span style=\"color: red;\">July 2019</span> and deletes the credit reporting referral.\n\nThe credit reporting program calculates the amount of delinquency <span style=\"color: red;\">through the prior calendar month</span>.</li>\n \t<li>When ICAR <b>has sent</b> a payor’s case information to the credit reporting agencies:\n<ul>\n \t<li>Do not do anything to stop the payor’s information from being reported to the credit agencies when the payor’s case no longer meets credit reporting criteria. ICAR runs the case through the credit reporting program on the 4th Friday of the month.</li>\n \t<li>When the case no longer matches the credit reporting criteria (i.e. the payor\'s <span style=\"color: red;\">case</span> IV-D balance is zero), ICAR <span style=\"color: red;\">updates</span> the CRREPORT screen <span style=\"color: red;\">account status field</span> and sends an update to the credit agencies to <span style=\"color: red;\">update</span> the payor’s credit agency records.</li>\n</ul>\nThe <span style=\"color: red;\">payor\'s case may</span> remain <span style=\"color: red;\">on the payor\'s credit history for up to 7 years after the balance is reported as zero</span>.</li>\n</ol>\n<b>Q.</b> The <i>Notice of Proposed Release to Consumer Reporting Agencies</i> has been sent to the payor. The case still meets credit reporting criteria, but I do not want the payor’s case information sent to the credit reporting agencies (i.e., I am in the process of correcting the balance on the case and I am waiting to receive documents from the payor’s attorney). How do I stop the payor’s case information from being reported to the credit agencies?\n<b>A.</b> <span style=\"color: red;\">Send an email to <a href=\"mailto:CSRUPolicy-CreditReporting@dhs.state.ia.us\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\"><b>CSRU Policy - Credit Reporting</b></a> with the case number, payor\'s name, and the reason why the case should not be reported to the credit reporting agency.</span>\n\n<b>Q.</b> <span style=\"color: red;\">A payor\'s case</span> is referred to the credit agencies. The payor needs the information removed immediately from his/her credit report and cannot wait until the credit reporting program runs again. What can I do?\n<b>A.</b> Send an e-mail to <a href=\"mailto:CSRUPolicy-CreditReporting@dhs.state.ia.us\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\"><b>CSRU Policy - Credit Reporting</b></a> requesting a review of the case. The Credit Reporting team will determine if a UDF (Universal Data Form) can be sent to the credit agencies to remove the delinquency from the payor’s credit report. Include the credit agency name for which the payor is disputing the information, the payor’s name, case number <span style=\"color: red;\">and the reason why the case should not be reported</span> in the e-mail.\n\n<b>Q.</b> In December 2010, Federal Interstate Regulations changed to mandate that only one state in an interstate action, the responding state, should be reporting <span style=\"color: red;\">payor\'s cases</span> for credit reporting enforcement. Has Iowa made this change yet?\n<b>A.</b> Yes, CSRU has made this automated change to credit reporting enforcement. When the rspn state field on the INTERSTA screen displays “IA” and the interstate process is not dismissed or ended (and the payor meets all other credit reporting criteria), CSRU reports the <span style=\"color: red;\">case</span> for credit reporting enforcement.\";i:1582566838967;s:953:\"When ICAR locates a <span style=\"color: red;\">case which</span> meets credit-reporting criteria, ICAR generates form 470-2223, <i>Notice of Proposed Release to Consumer Reporting Agencies</i>, to the laser printer in the Hoover building in Des Moines. The staff at the Hoover building mail out the form by regular mail to the payor\'s last known address.\n\nThe purpose of this notice is to give the payor an opportunity to request a conference. The payor has 15 days from the date on the credit reporting notice <span style=\"color: red;\">(current notice date on the CRREPORT screen)</span> to request the conference. The date displayed in the <span style=\"color: red;\">current notice date</span> field is seven (7) days after ICAR generates the <i>Notice of Proposed Release to Consumer Reporting Agencies</i> to the payor. This delay allows time for ICAR to generate the notice to the payor and for the U.S. Postal Service to deliver mail to the payor.\";i:1582566839287;s:570:\"A payor may request a conference verbally or in writing within 15 days of the date on the credit reporting notice.\n\nIf the payor reports a mistake of fact affecting the payor balance after the time period for review has passed, accept the information.\n\nIssues to discuss at the conference are limited to the following mistakes of fact.\n<ul>\n \t<li>There is a mistake of identity,</li>\n \t<li>There is a mistake in the balance to be reported, or</li>\n \t<li>The <span style=\"color: red;\">case</span> does not otherwise meet the credit reporting criteria.</li>\n</ul>\";i:1582566839607;s:484:\"<a href=\"http://dhs.iowa.gov/sites/default/files/11-c.pdf\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\"><b><img src=\"https://stcsruportalcli.blob.core.windows.net/csruportalwpcontent/2020/02/pdf.png\" /> Employees Manual Title 11, Chapter C</b></a>\n\n<a href=\"http://dhs.iowa.gov/sites/default/files/11-c-app.pdf\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\"><b><img src=\"https://stcsruportalcli.blob.core.windows.net/csruportalwpcontent/2020/02/pdf.png\" /> Employees Manual Title 11, Chapter C, Appendix</b></a>\";i:1582566839934;s:1032:\"The CRA balance is determined by comparing the prior 83 month coupon amount to the adjusted balance on the case though the prior month; the CRA balance is the lesser of the two numbers.\n\nExample:\n<ol>\n \t<li>The case has an obligation that started in 2/1/2001 for $200 per month. Coupons on the case for the past 83 month time period of 4/1/2012-2/28/2019 reflect $200 per month. The total coupons for the time period is $16,600.</li>\n \t<li>The case balance (less 17/47 coupons and payments) from the start of the case through 2/28/2019. In order to calculate this amount you add back in payments that are received after the 2/28/2019 date and subtract the coupons after 2/28/2019.</li>\n</ol>\nThe case has a total case balance of $14,680.76 (with no 17/47 balance on the case).\n\nPayments totaling $152.10 were received after 2/28/2019.\n\nCoupons billed after 2/28/2019 total $200.\n\n$14,680.76 + $152.10 –$ 200 = $14,632.86.\n\nYou then take the lesser of the two calculations above to get the CRA balance of $14,632.86.\";i:1582566840271;s:4124:\"There are three ways to remove a payor\'s <span style=\"color: red;\">case</span> from credit reporting.\n<ul>\n \t<li><b>Automatic Removal</b>The first method to remove a payor\'s <span style=\"color: red;\">case</span> from credit reporting is ICAR’s automated program. ICAR automatically sends the credit reporting agencies information to remove the credit reporting referral from the payor’s records when:\n<ul>\n \t<li>The case is closed.</li>\n \t<li>The <span style=\"color: red;\">payee is approved for</span> good cause.</li>\n \t<li>The bankruptcy (y/n) field on the PAYOR screen is “Y”.</li>\n \t<li>The init state field on the INTERSTA screen displays “IA” and the interstate process is not dismissed or ended.</li>\n \t<li>The case is in sub-system error status.</li>\n \t<li>There is a \"Y\" in the do not certify field on the CRREPORT screen.</li>\n \t<li>There is no DOB &amp; no SSN for the payor.</li>\n</ul>\n&nbsp;\n\nThis automated process is the best choice. However, if you determine the automatic program will not remove the case and you do not want to send the payor’s case information to the credit agencies, you may <span style=\"color: red;\">email <a href=\"mailto:CSRUPolicy-CreditReporting@dhs.state.ia.us\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\"><b>CSRU Policy - Credit Reporting</b></a> to see if an entry in the DO NOT CERTIFY field is appropriate. Send an e-mail to <a href=\"mailto:CSRUPolicy-CreditReporting@dhs.state.ia.us\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\"><b>CSRU Policy - Credit Reporting</b></a> requesting a review of the case. The Credit Reporting team will determine if a UDF (Universal Data Form) can be sent to the credit agencies to remove the delinquency from the payor’s credit report. Include the credit agency name for which the payor is disputing the information, the payor’s name, case number, and the reason why the case should not be reported in the e-mail.</span></li>\n \t<li><b>Do Not Certify</b><span style=\"color: red;\">Central Office</span> may enter a “Y” in the do not certify field:\n<ul>\n \t<li>Before ICAR sends a notice to the payor.</li>\n \t<li>After ICAR generated a notice to the payor and ICAR has not submitted the payor’s <span style=\"color: red;\">case</span> to the credit agencies. The credit reporting program does not send the payor’s <span style=\"color: red;\">case</span> to the credit agencies.</li>\n \t<li>After ICAR sends the payor’s <span style=\"color: red;\">case</span> to the credit agencies. ICAR sends an update to the credit agencies to <span style=\"color: red;\">delete</span> the <span style=\"color: red;\">case</span> from the payor’s credit agency records.</li>\n</ul>\n&nbsp;\n\nUse do not certify field only in limited circumstances. (One example is when the payor\'s <span style=\"color: red;\">case meets</span> all credit reporting criteria and there are accounting problems that can only be corrected through special handling).\n\nBefore you <span style=\"color: red;\">send an email please</span> make sure all of the following conditions exist:\n<ul>\n \t<li>We should not report the payor\'s <span style=\"color: red;\">case</span> to credit agencies.</li>\n \t<li>ICAR will not remove the case from credit reporting with the automated cycle unless a “Y” is displayed in the do not certify field.</li>\n \t<li>The condition that makes the payor\'s <span style=\"color: red;\">case</span> ineligible for credit reporting is permanent or of uncertain duration.</li>\n</ul>\n&nbsp;\n\nWhen <span style=\"color: red;\">Central Office</span> enters a \"Y\" in the do not certify field:\n<ul>\n \t<li>A narrative <span style=\"color: red;\">(CRA 46 or CRA55)</span> issues and prompts <span style=\"color: red;\">Central Office</span> to make an entry. <span style=\"color: red;\">Central Office</span> enters the reason a “Y” <span style=\"color: red;\">is entered</span> in the do not certify field.</li>\n</ul>\n&nbsp;\n\nWhen a “Y” <span style=\"color: red;\">is entered</span> in the do not certify field on one case, <span style=\"color: red;\">the payor may have other cases which could still report to credit reporting agencies.</span></li>\n</ul>\";i:1582566840585;s:2168:\"<b>Case Selection - The Second Friday of Each Month</b>\n\nOn the second Friday of each month, ICAR identifies new cases and generates form 470-2223, <i>Notice of Proposed Release to Consumer Reporting Agencies</i> to the payor. The initial search criteria is:\n<ul>\n \t<li>The <span style=\"color: red;\">cases</span> IV-D balance <span style=\"color: red;\">$1,001.00</span> or above.</li>\n \t<li>The case is in active status.</li>\n \t<li>There is a current or previously verified address on ICAR for the payor.</li>\n \t<li>There is a social security number for the payor.</li>\n \t<li>Good cause <span style=\"color: red;\">has not been granted for the payee</span>.</li>\n \t<li>The bankruptcy (y/n) field on the PAYOR screen is blank or “N”.</li>\n \t<li>The deceased field on PAYOR screen is blank or \"N\".</li>\n \t<li>The do not certify field on CRREPORT screen is blank.</li>\n \t<li>The case is not in sub-system error status.</li>\n \t<li>The rspn state field on the INTERSTA screen displays “IA” and the interstate process is not dismissed or ended.</li>\n</ul>\n\n<hr />\n\n<b>Reporting the Payors case to Credit Agencies—The Fourth Friday of Each Month</b>\n\nOn the fourth Friday of each month ICAR:\n<ul>\n \t<li>identifies the cases in which ICAR generated form 470-2223, <i>Notice of Proposed Release to Consumer Reporting Agencies</i> in the <b>previous month’s</b> initial search and\n<ul>\n \t<li>Sends the payor’s name, address, date of birth, SSN, case number, and <span style=\"color: red;\">case</span> IV-D balance to the credit agencies for the first time, or</li>\n \t<li>Deletes the <span style=\"color: red;\">current notice date field on the CRREPORT</span> screen when the payors’ case(s) no longer meets criteria.</li>\n</ul>\n</li>\n \t<li>identifies payors with cases already certified to the credit agencies and\n<ul>\n \t<li>Sends a balance update to the credit agencies, <span style=\"color: red;\">(once the balance is zero the case may remain on the payor\'s credit report for an additional seven years)</span>, or</li>\n \t<li>Deletes <span style=\"color: red;\">cases that no longer meet certain criteria</span>.</li>\n</ul>\n</li>\n</ul>\";}"
