                        "__cdata": "a:4:{i:1584460564183;s:1515:\"<b>What is ADMOD - Administrative Modification Process</b>\n\nThis process expedites modification of support awards to reflect changes in the financial or other circumstances of the parents of children entitled to support. The administrative modification process is used in those situations in which the administrative review and adjustment process is inappropriate or unavailable.\n\nThe administrative modification process is limited in scope to only those issue directly related to permanent child support and medical support obligations including:\n<ul>\n \t<li>A potential increase or decrease in the amount of the child support obligation because of a substantial change in the net income of either parent,</li>\n \t<li>Additional children need to be added to the support order,</li>\n \t<li>The dollar amount of the support order was set at zero or reserved,\nAn error was made during the preparation or filing of the support order, or</li>\n \t<li>A minor obligor failed to comply with the education or parenting class requirements.</li>\n</ul>\nThe Unit may begin the administrative modification process if:\n<ul>\n \t<li>One of the parties completes the form 470-2749, Request to Modify a Child Support Order to request an administrative modification and criteria are met.</li>\n \t<li>The Unit becomes aware of cases that meet the criteria for administrative modification (e.g., a child needs to be added to the order).</li>\n \t<li>The child support agency in another state requests a modification.</li>\n</ul>\";i:1584460565153;s:263:\"<a href=\"http://intra/csruhandbooks/HANDBOOKS/Admod/Flowcharts/Flowchart%20for%20Administrative%20Modificatio1.pdf\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\"><img src=\"https://stcsruportalcli.blob.core.windows.net/csruportalwpcontent/2020/02/pdf.png\" /> <b>Flowchart</b></a>\";i:1584460565664;s:37680:\"<h3>Postponement and the 3-month/3-month Rule</h3>\n<b>Part 1: Objectives</b>\n\nThe Child Support Recovery Unit uses the 3-month/3-month rule in order to assist customers experiencing a substantial financial change. This training gives you directions to use when applying the 3 month/3 month rule and postponement procedures in the administrative modification (admod) and review and adjustment (review) processes.\n\nThis training:\n<ul>\n \t<li>Provides background on the basis for the 3-month/3-month rule</li>\n \t<li>Clarifies which types of cases require the 3-month/3-month rule be met</li>\n \t<li>Clarifies when acceptance or denial of a review or admod request is appropriate</li>\n \t<li>Explains how to determine when a parent’s net income has changed by 50% or more during the admod process</li>\n \t<li>Clarifies the use of system and personal flags</li>\n \t<li>Explains how to use the weekly reports to track and follow up on cases with issues (multiple postponements, pending private modifications, etc.)</li>\n</ul>\n<b>Part 2: Background Information</b>\n<ol>\n \t<li style=\"list-style-type: none;\">\n<ol>\n \t<li><b>Legal Basis</b>\nIowa courts determined that in order to qualify as a “substantial change of circumstances,” the change must be permanent and continuous, rather than temporary. The “permanent and continuous” requirement was codified in Iowa Code and Administrative Rules as the 3-month/3-month rule—a change is “permanent” when it has lasted for 3 months and it is “continuous” when it is expected to last another 3 months.\n<ol>\n \t<li><b>From the Subchapter III, Administrative Modification Section of the Iowa Code Chapter 252H.18A(3) Request for review outside applicable time frames</b>\n3. …a substantial change in circumstances means there has been a change of fifty percent or more in the income of a parent, and the change is due to financial circumstances which have existed for a minimum period of three months and can reasonably be expected to exist for an additional three months.</li>\n \t<li><b>From the Division IV, Review and Adjustment of Child Support Obligations Section of the Iowa Administrative Rules 441—99.62(3)(a)(2) Review outcome</b>\n(2) Variation is due to a change in financial circumstances which has lasted at least three months and can reasonably be expected to last for an additional three months.</li>\n \t<li><b>From the Division V, Administrative Modification Section of the Iowa Administrative Rules 441—99.81(252H) Definitions</b>\n2. The change is due to financial circumstances which have existed for a minimum period of three months and can reasonably be expected to exist for an additional three months, pursuant to Iowa Code section 252H.18A.</li>\n \t<li><b>Iowa Administrative Rules 441—99.83(1) Substantial change of circumstances</b>\na. A change of at least 50 percent in the net income of a parent as defined by guidelines. The new net income will be compared to the net income upon which the current child support obligation was based.\nb. The change is due to financial circumstances which have existed for a minimum period of three months and can reasonably be expected to exist for an additional three months.</li>\n \t<li><b>Iowa Administrative Rules 441—99.91(5) Denying requests; Change of circumstances</b>\nc. The change in income has not yet lasted for three months, as required in paragraph 99.83(1)“b,” or\nd. The change in income is not expected to last another three months, as required in paragraph 99.83(1)“b,” or</li>\n</ol>\n</li>\n</ol>\n</li>\n</ol>\n&nbsp;\n<ol>\n \t<li><b>Administrative Modification</b>A customer may request an administrative modification due to a substantial change of circumstances; to add an additional child to the support order; to set reserved child support; to correct an error or omission in a child support order; when a minor obligor fails to comply with parenting class or education requirements; or for a cost-of-living alteration.\n\nThe 3-month/3-month rule <b>only</b> applies to administrative modifications for substantial change of circumstances. In other words, you should only postpone an administrative modification on ICAR using the FIN reason if the admod request was due to a party’s substantial change in their financial circumstances (ADMODRESN code SC).\n\n1. Mrs. A requests a modification because a new child was born and she wants to get the child added to the existing order. Last week, Mr. A started a new job. He was working at Home Depot and is now working at Lowe’s.\n\nRegardless of Mr. A’s current income, because the purpose of the modification is to add a child, accept the request and proceed with Admod. Do not postpone the action due to the change in financial circumstances not being ‘permanent’ and ‘continuous.’</li>\n \t<li><b>Review</b>A customer does not need to meet the substantial change requirement in order to qualify for a review. A child support obligation qualifies for the review process if it has been at least two years from the filing date of the support order or most recent modification or the last completed review, whichever is later.\n\nHowever, after you have accepted a review that meets the two-year requirement, a party’s financial situation may change in a way that triggers the 3-month/3-month rule.\n\n2. Mr. B requests a modification. The existing order was entered four years ago and has not been modified. You accept the request and begin a Review action. While calculating guidelines, you notice that Mr. B changed from working at Casey’s General Store to working at the State of Iowa 1 month ago. Mr. B’s income has changed in the last 3 months.\n\nAt this point in the Review process, you must postpone the process because Mr. B’s recent change in income has not yet existed for 3 months and thus does not yet meet the 3-month/3-month requirement.</li>\n</ol>\n<b>Part 3: Accepting or Denying the Modification Request</b>\n<ol>\n \t<li><b>Admod</b>Per Iowa Code and Administrative Rules (see above), a party’s change in financial circumstances must have existed for a minimum of three months in order to qualify for a modification due to substantial change. If a customer requests a modification due to substantial change before their financial circumstances have existed for three months, you should deny the request. Use Admod deny reason 13 – Request is for substantial change and there is no proof of a substantial change. Inform the customer of the 3-month/3-month rule and when it would be more appropriate for them to submit their modification request. This allows the customer to establish the “permanent” requirement of the 3-month/3-month rule.\n\nOnce the permanent requirement has been met, you can use a reasonable person standard to determine if the financial circumstances will last another 3 months, and meet the “continuous” requirement of the rule. Denying the modification request does not create a hardship for the customer; <span class=\"color: red;\">recurring postponements may. Explain the reasons for the two 3-month periods when you talk to customers so they understand, including the reasoning that it can be better to wait in case more changes happen during either three month period, which would cause more delays.</span>\n\n1. Mrs. C requests a modification because she was laid off from her job at Principal Financial last month and has not found a replacement. She is working some odd jobs, but is having a hard time fulfilling the existing court ordered support amount so wants the support lowered. The existing order was last modified 10 months ago.\n\nBecause the modification was requested due to Mrs. C’s substantial change in income and the change has not lasted 3 months, do not accept the Admod application and postpone the action until the financial circumstances are considered ‘permanent’ and ‘continuous.’ Instead, deny the request.</li>\n \t<li><b>Review</b>A review must be accepted and determined appropriate before you apply postponement procedures. If you know immediately that the parties don’t meet the 3-month/3-month criteria, accept the review request in one step, and then postpone the review in a second step. You don’t have to serve the parties before postponing. If the substantial change happens later in the process, postpone when you know about it.\n\n2. Mr. D requests a modification because he is now working a lower paying job. He was previously working for Wells Fargo, but 3 weeks ago he became self-employed running his own accounting business. He does not have a lot of business yet and is having a hard time fulfilling the existing court ordered support amount so wants the support lowered. The existing order was last modified 3 years ago.\n\nBecause it has been at least two years since the order was last modified, Mr. D qualifies for a review and you must accept the request and proceed with a review action.\n\nHowever, because Mr. D’s income change is not yet 3 months old, you must postpone the review action until his income change has existed for 3 months and can reasonably be expected to last another 3 months.</li>\n</ol>\n<b>Part 4: Determining the Income Change</b>\n\nThe customer’s substantial change in income must have existed for a minimum period of three months <u>and</u> must be reasonably expected to exist for an additional three months. During a modification, the 3-month/3-month rule is triggered by an <b>income change</b>, not necessarily an employment change.\n\nFor example, if a customer changes employers, but is performing the same kind of job at the same rate of pay, there is no substantial change in financial circumstances. Similarly, if a customer changes employers, is working a completely different kind of job, but is still making roughly the same amount of monthly income, there is no substantial change. Also, if a customer changes positions with the same employer but is making a different wage, a substantial change may have occurred, depending on the difference in wage.\n<ol>\n \t<li><b>Admod</b>To determine if a customer’s income has changed by 50% or more, compare the customer’s current net income to the net income used to set the current obligation. If the customer has another income change during the course of the admod, remember you are not comparing the second income change to the first income change. You are still comparing the second income change to the income used to set the current obligation. If the second income change does not meet the 50% requirement, you can end the modification process.\n\n1. Mrs. E requests an admod based on a substantial change in her income. The order was last modified 8 months ago. At the time the existing obligation was set, Mrs. E was working at Nationwide. Three months ago, she lost her job and began receiving unemployment benefits which are over 50% less than her income at Nationwide. You accept the request.\n\nAfter you have served both parties, Mrs. E calls you and reports she is back at Nationwide, making the same income as she was making in her old position. Mrs. E’s income is no longer 50% different than the income used to set the current obligation and thus no longer meets the requirements of the 3-month/3-month rule. End the process, with a 5, and narrate.</li>\n \t<li><b>Review</b>In the review process, the customer’s income does not have to have changed by 50% or more. Instead, the change in income must result in an obligation that varies from the current child support obligation by more than 20%.\n\n2. Mr. F requests a modification because his income has gone down and he would like his child support obligation reviewed. The order was last modified 4 years ago and qualifies for a review and adjustment.\n\nMr. F’s income at the time of the original order was $90,000 per year. Due to a job change than happened a year ago, Mr. F now makes $60,000 per year. The new child support amount varies from the old amount by more than 20%, but less than 50%. Because this is the review and adjustment process, the change meets the required variance and you may continue with modification.</li>\n</ol>\n<b>Part 5: Use of System and Personal Calendar Flags</b>\n\nWhen you postpone an admod or review on ICAR for substantial change in financial circumstances, the system issues calendar flags to check on the status of the customer’s financial information. These flags are set 90 days and 180 days from the calendar date you make entries to postpone the process. If you are able to postpone the process shortly after the customer’s financial change occurs, the system flag will properly serve as a reminder to check on the status of the customer’s financial information when you might be able to continue with the modification.\n\n<b><u>Admod</u></b>\n\n[ninja_tables id=\"1092\"]\n\n<b><u>Review</u></b>\n\n[ninja_tables id=\"1093\"]\n\nHowever, if you receive information about a customer’s financial change when it has already existed for a period of time, you also need to set a personal flag for 3 months from the date the change occurred. This will allow you to more accurately track when a customer’s financial change has met the “permanent” requirement of the 3-month/3-month rule, while also preventing the admod or review from being postponed longer than 3 months.\n\nIf a customer reports another change in financial circumstances while the process is currently postponed, you will need to set new flags to track the new 3-month period. You can do this by reopening the process and re-postponing it, and setting a personal flag if necessary to correctly track the 3-month time period.\n\nHowever, remember that for an admod, if the new income change is not a 50% or more change from the income used to set the current obligation, you can end the admod rather than re-postponing and setting new flags.\n\n<b>Part 6: Narrating the Postponement</b>\n\nWhen you postpone an admod on ADMOD1, ICAR issues narrative ADMOD14 – “Admod postponed because financial information did not meet the 3-month/3-month rule.” When you postpone a review on REVIEW1, ICAR issues narrative REV25 – “Review of support order postponed due to 3-month/3-month rule (temporary status of finances). Status generated for payor, payee, and any necessary third party.” The automatic ICAR narratives do not contain case-specific details. Whenever you postpone an admod or review for change in financial circumstances, you need to narrate the following:\n<ul>\n \t<li>Which party had the change in financial circumstances</li>\n \t<li>What the old source of income was and what the new source of income is</li>\n \t<li>How long the change has existed and when the second 3 month period will end</li>\n</ul>\n<b>Part 7: Weekly Reports</b>\n\nThe weekly Admod and Review reports contain information regarding currently postponed cases. Use this report each week to track the progress of postponed admods and reviews. The reports include columns for “Postponed Reason/Date” and “Review (or Admod) Reopened.” By regularly reviewing these dates, you can prevent admods and reviews from sitting idle after ICAR automatically reopens them when the 3-month time period expires.\n\n<hr />\n\n<h3>3-month/3-month Q &amp; A Sessions</h3>\n(11/2014)\n\n<b>Q1. </b>If a payee changes job, loses a job, or gets a job during the review/admod process and the payor is unemployed (the order will be a minimum order regardless) is it necessary to postpone?\n\n<b>A1. </b>Iowa law and rules are not party-specific when it comes to who must meet the 3-month/3-month rule. We choose to postpone when there is a substantial change in financial circumstance for either parent. This is because we want to be using the correct income for <b>both</b> parties, regardless of whether the resulting order will be a minimum order.\n\n<b>Q2. </b>If the payee or payor is a job hopper, postponing every 3 months may result in the review or admod dragging on for many months or possibly years. Is it okay to proceed at some point maybe using wage reporting income?\n\n<b>A2. </b>The key here is to look for an income change, not just an employment change. If the customer is changing jobs often, but still making roughly the same amount of income, you would not need to postpone.\n\nPlease refer to Part 4: Determining the Income Change, <i>second paragraph</i>. Example 1 - \"is performing the same kind of job at the same rate of pay\" means working for minimum wage at Casey\'\'s vs. Quik Trip. Example 2 - \"is working a completely different kind of job but is still making roughly the same amount of monthly income\" means working retail at $30,000 per year ($2,500 per month) vs working for Iowa Department of Health at $32,000 per year ($2,667 per month). $167 dollars a month is not a substantial change. You would not need to postpone in either of these situations.\n\n<b>Q3. </b>Is there a margin, dollar amount, or maybe percentage that workers can use to determine if a change in income is substantial enough to postpone? (For example, is it necessary to postpone if there is a $1.00 an hour change?) Some changes are easy and obvious to determine. Other changes are questionable.\n\n<b>A3. </b>This question deals with a second (or third, etc.) change in income after the modification process has been started (i.e., you have accepted the admod request, served the parties and are about to complete guidelines when you are informed that one of the parties has changed jobs). The questions you want to ask in each case scenario are:\n<ol>\n \t<li>Is the new change still a 50% change from the net income used to set the current obligation?</li>\n \t<li>Can this new change reasonably be expected to exist for an additional 3 months?</li>\n</ol>\nIf the parties are unhappy with the use of this income, they have the right to request a hearing. You would use a reasonable person standard in these situations - if you are unsure on whether or not you should postpone the process due to the new income, you can contact us for assistance.\n\n<b>Q4. </b>After reading this information we are wondering if we would ever postpone for FIN in ADMOD or if we would always just deny the ADMOD? Here are some examples:\n<ol>\n \t<li>Parent A has a 50% change in income that meets the 3mo/3mo rule. We initiate an ADMOD. Parent A continues to have the 50% change and meet the 3mo/3mo rule. Parent B has a change in income during the course of the ADMOD. Do we postpone for Parent B or just continue with the ADMOD because Parent A continues to meet the 50% change and 3mo/mo rule?</li>\n \t<li>Parent A has a 50% change in income that meets the 3mo/3mo rule. We initiate an ADMOD. At point of guidelines, Parent A has had a change in income again. It still meets the 50% change. Do we need to look at 3 mo/3mo again? Would we postpone or deny or simply proceed? (Parent A income in original guidelines was $3000/mo. Parent A goes on UIB and gets $1000/m and applies for ADMOD after 3 months or more of UIB. We initiate ADMOD and then at point of guidelines the UIB has just ended. Now the income is zero.) Do we deny? Postpone? Or just proceed?</li>\n \t<li>Parent A has a 50% change in income that meets the 3mo/3mo rule. We initiate an ADMOD. At point of guidelines, Parent Aâ€™s income no longer meets the 50% change. Do we just deny/end the ADMOD or should we also check the income of Parent B to see there is a possible 50% change in income for that parent?</li>\n</ol>\n<b>A4. </b>\n<ol>\n \t<li>See question 1. Both parties need to meet the 3-month/3-month rule.</li>\n \t<li>You would postpone the admod. The 50% change still exists; but now you must postpone the process to determine if it will meet the 3-month/3-month rule. <b>NOTE:</b> This is different than what you would do in the example in questions 2 and 3. A change in income from $1000 per month to $0 per month is a much more drastic change than earning $1 or $2 more per hour. The change in this example would drastically change the resulting recommended amount of support. The reasonable person standard would direct you to postpone in this situation.</li>\n \t<li>Generate a no change Admod NOD from the ADMOD3 screen. In the NOD, you\'\'ll put an \"X\" in the \"Modification is not appropriate because none of the criteria for an administrative modification were met\" line and remove the \"X\" from the substantial change line. This NOD includes the language that notifies the party of their right to request a hearing. End the Admod process with a 2 - ADMOD completed, modification not appropriate.</li>\n</ol>\n<b>Q5. </b>Can we deny an ADMOD after we have sent and served the NOI? Or do we process end the ADMOD using the \"Other\" reason and narrate?\n\n<b>A5. </b>No, you cannot deny after you have accepted a modification (either review or admod). You must end the process with an appropriate code.\n\n<b>Q6. </b>Do we really not need to serve parties before postponing a review?\n\n<b>A6. </b>There is no requirement to serve the parties before postponing. \"Postponement\" means you don\'\'t have to take any action until the postponement period is up. However, if your local office procedure is to continue with service, there is nothing prohibiting that. We know that some offices, as a best practice, get service out of the way while waiting for the 3 months to pass because in some instances it can take 2-3 months to get service done on a person.\n\n<b>Q7. </b>If we initiate an ADMOD due to a 50% change and the 3-month/3-month rule is met, and then at the point of guidelines we determine that the 50% change and 3-month/3-month rule is no longer met, how do we end the ADMOD?\n\n<b>A7. </b>See 4 c. c.\n\n<b>Q8. </b>Do the parties have the opportunity to challenge or request a hearing if we decide to end the ADMOD?\n\n<b>A8. </b>The have the same opportunity as when we end an ADMOD without making a change to the obligation. As explained above in answer 4 c. c., the no change Admod NOD includes information about their right to challenge or request a hearing. You are not required to complete and send guidelines with a no change Admod NOD.\n\nIf you have already sent an NOD with the guidelines, the NOD has that same information regarding the right to request a hearing, as in any other admod.\n\n<b>Q9. </b>What do we do if we receive a request for admod and the substantial change has not quite existed for 3 months yet (i.e., it has existed for 2 and a half months)? Are we able to accept that or must we deny it?\n\n<b>A9. </b>You do have the authority to deny it. However, if the customer is very close to meeting the first 3 month requirement and you do choose to accept the admod, you must set a personal flag for when the 3 month period will be up. If you only postpone on the ADMOD1 screen, the system flag will be set for 3 months from the date you enter the postponement. This will lead to the case being postponed for far longer than necessary and can lead to multiple postponements if other changes come up while it is postponed.\n\n<b>Q10. </b>Say we have a situation where a person ends employment and goes to prison. They apply for an admod during the first month of being in prison (so during month 1 of their substantial change). Can we accept their admod request if we know they will be in prison for longer than 6 months?\n\n<b>A10. </b>We do not have the expertise to predict what will happen with someoneâ€™s sentence when they are sent to prison. Our recommendation would be to deny the admod for not meeting the 3-month/3-month requirement, and inform the customer they can reapply after their substantial change has existed for 3 months.\n\n<b>Q11. </b>We do not have a case file but felt we needed some clarification. In the example below, we were not ending the Admod process we were going ahead with guidelines, etc.\n\nOrder established within the past year.\nOne of the parties of case file request or completes application for modification- based on job lost.\nWithin another month parties have been served and the individual that lost their job, has now found a new job.\nBy your directions, we should end the Admod process if there is no longer 50 percent change in income.\nBy doing this, the party can no longer request a court hearing because the process has ended.\nAre we interpreting your directions, correctly?\n\n<b>A11. </b>The correct way to end the Admod process for the above example is:\n<ol>\n \t<li>Generate a no change Admod NOD from the ADMOD3 screen. In the NOD, you\'\'ll put an \"X\" in the Modification is not appropriate because none of the criteria for an administrative modification were met\" line and remove the \"X\" from the substantial change line. This NOD includes the language that notifies the party of their right to request a hearing.</li>\n \t<li>End the Admod process with a 2 - ADMOD completed, modification not appropriate.</li>\n \t<li>You do not need to complete guidelines to send with this NOD.</li>\n</ol>\n\n<hr />\n\n<h3>Special Circumstances - Prisoner Cases</h3>\n<b>Incarcerated Payor Letter Process</b>\n\nPer federal regulations, child support agencies must now take action to let parties know they can request a modification when the agency learns a payor will be incarcerated for over 180 days. CSRU will notify parties of the ability to request a modification, in order to bring incarcerated payors\'\' obligations in line with their current income and ability to pay. The federal regulation Iowa chose to implement requires CSRU to notify both the payor and the payee on the case.\n\nCentral Office created the following documents for staff to use in complying with this regulation:\n<ul>\n \t<li>an \"Incarcerated Payor Letter\" Word document with fillable fields,</li>\n \t<li>an instruction sheet explaining when the Incarcerated Payor Letter does and does not need to be sent to a case party, how to complete the letter, and required case actions, and</li>\n \t<li>a checklist to determine when the Incarcerated Payor Letter does and does not need to be sent to a case party.</li>\n</ul>\nPlease begin using these procedures effective December 1, 2017\n\nWe do not expect or require staff to sort through cases with the sole purpose of finding incarcerated payors. If you are reviewing a case (for any reason) after the effective date of the policy, and you find that the payor is currently incarcerated AND will continue to be incarcerated for another 180 days, you need to follow these procedures, as appropriate.\n<ul>\n \t<li><a href=\"http://intra/csruhandbooks/HANDBOOKS/Review/Contents/SpecialCircumstances/Prisoner%20Cases/Field_Instructions_for_%20IncarceratedPayorLetter.docx\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\"><img src=\"https://stcsruportalcli.blob.core.windows.net/csruportalwpcontent/2020/02/word.png\" /> <b>Link to Instruction Sheet</b></a></li>\n \t<li><a href=\"http://intra/csruhandbooks/HANDBOOKS/Review/Contents/SpecialCircumstances/Prisoner%20Cases/Incarcerated_Payor_Letter_Checklist.docx\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\"><img src=\"https://stcsruportalcli.blob.core.windows.net/csruportalwpcontent/2020/02/word.png\" /> <b>Link to Checklist</b></a></li>\n \t<li><a href=\"http://intra/csruhandbooks/HANDBOOKS/Review/Contents/SpecialCircumstances/Prisoner%20Cases/Incarcerated_Payor_Letter.docx\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\"><img src=\"https://stcsruportalcli.blob.core.windows.net/csruportalwpcontent/2020/02/word.png\" /> <b>Link to Letter</b></a></li>\n</ul>\n<b>Processing Modifications</b>\n\nWhen issuing the NOD for Review or Admod on a prisoner case, manually generate a \"Proposed Order\" based on the Guideline Worksheet.\n\nYou will need to attach a post-it note that says \"Proposed Order.\"\n\nSend one original Proposed Order and one copy (customer copy) for the payor to keep for his/her records along with the NOD, the Guidelines Worksheet and the Child Support Declaration.\n\nAsk the incarcerated payor to review these documents and sign and return the Child Support Declaration if he/she is in agreement with the Proposed Order.\n\nSee the <a href=\"http://intra/csruhandbooks/HANDBOOKS/Review/Contents/SpecialCircumstances/Prisoner%20Cases/Payor\'\'s%20Declaration%20Cover%20Letter.doc\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\"><img src=\"https://stcsruportalcli.blob.core.windows.net/csruportalwpcontent/2020/02/word.png\" /> <b>sample cover letter</b></a>.\n\nAfter sending the Child Support Declaration to the incarcerated Payor, set a flag for: \"Check on return of the Child Support Declaration. Contact the payor\'\'s counselor if not returned.\"\n\nIf the payor does not sign and return the Child Support Declaration, you may attempt to contact the inmate\'\'s counselor, by phone or in writing. Use the following suggested language:\n\n\"Would you please verify that the recent documents mailed to (inmate\'\'s name) were in fact received by (inmate\'\'s name). If (inmate\'\'s name) has any questions about the documents, I can be reached at (phone number) or (inmate\'\'s name) may contact his/her own attorney.\n\nIf at any point during the modification you must change the language of the Proposed Order, resend the Proposed Order along with a new Child Support Declaration to for the payor to sign. Hopefully the payor will sign and return the child support declaration to you by the end of the waiting period so that you immediately proceed with entering the new order.\n\n<b>Note:</b> Be sure to avoid releasing confidential information.\n\n<hr />\n\n<h3>Tribes &amp; Child Support</h3>\n<b>OVERVIEW</b>\n\nThe Personal Responsibility And Work Opportunity Reconciliation Act of 1996 (PRWORA, Public Law, 104-193) and amended by the Balanced Budget Act of 1997 (Public Law 105-33) authorizes the direct funding of tribal child support enforcement programs by the federal government.\n\nTribes may have non-IV-D child support programs and their tribal courts may issue child support orders. For example, the Winnebago Tribe of Nebraska had a non-IV-D child support program before attaining IV-D status in November 2008.\n\nYou must observe the same confidentiality requirements when working with non-IV-D tribal child support programs as you would any other non-IV-D entity. See TRIBAL IV-D AGENCIES for information about confidentiality requirements when dealing with a IV-D tribal agency.\n\nIf a tribal child support program (IV-D or non-IV-D) contacts you requesting assistance, send their contact information to <a href=\"mailto:csrupolicytribes@dhs.state.ia.us\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\"><b>CSRU Policy – Tribes</b></a> and Central Office staff will assist them.\n\n<b> TRIBAL IV-D AGENCIES</b>\n\nTribal IV-D programs must comply with the Full Faith &amp; Credit for Child Support Orders Act (FFCCSOA), but not the Uniform Interstate Family Support Act (UIFSA). Tribal IV-D agencies are subject to the provisions of 45 CFR 309. <span style=\"color: red;\">For a list of Tribal IV-D agencies</span> <a href=\"?page_id=1094\"><b>click here</b></a>.\n\nThey are required to perform the same basic services as states. This includes enforcing and modifying child and medical support orders issued by other states, tribes and countries in accordance with FFCCSOA.\n\nTribal IV-D programs can:\n<ul>\n \t<li>Establish Paternity</li>\n \t<li>Establish Child Support Orders (Health care is not required but may be included)</li>\n \t<li>Enforce Support Orders, including Direct Income Withholding</li>\n \t<li>Modify Support Orders</li>\n \t<li>Share information with other IV-D programs (with some exceptions)</li>\n</ul>\nTribal IV-D programs may make arrangements with states for federal offsets. Iowa does not have this agreement with any Tribal IV-D agencies.\n\nTribal IV-D agencies can access the FPLS directly or they can make arrangements with states to access the FPLS for them. Iowa does not have this agreement with any Tribal IV-D agencies.\n\nYou may share the same types of information that is already on ICAR with Tribal IV-D programs as you do with State IV-D programs. However, information received from the IRS cannot be redisclosed unless independently verified. In addition, information received directly from FPLS or the FCR cannot be disclosed. Do not initiate new FPLS locate searches on behalf of the tribes. See <a href=\"?page_id=1106\"><b>Tribal Confidentiality</b></a> for addition information on what can be shared with tribes. Refer to <a href=\"?page_id=1113\"><b>IRS Address Verification</b></a> and the INTERSTATE CHILD SUPPORT CONFIDENTIALITY ISSUES (UIFSA) section of <a href=\"http://dhs.iowa.gov/sites/default/files/9-a.pdf\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\"><img src=\"https://stcsruportalcli.blob.core.windows.net/csruportalwpcontent/2020/02/pdf.png\" /> <b>9-A, General Program Information</b></a> for more information.\n\nThe Winnebago Tribe of Nebraska and Meskwaki Nation Child Support are the only tribes with Indian country in Iowa that have a IV-D agency. The Sioux City office handles case processing for CSRU that involves Winnebago Child Support. The Waterloo office handles intergovernmental case processing that involves Meskwaki Nation Child Support. The Ottumwa office handles all modifications that involve Meskwaki Nation Child Support.\n\n<b>VERIFICATION OF TRIBAL IV-D AGENCY</b>\n\n<a href=\"http://www.acf.hhs.gov/programs/css/resource/state-and-tribal-child-support-agency-contacts\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\"><b>This link</b></a> has a map which lists all states and the tribal agencies in that state. All tribes with an “*” beside them are in the start-up phase of becoming an approved Tribal IV-D agency. Until a tribe becomes an approved Tribal IV-D agency, do not release information to that tribe.\n\n<b>ADDING TRIBAL COURT ORDERS TO ICAR – HEALTH INSURANCE</b>\n\nTribal court orders are frequently silent with regard to health insurance coverage. This is because there is no requirement for tribal court orders to include medical support. However, tribes are encouraged to make sure children have access to medical care through the Indian Health Service (IHS).\n\nWhen the ONLY medical support language mentioned in the order is about the child(ren) having access to medical care through Indian Health Services, enter a \"Y\" in the hi/ms ordered field on the COURTORD screen.\n\nOn the HEALTH INSURANCE UPDATE screen:\n<ul>\n \t<li>Enter a \"Y\" in the health ins field,</li>\n \t<li>Enter a \"Y\" in the payee field under PARTY ORDERED TO PROVIDE HEALTH INSURANCE, and</li>\n \t<li>Enter an “N” in the cash med support field.</li>\n</ul>\nThese steps ensure the MEDSUM program doesn\'\'t attempt to enforce health insurance against a payor.\n\nFinally, enter a narrative that explains the \"Y\" entry on the payee field on HIUPDATE screen is actually IHS.\n\nIf the order does NOT mention the child(ren) having access to medical care through Indian Health Services, does NOT require a parent to provide a health benefit plan, and does NOT require a parent to pay cash medical support, enter an \"N\" in the hi/ms ordered field on the COURTORD screen.\n\nIf you have questions about whether language in the order refers to IHS, send an e-mail to <a href=\"mailto:csrupolicytribes@dhs.state.ia.us\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\"><b>CSRU Policy – Tribes</b></a>.\n\n<b>REGISTERING AND MODIFYING TRIBAL COURT ORDERS</b>\n\nBefore registering a tribal support order, contact the tribe involved to determine whether or not they still have jurisdiction and are enforcing. Handle as you would any other foreign support order you are registering for modification.\n\nBefore modifying a tribal court order, review the case with your office attorney or Central Office. You must give “full faith and credit” (FFCCSOA) to tribal support orders. Sometimes a tribe will have jurisdiction on a case even when all parties do not live on the settlement.\n\n<b>FILING TRIBAL COURT ORDERS FOR ENFORCMENT</b>\n\nIt is recommended that tribal court orders be registered in Iowa rather than filed for enforcement. Before registering a tribal support order, contact the tribe involved to determine whether or not they still have jurisdiction and are enforcing.\n\n<b>INCOME WITHHOLDING</b>\n\nBefore sending an IWO to an employer, review to see if instructions are provided in <a><b><i>Direct Withholding vs. Intergovernmental Referral</i></b></a>. If there are not instructions, contact <a href=\"mailto:csrupolicytribes@dhs.state.ia.us\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\"><b>CSRU Policy – Tribes</b></a>.\n\n<b>PER CAPITA/STIPEND</b>\n\nIf you find out that a party is receiving per capita or stipend, check to see if the tribe has a IV-D agency. See Verification of Tribal IV-D Agency for more information.\n\nIf you find out that a payor is receiving per capita from a tribe with a IV-D agency, contact the tribe to find out whether CSRU is able to attach the per capita. Find out what documentation the tribe needs from CSRU to attach the per capita.\n\nIf you receive information that the payor is receiving per capita or a stipend from a tribe without a IV-D agency, send an email to <a href=\"mailto:csrupolicytribes@dhs.state.ia.us\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\"><b>CSRU Policy – Tribes</b></a> with the case information and the name of the tribe.\n\n<b>TRIBAL TANF AND THE $25 ANNUAL FEE</b>\n\nIn addition to IV-D agencies, tribes may operate TANF programs. Tribes with TANF programs may not have a IV-D program. If a payee reports they are exempt from the $25.00 annual fee because they received a IV-A grant from a tribe, send an e-mail to the <a href=\"mailto:CSRUPolicy-DistTeam@dhs.state.ia.us\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\"><b>CSRU Policy – Dist Team</b></a> email address for instructions on updating the ANNFEE screen.\";i:1584460566024;s:5654:\"<ul>\n \t<li><a href=\"http://intra/csruhandbooks/HANDBOOKS/Admod/Contents/Resources/Revised_Documents_to_include_when_certifying_a_case_to_court_under_Iowa_Code_Chapters_252C_252F_and_252H.pdf\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\"><img src=\"https://stcsruportalcli.blob.core.windows.net/csruportalwpcontent/2020/02/pdf.png\" /> <b>Revised - Documents to include when certifying a case to court under Iowa Code Chapters 252C, 252F, and 252H</b></a></li>\n \t<li><a href=\"http://intra/csruhandbooks/HANDBOOKS/Admod/Contents/Resources/Documents_to_include_when_Certifying_a_Case_to_Court_Q&amp;A.pdf\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\"><img src=\"https://stcsruportalcli.blob.core.windows.net/csruportalwpcontent/2020/02/pdf.png\" /> <b>Documents to include when Certifying a Case to Court Q&amp;A</b></a></li>\n \t<li><a href=\"file://hoovr3s2/csru.772/CSDRAFT/10-R%20Administrative%20Modification\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\"><img src=\"https://stcsruportalcli.blob.core.windows.net/csruportalwpcontent/2020/02/folder.png\" /><b>Draft Manual 10-R</b></a></li>\n \t<li><b>Legal References</b>\n\n<a href=\"http://search.legis.state.ia.us/nxt/gateway.dll/ic?f=templates&amp;fn=default.htm\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\"><b>Iowa Code</b></a> Section <b>598.21(4)</b> authorizes the Iowa Supreme Court to prescribe uniform support guidelines in accordance with the Family Support Act. Any new or modified support orders entered on or after October 13, 1989, under Iowa Code Sections 598.21, 252A.3, 252C.2, 252H, 675.24, 234.39 or any other section of the Code, must use these guidelines to determine the amount of the child support obligation.\n\n<a href=\"http://search.legis.state.ia.us/nxt/gateway.dll/ic?f=templates&amp;fn=default.htm\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\"><b>Iowa Code</b></a> Section <b>252B.5</b> and <b>252H</b> authorize the Unit to -\n<ul>\n \t<li>Review support orders that the Unit enforces,</li>\n \t<li>Review support orders that are outside the minimum time frame for administrative review and adjustment,</li>\n \t<li>Establish the criteria to be used in the administrative modification process,</li>\n \t<li>Establish procedures for the administrative modification process,</li>\n \t<li>Enter administrative orders when a review of the child support order indicates that an adjustment of the obligation is appropriate.</li>\n</ul>\n&nbsp;\n\n<a href=\"https://www.legis.iowa.gov/docs/ACO/chapter/441.99.pdf\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\"><img src=\"https://stcsruportalcli.blob.core.windows.net/csruportalwpcontent/2020/02/pdf.png\" /> <b>441 Iowa Administrative Code (IAC)</b></a> chapter 99, Division V, contains the rules for the administrative modification process. Provisions in 441 IAC 98.104(3) require that Unit staff provide the payor with the forms necessary to request administrative modification during the license sanction process. The requires the payor to make a written request for administrative modification.\n\n441 IAC 98.3 (252E) and 99.83 (252B, 252H) authorize the Unit to add medical support provisions when the payor has a high potential of obtaining health insurance; unless the payee and children are already enrolled in a health benefit plan (other than Medicaid or HIPP).\n\n<a href=\"http://search.legis.state.ia.us/nxt/gateway.dll/ic?f=templates&amp;fn=default.htm\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\"><b>Iowa Code</b></a> Section 252H.2(6) and 252H.21-24 authorize the Unit to enter administrative orders altering the support order due to a change in the cost of living. The Unit increases or decreases the order by the percentage change of the appropriate consumer price index for the month and year after the month and year that the order was established. It also continues to increase or decrease the amount for each subsequent year through the year prior to the year the request for a cost-of-living alteration is received. The consumer price index for all urban consumers, United States city average, is published in the federal register by the federal department of labor, bureau of labor statistics.\n\nRules and regulations define what information may be released from a child support record. All forms generated by ICAR in the process conform to these rules and regulations. Be sure <b>not</b> to violate confidentiality in any aspect of the administrative modification process. <b>Do not</b> release confidential information including social security numbers, addresses, financial information, and location. Release an individual\'\'s financial statement to the other party only upon request. File the financial statements in the court field but; <b>do not</b> file any supporting documents in the court file. You may release the supporting documents to the court as exhibits during a court hearing. See <a href=\"http://dhs.iowa.gov/sites/default/files/9-a.pdf\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\"><img src=\"https://stcsruportalcli.blob.core.windows.net/csruportalwpcontent/2020/02/pdf.png\" /> <b>9-A, CONFIDENTIALITY OF CHILD SUPPORT INFORMATION</b></a>, for the guidelines on confidentiality.</li>\n \t<li><a href=\"http://intra/csruhandbooks/HANDBOOKS/CaseSetUp/Contents/Resources/MedicaidRecipients-ChangesInLivingArrangements.pdf\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\"><img src=\"https://stcsruportalcli.blob.core.windows.net/csruportalwpcontent/2020/02/pdf.png\" /> <b>Medicaid Recipients - Changes in Living Arrangements of the Child(ren); How CSRU &amp; IM Will Work Together</b></a></li>\n \t<li><a href=\"file://hoovr3s2/csru.772/CSRUPROC/Directives\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\"><img src=\"https://stcsruportalcli.blob.core.windows.net/csruportalwpcontent/2020/02/folder.png\" /> <b>Procedural Directives/Memos</b></a></li>\n</ul>\";}"
