                        "__cdata": "a:14:{i:1584644427187;s:6592:\"This page is devoted to the Building Customer Relationships training that was conducted state-wide in October and November of 2003 by the ISU trainers. During the course of their training, the trainers - Breehan Gerleman and Martha Stewart - collected \"best practice tips\" from around the state. Below you will find a link to those tips. As additional information regarding this training becomes available, it will be added here.\n\n<hr />\n\n<h3>Best practices collected from the field</h3>\n<b>To handle an enthusiastic talker</b>\n<ul>\n \t<li>Let the customer talk, and make a note of each separate concern voiced. Then, when the customer is through, say \"Let’s take one concern at a time\" and discuss each concern.</li>\n \t<li>If you must interrupt the customer, try to do so when the customer is on a positive point. Then, when you continue the conversation and move it in another direction, you can do so with a positive transition—and hopefully keep the conversation going in a positive direction.</li>\n</ul>\n<b>To shake a reluctant talker loose</b>\n<ul>\n \t<li>Use active listening to encourage a customer to add new information to the conversation. Try paraphrasing what a reluctant talker has just told you, as in \"So, you’re working full time now.\" Then, pause and wait for the customer to add some additional information, like where he or she is working or how long he or she has been working.</li>\n</ul>\n<b>When using TDD to communicate with hearing impaired customers</b>\n<ul>\n \t<li>Be especially careful that your wording and expression is professional and clear. The TDD operator transcribes <i>everything</i>, even \"uh\" and \"um,\" just as it is said.</li>\n</ul>\n<b>If you sense a customer has difficulty reading or writing</b>\n<ul>\n \t<li>Offer to work with the customer to fill out the application. Then, conduct an interview, using the form as a guide and fill out the form for the customer.</li>\n</ul>\n<b>To work with an angry customer</b>\n<ul>\n \t<li>Avoid using the statement \"I understand.\" Instead, use a phrase like - \"That sounds like it would be difficult.\" Using the statement \"I understand\" typically further agitates the customer because it implies the CSRU employee has experienced the exact situation as the customer, and, in most cases, the CSRU employee has not. Using a phrase like \"That sounds like it would be difficult\" implies empathy and concern but does not assume a first-hand understanding of the customer’s situation.</li>\n</ul>\n<b>To assist a customer who does not speak or write English</b>\n<ul>\n \t<li>Ask the customer to send a letter into the office in English that makes his or her requests.</li>\n \t<li>Ask the customer to bring in his or her own interpreter to the office. Remember to obtain ROI before starting communication through an interpreter.</li>\n \t<li>Create a list of local translation resources to distribute to customers.</li>\n</ul>\n<b>To best remind yourself and your co-workers to complete necessary case actions</b>\n<ul>\n \t<li>Use calendar flags (rather than Outlook’s calendar) as reminders. If reminders are in calendar flags, any and all employees can view reminders and act on them.</li>\n</ul>\n<b>When leaving messages and requesting a customer calls back</b>\n<ul>\n \t<li>Offer both your private phone number (if you have one) <b>and</b> the 1-800 number so customers can decide which number they would prefer to use. If it\'\'s a long-distance call for customers, they might prefer the 1-800 number.</li>\n</ul>\n<b>When writing narratives</b>\n<ul>\n \t<li>Offer enough detail so attorneys can build a contempt case. Detail all case information as your observations (\"NCP appeared angry and did not answer questions asked of him\"), rather than judgments you are making about the case or customer (\"NCP is always angry and won’t work with us\"). Narratives are part of a legal document.</li>\n</ul>\n<b>When talking with an NCP\'\'s family member that claims no knowledge of his or her whereabouts</b>\n<ul>\n \t<li>Ask the family member how he or she would contact the NCP if there was an emergency or if someone died.</li>\n</ul>\n<b>When negotiating a partial payment agreement with NCPs</b>\n<ul>\n \t<li>Ask them first how much they think they can pay. This gives them a sense of control over the situation and sometimes they may offer a larger payment than you were going to ask for.</li>\n</ul>\n<b>When answering customers’ questions</b>\n<ul>\n \t<li>If you don\'\'t know the answer to a customer\'\'s question, don\'\'t be afraid to admit that and offer to go find an answer.</li>\n</ul>\n<b>When calling for location information</b>\n<ul>\n \t<li>Identify yourself as calling from the State of Iowa. If the location contact questions your affiliation, you can state that you\'\'re calling for the Department of Human Services. If they question you further, explain that you have personal business with the individual in question and you would appreciate their help in locating them. Do not reveal any information that could compromise the NCP\'\'s confidentiality.</li>\n \t<li>If a former (or current) employer is reluctant to share the NCP\'\'s contact information with you or claims that the NCP is not an employee, ask if you can add that statement to the case record. This official sounding request will often convince them to cooperate.</li>\n</ul>\n<b>When talking on the phone with a customer</b>\n<ul>\n \t<li>If you need to look up something in ICAR or do anything else that keeps you rather quiet for a moment or two, explain to the customer what it is you\'\'re doing so they are included in the process. Don\'\'t just let the phone line go silent while you do a search.</li>\n</ul>\n<b>When working with customers face-to-face</b>\n<ul>\n \t<li>If customers ask you to hold their baby while they fill out paperwork, consider purchasing a used infant carrier to avoid any legal issues associated with handing customers’ children. Then you can explain to customers that you\'\'d love to hold their infant, but you\'\'re not allowed to and then offer them the carrier.</li>\n</ul>\n\n<hr />\n\nBelow are links to two community mediation programs that can be offered to customers with disputes about custody and/or visitation:\n<ul>\n \t<li><a href=\"http://www.creativejustice.org/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\"><b>The Center for Creative Justice</b></a> - This site serves families in Story County.</li>\n \t<li><a href=\"http://www.famres.org/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\"><b>Family Resources Inc.</b></a> - Locations in Bettendorf, Burlington, Clinton, Davenport and Muscatine.</li>\n</ul>\";i:1584644436861;s:2671:\"<b>Things to consider regarding change in living arrangement (custody) inquiries</b>\n\nThe following information should be considered in all change of living arrangement issues or complaints. Additionally, answers to these questions should be included in all referrals to Central Office.\n\nAlso see the <a href=\"http://intra/csruhandbooks/HANDBOOKS/CustomerService/Contents/Change%20of%20Custody/ChangeOfCustodyFlowchart.pdf\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\"><img src=\"https://stcsruportalcli.blob.core.windows.net/csruportalwpcontent/2020/02/pdf.png\" /> <b>Change of Custody flowchart</b></a>.\n\n<hr />\n\n<ul>\n \t<li><b>What is the origin of the inquiry or complaint?</b>Governor’s office, State legislators, Ombudsman, etc. Are there specific notes from Governor’s staff if Governor’s office is involved?</li>\n \t<li><b>DHS involvement</b>Was DHS involved in the change of living arrangement for the child, regardless of whether there is past or pending juvenile court action?Is either party receiving state aid for the child(ren)? If the payee was receiving assistance, is it being terminated because DHS determined the child is no longer residing with payee? Is the payor receiving assistance because DHS has determined the child is residing with the payor?\n\nIf the payor is not receiving aid, has aid been denied for reasons not related to residence of the child(ren)?</li>\n \t<li><b>CSRU suspension</b>Is suspension through CSRU an option? If so, have forms already been sent? What has the response been?Are there multiple children on the case but not all have changed custody and there is no step language in the order?\n\nHas CSRU already told any of the parties that CSRU cannot “assist” in facilitating the signing of the suspension forms?\n\nIs this a role reversal case as opposed to a case where the child relocates from the payee to a caretaker?</li>\n \t<li><b>Location/availability of payee or child</b>Is the payee incarcerated, out of state or the country, in a rehabilitation program, or whereabouts are unknown?Is the payee mentally or physically incapacitated? Include the basis for this belief.\n\nIs it questionable as to where the child is residing? Include the basis for this belief.</li>\n \t<li><b>Misc.</b>When contacting or referring to Central Office, list all known orders requiring payment of current CS (including both foreign and IA orders) and list the States and counties where the orders were entered.What is the current account type of the case?\n\nIs there any pending action before the court regarding child support or custody or was there any CS or custody action in the past 12 months (provide specifics)?</li>\n</ul>\";i:1584644437300;s:288:\"<a href=\"http://intra/csruhandbooks/HANDBOOKS/CustomerService/Contents/Change%20of%20Custody/ChangeOfCustodyFlowchart.pdf\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\"><img src=\"https://stcsruportalcli.blob.core.windows.net/csruportalwpcontent/2020/02/pdf.png\" /> <b>Change of Custody Flowchart</b></a>\";i:1584644437605;s:1496:\"<ul>\n \t<li><b>Staff safety</b> – The Department of Human Services has a policy regarding staff safety and policy set for safety issues. This policy can be found at <a href=\"https://das.iowa.gov/sites/default/files/hr/documents/MS_manual/Chapters/SM-09-75.pdf\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\"><b>Violence Free Workplace</b></a> (broken link).</li>\n \t<li><b>Security</b> - Refer to the safety plan for your office.</li>\n \t<li><b>Stress relievers</b> -\n<ul>\n \t<li>Use laughter and humor, but keep it private and limited. It shall not be at the expense of the customers.</li>\n \t<li>Take time away from the situation.</li>\n \t<li>Be mindful of confidentiality. Vent privately with other workers and not in front of, or about the customer. Also, it is not necessary to involve the entire office staff.</li>\n \t<li>Take time to relax and take a few deep breaths.</li>\n \t<li>Set aside something very involved and work on a lighter project for some time frame - then get back to the larger task at hand.</li>\n \t<li>Let another worker review the work product for input.</li>\n \t<li>Focus on what has been accomplished and goals that are met, not on what is not done.</li>\n \t<li>Deep Breath, Smile, Move On!</li>\n</ul>\n</li>\n \t<li><b>Attitude</b> - Keep a positive attitude towards others and yourself. If you have a positive attitude with co-workers and customers, this will affect your own attitude in a positive way. Don’t let others’ negative attitudes affect your attitude.</li>\n</ul>\";i:1584644437861;s:291:\"<a href=\"http://intra/csruhandbooks/HANDBOOKS/CaseResolution/Contents/Resources/Collaborative%20Red%20Dot%20Response.doc\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\"><img src=\"https://stcsruportalcli.blob.core.windows.net/csruportalwpcontent/2020/02/word.png\" /> <b>Collaborative Red Dot Response</b></a>\";i:1584644438164;s:332:\"<a href=\"http://intra/csruhandbooks/HANDBOOKS/CaseResolution/Contents/Resources/Customers%20who%20want%20to%20contact%20the%20BUreau%20Chief.docx\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\"><img src=\"https://stcsruportalcli.blob.core.windows.net/csruportalwpcontent/2020/02/word.png\" /> <b>Customers who want to contact the Bureau Chief</b></a>\";i:1584644438453;s:8664:\"<b>Dealing with a Difficult/Volatile Customer</b>\n\nThere are six steps to follow when dealing with a difficult customer:\n<ul>\n \t<li>Let the customer vent</li>\n \t<li>Avoid getting trapped in a negative filter *</li>\n \t<li>Express empathy to the customer</li>\n \t<li>Begin active problem solving</li>\n \t<li>Mutually agree on an appropriate course of action</li>\n \t<li>Follow up</li>\n</ul>\n* The friction between you and the customer may be increased by how you interpret his or her behavior. Dealing with difficult customers might cause you to label your customers, call names, or stereotype your customers (not to their face, but privately)-this is how a negative filter is created. Negative filters are contagious; if left unchecked, negative filters can spin out of control, and destroy any possibility of positive communication with the customer. The way out of the negative filter is a service filter. A \"service filter\" is when you ask yourself, <b>\"What does this customer need and how can I provide it?\"</b>\n\nThe question changes your focus (your filter) — from negative personal feelings to a service provider attitude — and highlights the issues that need to be addressed.\n\n<hr />\n\nSuggestions for when a customer becomes belligerent or offensive during a <b>face-to-face</b> situation:\n<ul>\n \t<li>Listen to the customer\'\'s concerns.</li>\n \t<li>Take notes while the customer vents. Then address one issue at a time.</li>\n \t<li>Empathize. Explain issues can be resolved if we remain calm and concentrate on the issues.</li>\n \t<li>Speak calmly, use eye contact, allow customer to vent; use ‘I’ statements (see <b>Top 10 Phrases</b>).</li>\n \t<li>Remain calm and speak in a normal tone of voice.</li>\n \t<li>Treat the customer with respect and honesty. Tell them the facts.</li>\n \t<li>Calm the customer by reassuring the person that you will work to find resolution.</li>\n \t<li>Focus on what you or the customer CAN DO.</li>\n \t<li>Explain the answer in more than one way to help the customer understand.</li>\n \t<li>Give the customer phone numbers of other organizations that might be able to help.</li>\n \t<li>Ask for assistance from lead worker/supervisor. Follow your office\'\'s policy for asking for assistance.</li>\n \t<li>Explain the behavior you expect from the customer (example: If the customer is using profanity, request that the customer stop using profanity).</li>\n \t<li>If the customer is threatening, call the supervisor, advise that CSRU does not take threats lightly, and that you must report threats to the authorities.</li>\n \t<li>When appropriate, call the police.</li>\n \t<li>Use a CODE system for safety and verbal signals. For example:\nIf you ask for the \"green form\" you are asking a co-worker to walk by. If you ask for the \"yellow form\" you are asking a co-worker to come into room. If you ask for a \"red form\" you are asking a co-worker to call 911. (These are examples. Follow your office policy).</li>\n \t<li>If the customer continues to act irate, terminate the visit. Ask the customer to return when he or she is calm. Offer to set up a time to discuss the matter. If they refuse to leave, follow your office\'\'s procedures for contacting the police.</li>\n</ul>\n\n<hr />\n\nSuggestions for when the customer becomes belligerent or offensive during a <b>phone call</b>:\n<ul>\n \t<li>Try to be a good listener and do not interrupt.</li>\n \t<li>Try to get to the bottom of the real issue as quickly as possible.</li>\n \t<li>Take notes on the issues; narrate completely.</li>\n \t<li>Don\'\'t place blame or make excuses.</li>\n \t<li>Try explaining the information in another way.</li>\n \t<li>Find a common ground on something both can agree on ex: the child support order was filed in May ’99.</li>\n \t<li>Try to get the customer back on track.</li>\n \t<li>Ask if the customer would like a minute or two to calm down.</li>\n \t<li>Remain calm in voice and manner, allow the customer to vent, and provide accurate responses. Determine whether the conversation can end positively or whether it\'\'s time to end the call.</li>\n \t<li>If there is no calming the customer, politely indicate you would like to speak with them at a later time when they\'\'ve had a chance to calm down so that you may address their concerns productively.</li>\n \t<li>In situations where the customer has a history of inappropriate behavior (belligerent, offensive, or making false claims about what worker said) be prepared to use the speakerphone. Have another staff person sit in the office and witness the conversation or ask permission from the customer to tape the conversation \'\'for quality assurance purposes\'\'.</li>\n \t<li>Try to speak in calm, low tones. If the caller refuses to heed warnings of terminating the call (based on foul language, repeating same things 4-5 times, etc.), clearly state, \"I am terminating this conversation. Goodbye,\" and hang up.</li>\n \t<li>Ask the supervisor or lead worker to intervene, if needed.</li>\n</ul>\n\n<hr />\n\n<b>The top ten phrases to avoid, and the alternatives</b>\n\n[ninja_tables id=\"1137\"]\n<ul>\n \t<li>Phrases to avoid when attempting to keep the conversation\nfrom escalating</li>\n \t<li>Suggested phrases to use to keep the conversation from escalating</li>\n \t<li>Suggested phrases to use for de-escalating a conversation, when the customer is very upset</li>\n</ul>\n<b>Phrases to <i>avoid</i> when attempting to keep the conversation from escalating</b>\n<ul>\n \t<li>You don’t seem to understand</li>\n \t<li>You are not listening</li>\n \t<li>We can not help you</li>\n \t<li>You did not hear me</li>\n \t<li>Excuses why work is not done</li>\n \t<li>Hey you loser</li>\n \t<li>Why don’t you get a job</li>\n \t<li>Hey, don’t get angry with me, you slept with him</li>\n \t<li>You are wrong</li>\n \t<li>Nothing can be done</li>\n \t<li>It doesn’t matter because</li>\n \t<li>You failed to do this</li>\n \t<li>Laying blame statements</li>\n \t<li>I know how you feel</li>\n \t<li>I can not assist you</li>\n \t<li>You should have done</li>\n \t<li>I don’t think you understand</li>\n \t<li>It’s not my decision</li>\n \t<li>This is not my fault</li>\n \t<li>The computer did it, or the computer didn’t</li>\n \t<li>Sorry there is nothing we can do for you, get a private attorney</li>\n \t<li>It’s our policy</li>\n \t<li>It’s our procedure</li>\n \t<li>But</li>\n \t<li>Never</li>\n \t<li>Always</li>\n \t<li>It was your responsibility</li>\n \t<li>You have to</li>\n \t<li>I have to</li>\n</ul>\n<b>Suggested phrases to use to keep the conversation from <i>escalating</i></b>\n<ul>\n \t<li>I understand</li>\n \t<li>We want to help you</li>\n \t<li>I can’t answer that question, but I will get someone that can</li>\n \t<li>CSRU cannot help, but I will attempt to lead them to another agency/someone who can</li>\n \t<li>I wish I could do more</li>\n \t<li>Let me do some research on this topic to ensure I have looked at every option</li>\n \t<li>I see</li>\n \t<li>Okay</li>\n \t<li>I noted that</li>\n \t<li>I appreciate you taking the time</li>\n \t<li>I can do this</li>\n \t<li>Sorry that happened</li>\n \t<li>I’m glad you came by</li>\n \t<li>Perhaps if I explain the program to you</li>\n \t<li>I will do everything I can to help you</li>\n \t<li>Let’s discuss calmly what can be done</li>\n \t<li>I am here to help anyway I can</li>\n \t<li>I will investigate your concerns</li>\n \t<li>I can imagine how frustrated you must feel</li>\n \t<li>I hear what you are saying</li>\n \t<li>What would you like to see done?</li>\n \t<li>It’s okay to be angry</li>\n \t<li>Thank you for providing this information</li>\n</ul>\n<b>Suggested phrases to use for <i>de-escalating</i> a conversation, when the customer is very upset</b>\n<ul>\n \t<li>We will do everything we can to help</li>\n \t<li>I apologize if you were misled or given incorrect information</li>\n \t<li>I’m not going to be able to help you if you’re this angry. Why don’t you let me see if I can help you/give me chance to help you?</li>\n \t<li>I certainly understand why you’re upset. I will do what is needed to correct the problem asap and contact you about the completed updates</li>\n \t<li>I will investigate your concerns</li>\n \t<li>Let me have some time to review this to make sure I have all the facts</li>\n \t<li>I apologize for any difficulties you have had getting through to us</li>\n \t<li>Ask them to try and calm down so that the issues can be discussed</li>\n \t<li>I understand you are upset</li>\n \t<li>I would like to get your concern taken care of and if something is incorrect on your case I want to correct it</li>\n \t<li>Would you like to speak to the Lead worker/Supervisor?</li>\n</ul>\";i:1584644438772;s:7708:\"Narratives create a written record of a case. In order to have a complete and accurate record it is essential that all case activities be narrated. (Case activities include but are not limited to: Personal contacts, case reviews, process actions, accessing available databases such as PIEX or IABC.) Each time a case is accessed there must be a corresponding narrative that is factual, concise, accurate, and reflects all steps taken. Workers shall clearly narrate what database was accessed, why, and what relationship the party has to the case.\n\nBecause multiple people and offices may work on a case it is vital for workers to make sure narratives can be clearly understood. Narratives should not contain personal opinion. In rare instances, narratives may be subpoenaed and become part of a permanent court record.\n\n<hr />\n\n<b>Types of Narratives</b>\n<ul>\n \t<li>System generated</li>\n \t<li>Worker entered</li>\n \t<li>Worker completed (system and worker)</li>\n</ul>\n\n<hr />\n\n<b>Identification</b>\n<ul>\n \t<li>All narratives will be ended with first initial and full last name of the worker making the entry.</li>\n</ul>\n\n<hr />\n\n<b>Questions to Ask Yourself when Narrating</b>\n<ul>\n \t<li style=\"list-style-type: none;\">\n<ul>\n \t<li>Who are you talking to?</li>\n \t<li>What happened?</li>\n \t<li>On which case(s) does this narrative belong?\n\n<b>Case party has multiple cases</b>\n<ul>\n \t<li>Case parties may have more than one case, and may have different case roles on additional cases. The cases do not cross-reference if the parties role is different.</li>\n \t<li>When narrating information regarding a case party, consider if the information is pertinent to other cases. If so, add the narrative to the other cases.</li>\n \t<li>Narratives may be needed on cases where the party has the same role, and cases where the party does not have the same role.</li>\n \t<li>Examples of information that may need to be included on multiple cases are location and financial information.\n<ul>\n \t<li>Location information should be entered on <b>all</b> cases for the party, for <b>all</b> case roles.</li>\n \t<li>Contact with a NCP, and information provided regarding financial circumstances is information that should be entered on all cases where the case party is an obligor or alleged parent. If the NCP is a CP on another case, the financial information may also be important if there is any establishment or modification action in process.</li>\n \t<li>Use the ADDSUM and EMPSUM screens to identify additional cases needing narratives included. Use the PF6 key to identify cases where the party has another case role.</li>\n</ul>\n</li>\n \t<li>Include the case number where the information originated, or use the ICAR “copy to” function.</li>\n</ul>\n</li>\n</ul>\n</li>\n</ul>\n&nbsp;\n<ul>\n \t<li>What action needs to happen later and who will take these actions?</li>\n \t<li>Will someone reading this narrative 10 years from now understand what action you have taken and why you took that action on the case?</li>\n \t<li>Is the information factual?</li>\n</ul>\n\n<hr />\n\n<b>Tips</b>\n<ul>\n \t<li>ICAR does not have word wrap. Move to the next line to start a word or to start an approved abbreviation/acronym.</li>\n \t<li>Narratives can be subpoenaed for court testimony.</li>\n \t<li>Use the appropriate process code when entering narratives (see Help Text).</li>\n \t<li>Proofread your narratives for grammar, punctuation, and appropriate use of abbreviations/acronyms (i.e. using the correct case party CP, NCP, etc.)\nSee <a><b><i>Abbreviations/Acronyms</i></b></a>.</li>\n \t<li>Timeliness – Narrate as soon as possible after a call, a face-to-face meeting, completion of a referral, or when mail/fax is received.</li>\n \t<li>Use the existing ICAR narration macros. Standardized narratives allow staff to easily find special narratives.</li>\n \t<li>Do not criticize another worker or office in your narrative. For example, do not use your narrative to address training issues or possible worker errors (i.e. missed calendar flags – refer to the flag, not to the fact it was missed).</li>\n \t<li>Corrections to narratives can only occur during the same business day as entered.</li>\n</ul>\n\n<hr />\n\n<b>Appropriate Narration</b>\n\nThe right things to narrate:\n<ul>\n \t<li>When dealing with a customer who is verbally abusive, irate, or threatening, make sure to narrate exactly what you said. This practice will prevent misunderstandings in the future should that customer call back or file a complaint on the way the matter was handled.</li>\n \t<li>Threats: Narrate the time of the call or face-to-face meeting and specifically what the person said using quotation marks for direct quotations.</li>\n \t<li>Use only approved <a><b><i>Abbreviations/Acronyms</i></b></a>.</li>\n \t<li>Include specific dates or dollar amounts in your narratives.</li>\n \t<li>If a caller requests a callback, narrate their phone number and best time for callback.</li>\n \t<li>With out-of-state workers, narrate their name, state, phone number, and fax number.</li>\n \t<li>If a hearing is scheduled, be specific as to the type, time, and date of the hearing.</li>\n \t<li>When referring for employer verification, narrate the name, location, and phone number (if available) of the employer to be contacted.</li>\n \t<li>If a customer has an attorney, narrate name, address, phone number, and fax number of the attorney.</li>\n \t<li>When requesting an affidavit for a lost warrant or requesting a copy of a redeemed warrant, narrate the warrant number, amount, mailing date, and other information from the WARRANT DETAIL screen. If you have access to OUTS, include the information from that system, also.</li>\n \t<li>If you discuss more than one case with a customer, narrate the relevant information on each of the cases.</li>\n \t<li>If you provide a customer with information from an earlier narrative, narrate the date of the narrative and the information you provided.</li>\n \t<li>When discussing PIEX or DLIC, etc., for current spouse of a case party, narrate system access and why.</li>\n</ul>\nThings you do not narrate:\n<ul>\n \t<li>Do not narrate unfavorable impressions of the customer. It is fine to say someone is frustrated, upset, confused, using foul language, etc. However, refrain from making inappropriate personal comments regarding the customer.</li>\n \t<li>Do not narrate specific criticisms of a worker or representative. For example, rather than describing what a worker did incorrectly, state that the customer has customer service concerns.</li>\n \t<li>Do not narrate agency barriers, such as backlogged in work, short staffed, or staff vacancies.</li>\n \t<li>Even in the event of a threat, it is not necessary to narrate specific profane comments.</li>\n</ul>\nA good narrative can make your job easier. It can also eliminate extra work.\n\n<hr />\n\n<b>Special Characters</b>\n\nSpecial characters affect not only the COMMENTS section of all screens which have a COMMENTS section, but also the narratives which are entered on cases.\n\n<b>Narratives and Comments</b>\n\nWhen entering narratives and \"Comments\" on the NARRCASE screen (as well as other screens), please <b>DO NOT USE</b> any special characters, whether it\'\'s at the beginning, end or a part of the comment. Why? We have programs which use these comments for reports and when there is a special character included, the program ceases to run, causing problems for many of us.\n\nThe special characters that you <b>SHOULD NOT</b> use are ~ % ^ * &lt; &gt;\n\nThe @ and $ can be used, but not at the beginning of a sentence.\n\n<b>Addresses</b>\n\nYou may still use the % in place of c/o in addresses.\";i:1584644439019;s:17962:\"<b>What is an internal customer?</b>\n\nInternal customers are people who work with you inside your agency and rely on you for the services, products and information that they need to get their job done. They are not traditional customers, but they need the same caring attention that you provide to your external customers.\n\nThe customer service provider working at CSRU needs to remember that 66 percent of all costs for the services provided by CSRU are paid by the federal government (with few exceptions) and 34 percent is matched by the state. Thus various institutions, including the Governor’s office, Legislature (senators and representatives), DHS Director’s office, other state child support agencies – to name just a few – make up the portrait of CSRU’s internal customers.\n\nAlthough CSRU is one agency, it is made up of many different offices. This includes 18 field offices across the state, central office, operations, FCRU, CSC and EPICS. We are internal customers to each other and within our own offices.\n\nThe internal customer chain works both ways. Sometimes you are the customer and other times you are the service provider. For example, when a co-worker asks you for a printout or a report, you are the service provider because you are providing the co-worker with what is needed. Five minutes later you may go to the same co-worker and ask for help on a project; now you become the customer.\n\n<hr />\n\n<b>Giving good internal customer service</b>\n\nProviding excellent customer service requires good listening skills, ability to devote your complete attention to the customer, showing interest in what the customer is saying, being consistent in responses and finding the correct answers, and being friendly and compassionate. Whether talking to a customer in the interview room or talking to a co-worker, the rules of customer service remain the same and should be followed at all times.\n\n<hr />\n\n<b>How to deal with the difficult internal customer</b>\n\nBe attentive and your voice calm and quiet. Listen to the internal customer and respond to their concerns. The same respect should be shown to an internal customer as an external customer. Explain what you can and can not address regarding their concerns. Keep the communication on a professional level and address only work issues. Inform them of options they may have and how to proceed with those options if you or someone else can not help them. If actions will be taken by you or directed to someone else, give the internal customer a timeline of when this will happen. (If possible summarize the conversation verbally or with an e-mail.)\n\n<hr />\n\n<b>Internal Customers within the CSRU agency and how communication flows</b>\n<ol>\n \t<li style=\"list-style-type: none;\">\n<ol>\n \t<li><b>From Central Office and Operations to Field Offices</b>\n<ol>\n \t<li><b>Red dots</b> – Red dots are defined as a written communication from a party to a governmental agency that requires a written response from CSRU. These are sent to the operations unit and they then forward to the respective field office for investigation and a written response. Red dots are normally faxed to the office and an e-mail is sent to the case resolution worker that it is coming to insure that it is received. For procedure and processing Red dots see <a href=\"http://intra/csruhandbooks/HANDBOOKS/CaseResolution/Contents/Resources/Collaborative%20Red%20Dot%20Response.doc\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\"><img src=\"https://stcsruportalcli.blob.core.windows.net/csruportalwpcontent/2020/02/word.png\" /> <b>Red Dot Procedure</b></a> in the Case Resolution BPH.</li>\n \t<li><b>Case Inquiries</b> – These are questions on cases that come through central office or operations staff. These are different from red dots, in that they do not always require a written response and are not always received in writing. The field investigates these concerns and cases. Field staff is normally asked to make contact with the customer and report the outcome back to operations staff. This is done by both telephone and e-mail. (Examples: Directors inquires, cases where individuals have contacted Policy or Operations directly, etc.)</li>\n \t<li><b>Policy and procedures</b> – Policies and procedures are sent to the field offices in both paper and electronic form. If sent by electronic form it is sent to the ‘CSRU Policy Distribution’ e-mail list. Supervisors or lead workers then forward these messages to the appropriate staff.</li>\n</ol>\n</li>\n</ol>\n</li>\n</ol>\n&nbsp;\n\n<hr />\n\n<ol>\n \t<li style=\"list-style-type: none;\">\n<ol>\n \t<li><b>From Field Offices to Central Office</b>\n<ol>\n \t<li><b>Red dots</b> - (A written inquiry, not initially received by the local office, that requires a formal written response.) – Field office staff researches Red dots and prepares a written response. The written response is sent to operations electronically. For procedure and processing Red dots see <a href=\"http://intra/csruhandbooks/HANDBOOKS/CaseResolution/Contents/Resources/Collaborative%20Red%20Dot%20Response.doc\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\"><img src=\"https://stcsruportalcli.blob.core.windows.net/csruportalwpcontent/2020/02/word.png\" /> <b>Red Dot Procedure</b></a> in the Case Resolution BPH.</li>\n \t<li><b>Case Inquiries</b> - (Examples include messages from legislators, ombudsman’s representative, Governor’s office, &amp; AG’s office.) - Field staff investigates these case concerns and makes contact with the customer. Field staff then reports back to central office with the resolution. This step can be done by both telephone and e-mail.</li>\n \t<li><b>System Issues or Problems</b> – Field staff report these issues to central office staff. Prior to reporting to central office staff, the field should investigate the potential problem with their lead worker or supervisor.</li>\n \t<li><b>Policy Questions or Clarifications</b> – Field staff may have questions or need clarification from policy staff in central office on any process in child support. These questions are to be researched by field staff first to insure their concern has not already been addressed. Before taking the question to a lead worker or supervisor, research all available resources including CSRU manual, procedural directives, and PIFs. Questions directed to policy staff are to be directed through the supervisor or lead worker only. See the <b>Communication Plan</b> in the <a href=\"file://hoovr3s2/csru.772/cstmwrk/Guidebook/Guidebook\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\"><img src=\"https://stcsruportalcli.blob.core.windows.net/csruportalwpcontent/2020/02/folder.png\" /> <b>Pit Crew Guidebook</b></a>, for the definition of \"Normal Channels\" for submitting questions to policy.</li>\n \t<li><b>Help Desk</b> – Field offices contact the DHS Help Desk (515-281-4694 or 1-800-922-8905) when they have computer issues that can not be resolved by the PC coordinator. Questions or problems for the help desk are to be directed through the PC coordinator or the supervisor. Also see <b>PCC handbook</b>, <a href=\"http://intra/csru/Technical%2520Assistance%2520Contacts/Cover-TechnicalAssistContacts.htm\"><b>Technical Assistance Contacts</b></a> (broken link).</li>\n</ol>\n</li>\n</ol>\n</li>\n</ol>\n&nbsp;\n\n<hr />\n\n<ol>\n \t<li style=\"list-style-type: none;\">\n<ol>\n \t<li><b>Contacts between EPICS &amp; Field Offices</b>\n<ol>\n \t<li><b>EPICS Forms</b> – Should field office staff need copies of the forms sent or received by EPICS, and do not have access to the imaged forms, workers may request copies through their EPICS liaison.</li>\n \t<li><b>Referrals</b>\n<ul>\n \t<li>The initial referral to contact the customer is sent from EPICS to the field office liaison.</li>\n \t<li>If the referral is sent to the wrong field office, the field office liaison will e-mail the referral to the appropriate field office and carbon copy the EPICS contact.</li>\n \t<li>Additional information about referrals can be found in EPICS Protocol document and the <span style=\"color: #ff00ff;\">Referrals</span> chapter of the Customer Service Handbook.</li>\n</ul>\n</li>\n \t<li><b>E-mail Other than Referrals</b> – Each field office has a liaison that works with an EPICS staff member via e-mail with any concerns between EPICS and field offices. E-mail is professional and focuses on case information or questions.</li>\n \t<li><b>Telephone Contacts</b> – If the field office EPICS liaison or worker determines that there is an immediate concern with case information to the client, a telephone contact may be made. Telephone contact is professional and focuses on case information or questions.</li>\n</ol>\n</li>\n</ol>\n</li>\n</ol>\n&nbsp;\n\n<hr />\n\n<ol>\n \t<li style=\"list-style-type: none;\">\n<ol>\n \t<li><b>Contacts between CSC &amp; Field Offices</b>\n<ol>\n \t<li><b>E-mail</b> – All e-mail exchanges should be professional and contain only information pertinent to the case. A separate e-mail should be sent for each case. CSC sends a response to the e-mail within 2 working days. This response may identify the solution or report that additional time is needed. E-mail is professional and not accusatory. NOTE: CSC accounting staff is not available on Mondays due to the demands of payment processing.</li>\n \t<li><b>Telephone Contacts</b> – Contacts between the field office and CSC may be made if the case issue is very involved or time sensitive. Telephone conversations should be professional and contain only information pertinent to the case.</li>\n \t<li><b>Requests for Payment Research</b> – All requests for payment research should be sent to the CSC representative handling the case. (CSC representatives are listed in Child Support Directory with the breakdown of cases they handle.) All requests should contain complete information to allow the representative to research in the least amount of time. CSC representative will respond via e-mail to worker when research is complete and results have been narrated.</li>\n \t<li><b>Faxes</b> – Faxes should be handled as incoming mail unless received as a priority. Indicate priority items by describing any special instructions on the fax’s cover page. The same etiquette should be used in faxes that applies to e-mail.</li>\n</ol>\n</li>\n</ol>\n</li>\n</ol>\n&nbsp;\n\n<hr />\n\n<ol>\n \t<li style=\"list-style-type: none;\">\n<ol>\n \t<li><b>From Field Office to Field Office</b>\n<ol>\n \t<li><b>Legal referrals</b>\n<ul>\n \t<li>Review the checklist to make sure the case meets the criteria for a legal referral and the referral is complete. After reviewing the checklist send the packet to the responding field office with the legal action referral sheet.</li>\n \t<li>For more information see <a href=\"file://hoovr3s2/CSRU.772/Cstmwrk/PITCREWS/Review/PIFs/Resolved%20PIFS%20admod-rev-susp/2001\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\"><img src=\"https://stcsruportalcli.blob.core.windows.net/csruportalwpcontent/2020/02/folder.png\" /> <b>Review PIF REV0601</b></a>, <a href=\"file://hoovr3s2/CSRU.772/Cstmwrk/PITCREWS/Review/PIFs/Resolved%20PIFS%20admod-rev-susp/2001\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\"><img src=\"https://stcsruportalcli.blob.core.windows.net/csruportalwpcontent/2020/02/folder.png\" /> <b>Admod PIF ADM0501</b></a>, and <a href=\"file://hoovr3s2/CSRU.772/CSTMWRK/PITCREWS/LEGAL/Best%20Practices/Final%20Document/4Checklist.doc\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\"><img src=\"https://stcsruportalcli.blob.core.windows.net/csruportalwpcontent/2020/02/folder.png\" /> <b>Contempt BPH checklist</b></a></li>\n \t<li>Responding Field Office sets up skeleton file and refers to attorney/legal for legal action requested</li>\n \t<li>Upon completion of the legal action, update ICAR as appropriate by process (see above links for more information). Send the order obtained to the initiating office.</li>\n</ul>\n</li>\n \t<li><b>Impact of Changes on Related cases</b>\n<ul>\n \t<li>Note: When modifying information on related cases it is important to remember your changes can affect the related case. For example: IWO distribution, caretaker issues, license sanction, and UPPA.</li>\n \t<li>If you make corrections or entries to a related case, the other worker may not be automatically notified. Make the worker on the related case aware of the steps you have taken.</li>\n</ul>\n</li>\n \t<li><b>Relative cases</b> – If an employee is related to someone with a case in his or her office, that case should be transferred to another CSRU office. Contact your office supervisor for the designated office location to which the case should be transferred. See <a href=\"http://dhs.iowa.gov/sites/default/files/9-a.pdf\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\"><img src=\"https://stcsruportalcli.blob.core.windows.net/csruportalwpcontent/2020/02/pdf.png\" /> <b>Chapter 9-A, Confidentiality of Child Support Information</b></a> for additional information.</li>\n \t<li><b>Telephone Contact</b> - Contacts between field offices may be made if the case issue is very involved, if the action needs to be taken quickly, or if further clarification is needed. Telephone conversations should be professional and contain only information pertinent to the case.</li>\n \t<li><b>E-mail</b> – E-mail should be professional and contain only information pertinent to the case. The same etiquette should apply as if you were writing to an external customer.</li>\n \t<li><b>Faxes</b> - Faxes should be handled as incoming mail unless received as a priority. The same etiquette should be used in faxes that applies to e-mail.</li>\n \t<li><b>Sharing of Knowledge</b>\n<ul>\n \t<li>Field Worker to Field Worker – You may need to call upon the knowledge or expertise of other field staff. Make sure that your solutions do not conflict with any written resources that are available to CSRU staff.</li>\n \t<li>Supervisor to Supervisor(s) – If a supervisor is uncertain of how to resolve a case issue for staff, they may ask for input from other supervisors. The second supervisor may consult with specialists in his or her own office for additional information.</li>\n</ul>\n</li>\n</ol>\n</li>\n</ol>\n</li>\n</ol>\n&nbsp;\n\n<hr />\n\n<ol>\n \t<li><b>Within Individual Field Offices</b>\n<ol>\n \t<li><b>In Person Contact</b> – Co-workers should be kind, courteous, and respectful of each other. Address issues so the co-worker can understand the situation or question at hand. Be mindful of body language and facial expressions. If there is an issue that can not be resolved between the two workers, address the issue with a lead worker or supervisor.</li>\n \t<li><b>Telephone/Intercom</b> – Speak clearly and with a smile. When you speak by telephone with a smile it can be heard on the other end. Speak in a professional manner. Be aware other internal and external customers may be able to hear what is being said on the intercom.</li>\n \t<li><b>E-mail</b> - E-mail should be professional and directed to case information or questions. The same etiquette should apply as if you were writing to an external customer. Do not put personal feelings or opinions in e-mails. Do not put e-mail messages in all capital letters as this can be interpreted as aggressive. Make sure you keep a positive tone in the e-mail message.<b>When sending e-mail containing confidential information, you must follow the DHS policy regarding confidential e-mail information.</b>\n\nYou may send, reply to, or forward confidential information, including client-identifying information, by e-mail. Do not send, reply to, or forward confidential information to anyone who should not get it. Use every precaution to make sure you send the email only to the intended recipients.\n\nAll information relating to clients is considered confidential. DHS is committed to protecting the confidentiality of its clients, and will therefore continue to pursue the highest level of data integrity of all confidential information through the use of reasonable and attainable data security products.\n<ul>\n \t<li>How to send messages containing confidential information:</li>\n</ul>\n&nbsp;\n\nE-Mail messages containing confidential information must include the following at the top of the message:\n\n\"THIS MESSAGE CONTAINS CONFIDENTIAL INFORMATION FOR THE DEPARTMENT OF HUMAN SERVICES. UNAUTHORIZED USE OR DISCLOSURE IS PROHIBITED.\"\n\n<b>Only use this statement when your email does contain confidential information.</b></li>\n \t<li><b>Sharing of Knowledge</b> – There are many times when a worker may get information or find a better way of doing something with child support processes or cases. Share this information with others in team meetings, with your supervisor and in staff meetings. If there is a question on policy or rules with the information, talk about this with your supervisor, lead worker, or attorney, after reviewing all accessible resources. This information should also be shared with the PIT Crew for that particular process. We are all working to better the child support program, to meet our Balanced Score Card Goals, and to improve customer service. This improvement happens by sharing our knowledge with each other.</li>\n \t<li><b>Passing of case files and written notations</b> – There are many times that cases will need to go from one worker to another in the office. This transfer may be for additional casework or review of case information. Make sure it is clearly noted in narratives or in a written note as to what needs to be done. Use your office policy to document where the case file is located; this might be narratives, or worker number notation. If you have a written notation on the case, make sure it is secure so that it does not become lost or fall off. Please see that the file is in order, and all documents tacked down before passing to another worker. Everyone needs to work together to make sure things are not missed and everything is accomplished on the case to better serve our customers.</li>\n</ol>\n</li>\n</ol>\";i:1584644439315;s:3041:\"As the dynamics of our population change, so must the application of good customer service. Excellent customer service means developing an awareness and a response to the special needs of Iowans.\n\nA special needs customer has a condition that requires special accommodations. Be aware of any barriers within your office that could affect a person with special needs. Exercise sensitivity and plan ahead if you know a special needs person is coming into the office.\n\n<hr />\n\n<b>Non-English Speaking</b>\n\nNon-native English speakers and people who cite English as their second language constitute an increasing percentage of the population. Language barriers and cultural differences can present a challenge to the customer and the customer service provider. The following tips may help to promote understanding and increase communication.\n\nHints for dealing with people who have English as a second language:\n<ul>\n \t<li>Avoid \"bureau speak\"</li>\n \t<li>Avoid speaking loudly -- just speak clearly</li>\n \t<li>Speak at a reasonable pace</li>\n \t<li>Refrain from using metaphors, figures of speech and slang (i.e., \"My hands are tied\")</li>\n \t<li>Keep in mind the cultural differences in communication\n<ul>\n \t<li>The space between you and the person to whom you are speaking</li>\n \t<li>Eye contact</li>\n \t<li>Body language</li>\n</ul>\n</li>\n \t<li>If possible, locate organizations within your community that provide translation services.</li>\n</ul>\n&nbsp;\n\n<hr />\n\n<b>ILLITERACY</b>\n\nSome individuals struggle with reading and writing. Good customer service means being aware, being nonjudgmental, and providing clear and thorough explanations. A verbal account of written information aids a customer’s understanding (i.e., explaining a form and its implications prior to asking a customer to sign it).\n\nIf you read a form to someone who cannot read, narrate in detail each section of the form you read to the customer. This is to protect you from having the customer come back at a later date and say you did not tell them something that was in the form.\n\nIf a customer claims an inability to submit a written request (as required by CSRU procedures), suggest that the request be written by someone else and signed by the customer.\n\nIf a customer lacks the skills or physical ability to sign a document, please consult your office\'\'s attorney for the procedures you must follow.\n\n<hr />\n\n<b>ADDITIONAL INFORMATION</b>\n\nPhone numbers for hearing/voice impaired:\n\n<b>Iowa Relay</b>\n(800)735-2942 for hearing impaired\n(800)735-2943 for voice impaired\n\nInstructions for use:\n<ul>\n \t<li>Dial the number.</li>\n \t<li>Give the agent the number you would like to call He/she will stay on line to relay the conversation</li>\n \t<li>Talk directly with the person you are calling</li>\n</ul>\nThis is totally confidential. There is no cost for local calls. Long distance calls will be billed accordingly. A 24 hour service.\n\n<b>TTY</b> (Telecommunications for the hearing impaired/voice)\n(800) 223-3131\";i:1584644439603;s:5171:\"<b style=\"text-align: center;\">November 2010</b>\n\nThis page is primarily addressing ROIs related to complaints received from customers.\n\n<hr />\n\n<b>New Procedures for ROI information on the PRCONTAC/PECONTAC screen</b>\n\nThis is a follow up training note for the PRCONTAC/PECONTAC screen. We have developed a standard procedure on how to enter ROI information onto the PRCONTAC/PECONTAC screen to avoid a possible <b><u>breach</u></b>. The following are the best practice steps for ROI information. Following these steps insures that every case for that person with the same social security number and date of birth will share all the exact same ROI information.\n<ol>\n \t<li>Enter an \"R\" in the TYPE field on the PRCONTAC/PECONTAC screen on the same line as the ROI phone number.</li>\n \t<li>Enter the first name of the ROI in the INFO field on the PRCONTAC/PECONTAC screen on the same line as the ROI phone number.</li>\n \t<li>Enter the complete name of the ROI <b>and</b> the case number(s) that the ROI may be contacted in the PRCONTAC/PECONTAC screen\'\'s COMMENTS field. If the ROI is relative, stating the relationship in the COMMENTS field is appropriate.</li>\n</ol>\n<b>NOTE:</b> The person may only have one case now. However when a new case is added to ICAR for that person, the existing contact information will be immediately shared with the new case. The ROI may only be valid for the original case.\n\n<hr />\n\n<b>Ombudsman’s Office and Governor’s Office:</b>\n\n<b>Do not</b> need a ROI from case parties to obtain information about cases.\n\n<b>Legislators (both federal and state):</b>\n\n<b>Do</b> need a ROI from case parties to obtain information about cases.\n\n<b>Federal legislators</b> - usually already have written ROIs when we receive a complaint (included with the complaint). However, in some circumstances the person who contacted the legislator gave authorization to give information to the legislator, (example, grandparent wrote to legislator) but the grandparent does not have a ROI for the case.\n\nIn this situation, contact the case party the complaint is connected to (example - if payee’s mother wrote, contact payee) and discuss the concerns with the case party. Let the case party know we don’t have a ROI for the person who wrote, and ask the case party if we can release information to the person who made the complaint. If the case party says yes, tell the case party how to get a signed ROI to you quickly. If a ROI is received, contact the writer of the complaint as usual.\n\nIf a ROI is not received by the time you need to draft the written response, contact the letter writer and explain that you have spoken to the case party about the letter writer’s concerns, but you are not authorized to share confidential information with the letter writer. If providing general program information would be helpful and provide clarification, discuss processes in a generic sense with the letter writer.\n\n<b>Example 1</b> – Payor’s mother sends in a case concern to her senator with no ROI. Payor’s mother complains that payments have been made on time each week and we need to stop harassing the payor with threats about what we will do if the payor doesn’t make payments.\n\nPayor’s mother signs ROI to the senator but there is no ROI from the payor or payee noted on the case for the payor’s mother.\n\nCall the payor and tell him you are calling because his mother has written to the senator. Talk to the payor about his payment record and ask the payor if he has questions or concerns about any of the actions we are taking.\n\nExplain to the payor that we cannot share information with his mother unless he signs a release for us to do so. Tell the payor we also will not share information with the senator without the payor signing a release. If the payor says he does not want either party to have a release, proceed as follows:\n\nCall the payor’s mother and tell her you have talked to the payor about his child support case in response to the mother’s letter to the senator. However, explain that you cannot discuss details with the mother because she isn’t authorized by the payor to get confidential information about the case.\n\nWrite a letter containing similar information to the senator.\n\n<b>Example 2</b> – Payor’s mother writes to a legislator with no ROI. The mother complains that payments have been made on time each week and we are trying to take the payor’s driver’s license. Contact the payor and discuss LISAN. Ask the payor if she wants her mother or the legislator to be given confidential information. If the the payor says no, call her mother and discuss general program information about the License Sanction process, but do not give the mother information about the payor’s situation.\n\nWrite a letter containing similar information to the legislator.\n\nState legislators often do not have ROIs. When contacting the case party, ask the case party if you can release information to the legislator about the case. If the case party says yes, request a written ROI. However, respond to the state legislator based on the verbal ROI from the customer.\";i:1584644439883;s:646:\"<p>All staff who accepts payments at the customer window will review CASESTAT for open LISAN or Contempt screen. Appropriate/assigned worker (if different than person receiving payment) is notified. That worker is expected to review narratives and refer to EPICS/LISAN if a noncompliance has been issued, or to legal if contempt and legal has requested notification.</p>\n<p>When completing a Case Review, CASESTAT is to be checked for open LISAN and Contempt screens and narratives will be reviewed to determine if referral to EPICS/LISAN needed as noncompliance has been issued, or to legal if contempt and legal has requested notification.</p>\";i:1584644440188;s:6929:\"<p><b>Guidance for CSRU administrative staff - October 2010</b></p>\n\n<hr />\n\n<p><b>Note:</b> This document is for non-attorney staff only. CSRU attorneys have a separate set of professional standards to adhere to when a customer is (or may be) represented by legal counsel.</p>\n<p><b>Overview:</b> If an attorney represents a customer regarding child support matters, communication with CSRU about some issues must occur only with the customer’s attorney, who will then communicate with their client. The following guidance is intended to help non-attorney staff know when it is okay to communicate directly with the customer and how to do so appropriately.</p>\n<p>Sometimes customers have an attorney on retainer, or use a particular attorney when legal services are needed. In this situation a customer might make reference to “their attorney” but might not mean the attorney is representing them right now for a CSRU related issue. Asking a customer if they have hired an attorney to represent them for a specific child support process will help clarify the attorney-client relationship and help you determine whether you can discuss case specifics directly with the customer.</p>\n\n<ol>\n<li><p><b>If you know the customer is represented</b>, do your best to determine what areas related to child support the attorney is handling for the customer. If you are asked questions about these topics, refer the customer to their attorney to have their questions answered.</p>\n<p><b>You are still able to assist customers with their case if it is not directly related to topics for which they are represented by an attorney. (example – a customer is represented for Review but they have questions about their IWO).</b></p>\n<p><b>Example 1:</b> The payor is involved in a contempt action with CSRU and the payor is represented. The payor calls their caseworker and says they want to fax pay-stubs to the field office to show their employer has started withholding, although payments will not be received prior to the court hearing.</p>\n<p>The payor is scheduled for a contempt hearing tomorrow and their attorney is out of town today.</p>\n<p>The payor wants their caseworker to call them to acknowledge the fax has been received.</p>\n<p><b>What should CSRU do?</b> Provide the customer with the office fax number, and then call the customer to let them know when the pay-stubs have been received.</p>\n<p><b>What should CSRU <i>NOT</i> do?</b> Explain to the customer what impact (if any) the pay-stubs may have on the outcome of the hearing.</p>\n<p><b>Example 2:</b> A new case is opened and CSRU is in the process of establishing an obligation against an alleged father. The AF is represented by an attorney for the establishment process. CSRU receives a request for genetic testing.</p>\n<p><b>What should CSRU do?</b> Make a CEC contact to the customer to explain that CSRU will be in communication with his attorney because he is represented, which includes sending all forms related to this particular process to the attorney exclusively. Then send the response to the request for GT to the attorney.</p>\n<p><b>What should CSRU <i>NOT</i> do?</b> Discuss the genetic testing request with the customer directly, as he is represented for this process.</p>\n<p><b>Note:</b> Do not assume a private attorney will be knowledgeable about CSRU’s procedures and expect the attorney to explain to the AF that CSRU will send all forms and other correspondence to the attorney instead of sending to the customer directly.</p></li>\n<li><p><b>How do I know for sure the customer is represented?</b> This is a determination driven by the customer. In general, if a customer says they are not represented, assume they are not. If the customer states they are represented, assume they are and discuss topics accordingly.</p>\n<p>If you have recent documentation indicating they are represented (such as narration or the ATTORNEY screen shows they are represented) assume the customer is represented unless the customer tells you differently.</p>\n<p>If a customer says they are not represented, but documentation in the case and on ICAR shows differently, ask the customer for clarification. Always narrate clearly if a customer tells you they are <b>not represented</b> when that conflicts with recent narratives, ICAR screens, or other direct information you have. This narration will support why you talked to the customer about topics you otherwise would not if they had an attorney. Also, ask the customer to provide a written statement saying they are no longer retaining an attorney for child support matters. It is not required that the customer provide the written statement, but still ask them to do so. Narrate that you made this request.</p></li>\n<li><p><b>What do I do if a customer does not have an attorney and they ask questions about legal processes, forms or other questions that have to do with the court or a legal action?</b></p>\n<p>Giving legal advice - While it is very important not to say anything to a customer that could be construed as legal advice, providing appropriate information about a process is good customer service. It can be difficult to determine the fine line between the two. In general, advice is giving a person direction on what they should or shouldn’t do. Information is based on facts and not opinion.</p>\n<p>Example – A payee asks if he/she should attend the court hearing on a contested Review action.</p>\n<p><b>What could CSRU staff say?</b> It is not <i>required</i> that you attend the hearing. Important decisions are made at those hearings, but you must decide for yourself if you are going to attend. If I talked to you about whether you should go, I would be giving you legal advice.</p>\n<p>The first 2 sentences provide factual information and are not giving advice.</p>\n<p><b>What CSRU staff should not say?</b> – You are not required to attend the hearing, but I suggest you go because important decisions are made at those hearings.</p>\n<p>Example – An alleged father has hired an attorney to represent him for the establishment process. The payee asks if she needs to hire an attorney.</p>\n<p><b>What could CSRU staff say?</b> It is not required that you hire an attorney. I will provide you information regarding the steps CSRU will take, the timeframes involved and what rights you have to contest an action or object to an outcome. You must make the decision as to whether you want to hire an attorney to advise you.</p>\n<p><b>What CSRU staff should not say?</b> – You are not required to hire an attorney. However, if he has one, I would hire one too if I was you.</p></li>\n</ol>\n<p>The information summarized above will not fit every situation you encounter exactly. However, it will serve as a model to help determine the most appropriate course to take when confronted with questions about how to communicate with customers.</p>\";i:1584644528397;s:9725:\"<b>Contact Notations</b>\n\nContact notations are written records of <b>all</b> official business contacts with CSRU staff from legislators and their staff, Governor’s office staff, Ombudsman’s office staff, media (newspapers, radio, TV), legislative and governor’s office staff from other states, federal officials and congressional staff. (Contact notations do not need to be done in response to red dots). In addition, any other highly unusual contact with CSRU staff should be reported on a contact notation if it is believed that there may be significant repercussions from the contact.\n\nThese contact notations provide the Bureau Chief with a broad overview of customer concerns, including watching for trends in concerns statewide. These contact notations could lead to potential policy and process improvements.\n\nAs soon as possible, write the contact notation as a note in Outlook. The <b>Subject</b> is: <i>Contact Notation</i>. Address it to the distribution list found in the Outlook address book: <b>CSRU/CSRU Contact Notation</b> and copy your supervisor and regional administrator.\n\nHere is the format for the contact notation: The section below is written as if the contact will always be a call. In many instances it could be a response to an email.\n<ul>\n \t<li>Subject: Contact Notation</li>\n \t<li>First paragraph should indicate the name of contact, phone number and other identifying information about the caller, the date and time of the call</li>\n \t<li>Second paragraph should summarize the questions posed or issues raised by the caller</li>\n \t<li>Third paragraph should summarize the response provided</li>\n</ul>\nFinal paragraph should summarize, if needed, the follow-up actions and time frames needed to more fully address the questions or issues posed by the caller.\n\n<hr />\n\n<a href=\"http://dhssp/manual/subsite/Chapter4Reference/Iowa_Counties_and_Office_Info.xlsx\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\"><img src=\"https://stcsruportalcli.blob.core.windows.net/csruportalwpcontent/2020/02/excel.png\" /> <b>CSRU Telephone Directory</b></a>\n\n<hr />\n\n<a href=\"https://secureapp.dhs.state.ia.us/customerweb/offices\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\"><b>County DHS Field offices addresses</b></a>\n\n<hr />\n\n<b>Interpreters</b>\n\n<b>CTS LanguageLink</b>\n<ul>\n \t<li><a href=\"http://intra/csruhandbooks/HANDBOOKS/CustomerService/Contents/Resources/CTS%20LanguageLink/Instructions%20for%20Using%20CTS.doc\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\"><img src=\"https://stcsruportalcli.blob.core.windows.net/csruportalwpcontent/2020/02/word.png\" /> <b>Instructions for using CTS LanguageLink, and office account numbers</b></a></li>\n \t<li><a href=\"http://intra/csruhandbooks/HANDBOOKS/CustomerService/Contents/Resources/CTS%20LanguageLink/Point%20to%20Your%20Language%20Poster.pdf\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\"><img src=\"https://stcsruportalcli.blob.core.windows.net/csruportalwpcontent/2020/02/pdf.png\" /> <b>Point to Your Language poster</b></a></li>\n \t<li><a href=\"http://intra/csruhandbooks/HANDBOOKS/CustomerService/Contents/Resources/CTS%20LanguageLink/CTS%20Tips%20&amp;%20Advice%20on%20Working%20With%20an%20Interpreter.pdf\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\"><img src=\"https://stcsruportalcli.blob.core.windows.net/csruportalwpcontent/2020/02/pdf.png\" /> <b>CTS Tips &amp; Advice on Working with Interpreters</b></a></li>\n</ul>\n<b>Telephone Language Translation and Sign Language Interpretation Services</b>\n\n<b>Telephone Language Translation Services</b>\n\n<b>Note:</b> CTS LanguageLink is the <b>only</b> authorized provider of telephone language interpretation services that you may use. <b>Effective 12/30/13, you may no longer use the AT&amp;T Language Line.</b>\n\nCTS LanguageLink provides both inbound and outbound calls requiring an interpreter. Following are instructions for using CTS\'\'s services. There are separate CTS accounts for each region, as well as for CSC and Central Office. <i>Please read and follow the instructions carefully to ensure proper billing of the calls</i>.\n\n<hr />\n\n<b>How to Use the CTS Interactive Voice Response (IVR) - For Telephone Language Translation</b>\n<ul>\n \t<li style=\"list-style-type: none;\">\n<ul>\n \t<li><b>Step 1:</b> Call 1 888-338-7394</li>\n \t<li><b>Step 2:</b> Enter Account Number, followed by # sign</li>\n \t<li><b>Step 3:</b> Select 1 to be connected directly to your Spanish interpreter, or\nSelect 2 to be connected directly to your Russian Interpreter, or\nSelect 9 for all other languages</li>\n \t<li><b>Step 4:</b> Enter your 10-Digit Phone Number, followed by # sign</li>\n</ul>\n</li>\n</ul>\n* If you require a 3rd party call, press 9 to reach a Customer Service Representative\n\n<hr />\n\n<b>IVR FAQs</b>\n\n<b>What if I do not know my Account number?</b>\nYou do need this information in order to reach the interpreter directly. If you are unsure of your account number, wait and the system will direct you to a live operator who will look up your account.\n\n<b>What is IVR?</b>\nIVR stands for Interactive Voice Response. CTS LanguageLink\'\'s IVR system allows a customer to quickly select the language desired for interpretation and be connected immediately to an interpreter without interaction with a live attendant. The benefit of this is an even faster connect time to your interpreter and better service to your limited English proficient (LEP) client.\n\n<b>What is a third party call?</b>\nA third party call is when you need CTS LanguageLink to call the LEP client and then bridge the call together with you and the interpreter.\n\n<b>How do I make a third party call with CTS LanguageLink?</b>\nIf you need a third party call, <b>press 9</b> (<i>even for Spanish</i>) to reach a Customer Service Representative (CSR) and let the operator know you need a third party call. We are happy to assist you with this at no additional charge. Our <i>interpreters are not able to make the third party call</i> directly.\n\n<b>I need another language other than the ones listed. How do I get my interpreter on the line?</b>\n<b>Press 9</b> for other languages and let the CSR know which language you require and they will connect you. If the language is unknown, you may reference the Point to your Language visual for help with most requested languages or ask a representative for assistance.\n\nContact Quality Assurance Team if you have any further questions:\nEmail: <a href=\"mailto:qualityassurance@ctslanguagelink.com\" target=\"_blank:\"><b>qualityassurance@ctslanguagelink.com</b></a>\nToll Free: 1 (866) 610-1338\n\nTo ensure proper billing, it is important to identify your office location by entering the <b>Account Number</b> as follows:\n<ul>\n \t<li>CSRU - Western Region\nAcct #: 10066</li>\n \t<li>CSRU - Central Region\nAcct #: 10062</li>\n \t<li>CSRU - Des Moines Region\nAcct #: 10064</li>\n \t<li>CSRU - Eastern Region\nAcct #: 10065</li>\n \t<li>CSRU - Central Office\nAcct #: 10061</li>\n \t<li>CSRU - Collection Services Center\nAcct #: 10063</li>\n</ul>\nBy also entering your 10-digit telephone number (at the prompt), we can more accurately track individual offices\'\' use of CTS and more easily reconcile invoices.\n\n<hr />\n\n<b>Additional Tools</b>\n\nThis \"Point to Your Language\" poster is helpful if you have a customer in the office who requires translation assistance and you are unable to determine their needed language.\n\nThis \"Tips &amp; Advice\" document provides helpful information in working with an interpreter.\n<ul>\n \t<li><a href=\"http://intra/csruhandbooks/HANDBOOKS/CustomerService/Contents/Resources/Language%20Line/Point%20to%20Your%20Language%20Poster.pdf\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\"><img src=\"https://stcsruportalcli.blob.core.windows.net/csruportalwpcontent/2020/02/pdf.png\" /> <b>Point to Your Language</b></a></li>\n \t<li><a href=\"http://intra/csruhandbooks/HANDBOOKS/CustomerService/Contents/Resources/Language%20Line/CTS%20Tips%20&amp;%20Advice%20on%20Working%20With%20an%20Interpreter.pdf\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\"><img src=\"https://stcsruportalcli.blob.core.windows.net/csruportalwpcontent/2020/02/pdf.png\" /> <b>Tips &amp; Advice</b></a></li>\n</ul>\n\n<hr />\n\n<b>Sign Language Interpretation Services</b>\n\n<a href=\"http://www.deafservices.iowa.gov/interpreting/list-of-interpreters.html\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\"><b>Deaf Services Commission of Iowa\'\'s website</b></a> (broken link) provides detailed information on obtaining sign language interpretation services, including a list of Iowa-licensed interpreters.\n\nTo find a sign language interpreter in your area, do the following:\n<ul>\n \t<li>In the center of the page, under \'\'List of Interpreters in Iowa,\'\' click the link next to \'\'Listed via County\'\' to download the PDF file.</li>\n \t<li>The list is arranged by county #, listed in the first column in numerical order.</li>\n \t<li>Search for the appropriate county # (e.g., 77 for Polk Co.) to find those interpreters in your area.</li>\n \t<li>You may then call one or more interpreters to determine availability and cost.</li>\n</ul>\nNo matter which interpreter you decide to use, all that should be required for payment is a W-9 and invoice from the person. Payment can then be made on a GAX as long as the cost does not exceed $1,000 (if it does, contact the <a href=\"mailto:CSRUContractsTeam@dhs.state.ia.us\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\"><b>Contracts Team</b></a> prior to the services, as a contract will be required). Your AA2 should be able to assist you with the necessary requirements for payment.\n\nIf you have any questions regarding the use of sign language interpretation services please <a href=\"mailto:shase@dhs.state.ia.us\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\"><b>Susan Hase</b></a>, Diversity Manager (515) 281-3095.\";}"
