                        "__cdata": "a:13:{i:1585861793716;s:2710:\"<p><b>Case Management Adhoc Team Members</b></p>\n<ul>\n<li>Wendy Alcorn - Mason City</li>\n<li>Becky Jackovich - Des Moines</li>\n<li>Julie Eipperle - Marshalltown</li>\n<li>Eileen Thompson - Davenport</li>\n<li>Teresa Craft - Creston</li>\n<li>Jody Sutton - Council Bluffs</li>\n<li>Michelle Schwartzhoff - Decorah</li>\n<li>Jennifer Baldwin - Clinton</li>\n<li>Kathy Gove - Council Bluffs</li>\n<li>Amy Wolfe - Burlington</li>\n<li>Rhonda Ruchotzke - Dubuque</li>\n</ul>\n\n<hr />\n\n<p><b>Past Adhoc Members</b></p>\n<ul>\n<li>Jeanette Bower</li>\n<li>Fay Dostart</li>\n<li>Connie Chase</li>\n<li>Paul Sistrunk</li>\n<li>Kris Neubert</li>\n<li>Judy Orth</li>\n<li>Jeanne Burns</li>\n<li>Alinda Babcock</li>\n<li>Renee Hageman-Frana</li>\n</ul>\n\n<hr />\n\n<p><b>Case Management CORE Team Members</b></p>\n<p>Effective 10/01/02, the Case Set-up & Location pitcrews ended and the Case Management Core team was formed.  Membership consists of:</p>\n<p><b>Current PIT Crew members</b></p>\n<ul>\n<li>Audrey Haverkamp, RPM - Council Bluffs</li>\n<li>Ashley Allen - Davenport</li>\n<li>Sara Nelson - Central Office</li>\n<li>Sandra Christensen - EPICS</li>\n<li>Siri Granberg - Central Office</li>\n<li>Deb Billings - Mason City</li>\n<li>Susan Bennett - Linn County</li>\n<li>Kelli Hulin - Marshalltown</li>\n<li>Diane Forrest - Central Office</li>\n<li>Denise Pfaff - Des Moines</li>\n<li>Tonya Cunningham - Central Office</li>\n<li>Laurie Pierce - Sioux City</li>\n<li>Katie Schutter - Ottumwa</li>\n</ul>\n\n<hr />\n\n<p><b>Former PIT Crew members</b></p>\n\n<ul>\n<li>Jennifer Baldwin</li>\n<li>Sarah Raaymakers</li>\n<li>Patti Walsh</li>\n<li>Dana Massie</li>\n<li>Patti Stephens</li>\n<li>Vickie Durham</li>\n<li>John Heim</li>\n<li>Lynda Novotny</li>\n<li>Janice Payne</li>\n<li>Barb Daniels</li>\n<li>Diane Schoville</li>\n<li>Becky Seyffer</li>\n<li>Brian Laatsch</li>\n<li>Jeana King</li>\n<li>Jennifer Johnson</li>\n<li>Susan Bennett</li>\n<li>Eva Nichol</li>\n<li>Shelly Dirksen</li>\n<li>Rita Fleming</li>\n<li>Barb Smith</li>\n<li>Sarah Gardner</li>\n<li>Holly Upah</li>\n<li>Vicki Thompson</li>\n<li>Kevin Babcock</li>\n<li>Kathleen Gove</li>\n<li>Terry Fritz</li>\n<li>Lori Wray</li>\n<li>Kande Petersen</li>\n<li>Bonnie Stark</li>\n<li>Jared McMurray</li>\n<li>Blaine Cormaney</li>\n<li>Barb Charlson</li>\n<li>Roberta Harden</li>\n<li>Michelle Livermore</li>\n<li>Donna Dralus</li>\n<li>Shelly Meeker</li>\n<li>Karen Havlicek</li>\n<li>Janet Arnold</li>\n<li>Cathy Cordray</li>\n<li>Marie Theisen</li>\n<li>Terri Pollard</li>\n</ul>\n\n<hr />\n\n<p><b>Contributors</b></p>\n<ul>\n<li>Statewide Case Set-Up Staff</li>\n<li>Interstate PIT Crew</li>\n<li>Support Recovery Supervisors</li>\n</ul>\";i:1585861794540;s:16040:\"<h4>AutoLocate Overview</h4>\n<p><b>Legal reference:</b> 45 CFR 303.3(b)(1)</p>\n<p>AutoLocate is the automated program that provides data-matches and locate searches primarily with other governmental departments <b>within the State of Iowa</b>.</p>\n<ul>\n<li>Sources searched on a daily basis: \n<ul>\n<li>Iowa Department of Transportation (IDOT)</li>\n<li>Iowa Workforce Development (IWD or JOBS)</li>\n<li>Iowa Automated Benefit Collections (IABC)</li>\n<li>Iowa Department of Corrections (ICON)</li>\n<li>Iowa Department of Revenue (INTX)</li>\n<li>Public Information Exchange (PIEX)</li>\n<li>Iowa Department of Natural Resources (IDNR)</li>\n</li></ul>\n<li>Sources searched on a monthly basis:\n<ul>\n<li>Public Utilities Matching Program (PUMP)</li>\n</ul></li>\n<br />\n<p>Please note that PUMP has its own unique search criteria that remains separate from the daily AutoLocate functions.</p>\n</ul>\n\n<p>Weekly AutoLocate matching processes use the same basic criteria.  These programs do not match records on ICAR if:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>The case is closed or has been redirected.</li>\n<li>There is ‘Good Cause’ on the case.</li>\n<li>The obligor/obligee is deceased.</li>\n<li>The CASE WORKER ID on the CASE screen is blank.</li>\n<li>The CASE ACCOUNT TYPE is 16 or 17 and the WORKER ID on the CASE screen is ‘AFC’, ‘PLD’, or ‘AAF’.</li>\n<li>The CASE ACCOUNT TYPE is 17 and the WORKER ID begins with the letters ‘CSC’.</li>\n<li>The CASE ACCOUNT TYPE is 17 and the only account type with a balance greater than zero is a 17 account.</li>\n</ul>\n<p>The manual setting for searches on APAUTLOC will not be allowed for a locate person that meets any of the following criteria:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>BYPASS AF field is set to \"Y\" on the LOCATE screen.</li>\n<li>ACTION DISMISSED/PROCESS ENDED field contains the AFEX entry on ADPAT2.</li>\n<li>PROCESS ENDED field is set to \"Y\" on the PATEST3 screen.</li>\n</ul>\n<p>If you attempt to set a manual search on a locate person that meets one of these criteria, a screen message will display of \"No Auto Locate Searches Allowed - Person is Bypassed\" or \"No Auto Locate Searches Allowed - Adpat Action Dismissed - AFEX\".</p>\n<p><b>Note:</b> Case referencing does not apply to the AutoLocate weekly programs.  These programs match each person by social security number only.  Because of this, the program issues appropriate narratives on an individual across roles regardless of whether the person is an payor on one case and an payee on another.</p>\n\n<hr />\n\n<h4>Bureau of Health Statistics (BHS)</h4>\n<p>Also see: <b>Non-automated location sources - <a href=\"?page_id=1261\">Bureau of Health Statistics (BHS)</a>.</b></p>\n\n<p>The Bureau of Health Statistics (BHS) supplies certified copies of birth, death, and marriage certificates, as well as paternity affidavits.</p>\n<p>The Bureau of Health Statistics (BHS), a unit of the Department of Public Health, is responsible for maintaining the official archives of all marriages and deaths that occur in Iowa.  Access to these records is crucial for the Child Support Recovery Unit (CSRU) to carry out its mission.  Federal and state law allows BHS to provide CSRU with necessary information.</p>\n<p>Beginning with BHS records filed on January 1, 1999, BHS sends two files to CSRU towards the end of each month. These files contain information about records the BHS added to their data base the previous month.  ICAR processes these files on the 3rd Friday of the month. By the middle of the next month, the BHS website reflects these files.</p>\n<p><b>Example:</b> If BHS adds a record to their database on February 2nd, ICAR matches with the record at the end of March, and workers can view the record on the BHS website by the middle of April.</p>\n<p>Please refer to <b>Non-Automated Location Sources - <a href=\"?page_id=1261\">Bureau of Health Statistics (BHS)</a></b> for more information about the BHS website.</p>\n<p>The marriage and death files from the Department of Public Health interface with the Iowa Collections and Reporting (ICAR) system to identify matches with child support case participants who are payors, alleged fathers, or payees.  The records in these files contain at least one social security number (SSN).</p>\n<p>If a match is found, ICAR automatically issues a narrative and a calendar flag to alert the CSRU worker to new information.  You can confirm this information on the Vital Statistics Search intranet site.  Please refer to <b>Non-Automated Location Sources - <a href=\"?page_id=1261\">Bureau of Health Statistics</a></b> for more information about the site.</p>\n<p><b>Note:</b> An individual in the case role of child on an ICAR case will <b>not</b> automatically match with BHS marriage and death files.</p>\n<p>Refer to <a href=\"http://dhs.iowa.gov/sites/default/files/10-c.pdf\" target=\"_blank\"><img src=\"https://stcsruportalcli.blob.core.windows.net/csruportalwpcontent/2020/04/pdf.png\"> <b>Paternity by Affidavit, Chapter 10-C</b></a> of the Employee Manual for more information about matches with paternity affidavits and birth certificates—including how to request certified copies.</p>\n\n<p><b>Case Selection Criteria</b></p>\n<p>ICAR updates marriage and death information automatically whenever the Social Security Number on a BHS record matches that of an ICAR case payor, alleged father, or payee.</p>\n<p>ICAR does <b>not</b> update the case if any of the following criteria are met:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>The matched SSN consists of all the same digits (for example: 999-99-9999 or 111-11-1111)</li>\n<li>The STATUS field on the CASE screen is \"C\", \"D\", or \"H\".</li>\n<li>The BYPASS AF? field on the LOCATE screen is \"Y\".</li>\n<li>The case account type is 17 <b>and</b> the CASE WRKR ID field is \"CSC\".</li>\n<li>The case has been redirected.</li>\n<li>The case account type is 17 <b>and</b> the only account balance >0 is type 17.</li>\n<li>The case account type is 17 <b>and</b> no balances exist and the worker ID is not AFC, AAF, or PLD.</li>\n<li>The DECEASED field on the LOCATE screen is \"Y\" <b>and</b> the DATE OF DEATH field is greater than zero.</li>\n<li>The DECEASED field on the PAYOR screen is \"Y\" <b>and</b> the DATE OF DEATH field is greater than zero.</li>\n<li>The ACTION DISMISSED/PROCESS ENDED field on the ADPAT2 screen is \"AFEX\".</li>\n<li>The RESULTS RECEIVED field is >0 <b>and</b> PROBABILITY field = 0 <b>and</b> PATERNITY INDEX field = 0 on the PATEST2 screen.</li>\n<li>The PROCESS ENDED (Y/N) field is \"Y\" on the PATEST3 screen.</li>\n<li>The CASE WRKR ID field is blank.</li>\n<li>There is an \"A\" or \"P\" in the GOOD CAUSE field on the PAYEE screen.</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p><b>Marriage Records</b></p>\n<p>All legal marriages that take place in the state of Iowa are registered with BHS.  If there is a match between a BHS marriage file entry and an ICAR case participant, ICAR issues narrative (LOC 296) and calendar flag (LOC 103) to indicate a possible location source.  The narrative identifies the match by the individual’s name and SSN and informs you that the person has recently been married.</p>\n\n<p><b>Death Records</b></p>\n<p>If there is a match between a BHS death file entry and an ICAR case participant, ICAR will issue narrative LOC 366.  If there is not an existing date of death entry on the LOCATE or PAYEE2 screen, ICAR will issue calendar flag LOC 149.</p>\n<p>The match is made only on an individual’s social security number. Occasionally, the social security number from BHS is for a different person than who it matches with on ICAR.  We display the person’s name provided by BHS in the narrative and calendar flag. If the name is different than the case party’s, it may indicate the death information received is incorrect.  Refer to <a href=\"?page_id=1261\"><b>Reporting Errors In BHS Records</b></a> for more information.</p>\n<p>Effective December 22, 2005, ICAR stopped loading death information to the LOCATE and PAYEE2 screens. This allows you the opportunity to verify the information before ICAR stops enforcement processes and begins the case closure process.</p>\n\n<hr />\n\n<h4>Child Support Enforcement Network (CSENet)</h4>\n<p>CSENet is a national information system that automatically transmits child support enforcement information between states.  You can use CSENet quick locate (LO1) capability to request location information from other states.</p>\n<p>Initiate a quick locate request to the other state when you believe the non-custodial or custodial parent is in another state, have the locate person\'s SSN, but lack sufficient data to work the case. ICAR automatically processes the request and sends it to the other state by CSENet, if possible, or as a paper Locate Data Sheet (470/3475).</p>\n<p>To determine if a quick locate request will issue through CSENet or on paper, check the <a href=\"http://intra/csruhandbooks/HANDBOOKS/Intergovernmental/Contents/Resources/CSENET/CsenetAgreementTable.doc\" target=\"_blank\"><img src=\"https://stcsruportalcli.blob.core.windows.net/csruportalwpcontent/2020/04/word.png\"> <b>CSENet Agreement Tables</b></a> to see if Iowa has a quick locate agreement with other state.</p>\n<p><b>Best Practice TIP:</b></p>\n<p>Workers should set themselves a manual calendar flag 30 days from the date of the initial Quick Locate to check for a response from the other state. If no response in 30 days, reset a calendar flag another 30 days.</p>\n<p>You may also pursue other location activities such as credit check or use other location resources listed in Non-Automated Location Sources in the Location BPH.</p>\n<p>See Response to Quick Locate Request below for information about why a response may not load to ICAR.</p>\n<p><b>Note:</b> If the case is closed or if you make changes in the SSN after the Quick Locate entry is made, the system will not send the Quick Locate. ICAR also will not send the Quick Locate request if the case is a CSC-17 or redirected.</p>\n\n<p><b>Payor/Alleged Father Quick Locate:</b></p>\n<p>You initiate a quick Locate on a payor or alleged father from the LOCATE screen:</p>\n<img src=\"https://stcsruportalcli.blob.core.windows.net/csruportalwpcontent/2020/04/CsnetParentLocate.gif\" />\n<p>To submit a quick locate request on a payor or alleged father, type LOCATE at any next screen prompt. Enter the ICAR case number in the CASE NUMBER field and press PF5. Select the individual you are interested in by pressing PF7 and PF8 to scroll through the names on the LOCATE screen.</p>\n<p>Once the appropriate person is displayed in the LOCATE NAME field, tab to the SPLS/QUICK LOCATE field and enter the appropriate two-letter postal abbreviation for the other state.\n You can enter up to five states at one time. Press PF3 twice to submit the request. ICAR issues narrative (LOC 298) when the request is confirmed.</p>\n<p>For those states that are not CSENet ready, ICAR automatically produces and sends a Locate Data Sheet. If ICAR determines the state is CSENet ready, the request is transmitted electronically. See chapter <a href=\"http://dhs.iowa.gov/sites/default/files/9-j.pdf\" target=\"_blank\"><img src=\"https://stcsruportalcli.blob.core.windows.net/csruportalwpcontent/2020/04/pdf.png\"> <b>9-J, Child Support Enforcement Network</b></a> (CSENet) for detailed information.</p>\n<p><b>Best Practice TIP:</b></p>\n<p>Workers should set themselves a manual calendar flag 30 days from the date of the initial Quick Locate to check for a response from the other state. If no response in 30 days, reset a calendar flag another 30 days.</p>\n<p>You may also pursue other location activities such as credit check or use other location resources listed in Non-Automated Location Sources in the Location BPH.</p>\n<p>See Response to Quick Locate Request for information about why a response may not load to ICAR.</p>\n<p><b>Note:</b> If the case is closed or if you make changes in the SSN after the Quick Locate entry is made, the system will not send the Quick Locate. ICAR also will not send the Quick Locate request if the case is a CSC-17 or redirected.</p>\n\n<p><b>Payee Quick Locate:</b></p>\n<p>Under certain circumstances, undistributed funds for example, you may need to initiate a quick locate on the payee.  Request a quick locate for the payee from the PAYEE2 screen.</p>\n<img src=\"https://stcsruportalcli.blob.core.windows.net/csruportalwpcontent/2020/04/CsenetPayee2.gif\" />\n<p>To submit a quick locate request on the payee, type PAYEE2 at any NEXT SCREEN prompt.  Enter the ICAR case number in the CASE NUMBER field and press PF5.  Tab to the SPLS/QUICK LOC field and enter the appropriate two-letter postal abbreviation for the other state.  Press PF3 twice to submit the request.  Up to five states may be entered here at a time.  ICAR issues narrative (LOC 298) when the request is confirmed.</p>\n<p>For those states that are not CSENet ready, ICAR automatically produces and sends a Locate Data Sheet.  If ICAR determines the state is CSENet ready, the request is transmitted electronically.  See chapter <a href=\"http://dhs.iowa.gov/sites/default/files/9-j.pdf\" target=\"_blank\"><img src=\"https://stcsruportalcli.blob.core.windows.net/csruportalwpcontent/2020/04/pdf.png\"> <b>9-J, CSENet</b></a> for detailed information.</p>\n<p><b>Best Practice TIP:</b> Workers should set themselves a manual calendar flag 30 days from the date of the initial Quick Locate to check for a response from the other state. If no response in 30 days, reset a calendar flag another 30 days.</p>\n<p>You may also pursue other location activities such as credit check or use other location resources listed in Non-Automated Location Sources in the Location BPH.</p>\n<p>See Response to Quick Locate Request for information about why a response may not load to ICAR.</p>\n<p><b>Note:</b> If the case is closed or if you make changes in the SSN after the Quick Locate entry is made, the system will not send the Quick Locate. ICAR also will not send the Quick Locate request if the case is a CSC-17 or redirected.</p>\n\n<p><b>Response to Quick Locate Request:</b></p>\n<p>When another state responds to a quick locate through CSENet, <span style=\"color: red;\">ICAR only processes the information if the other state sends us the CSC case number and the person’s SSN. ICAR discards the information when the case number and SSN do not match the case participant’s information on ICAR</span>.</p>\n<p><b>Caution:</b> The other state may only use the person’s name to search their systems for locate information. Therefore, some states may return information for a person with the same name as the party you are looking for.</p>\n<p>ICAR populates blank demographic fields (i.e. hair color, height, weight, etc.) and issues narrative (LOC 281) informing from which source the information was received.</p>\n<p>Incoming CSENet <span style=\"color: red;\">current</span> address and employment information runs through the normal address and employer processing. Refer to <a href=\"\"><b><i>Worker & System Procedures for Loading and Verifying Addresses & Employers</i></b></a> for more information.</p>\n<p>When loading address or employer information from CSENet, ICAR displays \"CSENET-XX\" in the SOURCE OF ... fields on ADDVER or EMPVER. (The \"XX\" is the two-character abbreviation for the state providing the information.)</p>\n<p>Incoming CSENet “last known” address and employment information is not processed through the normal address and employer processing. Instead, ICAR issues a narrative (LOC 299 or LOC 302) and calendar flag (<a href=\"\"><b><i>LOC 116 or LOC 117</i></b></a>.)  ICAR issues a narrative (LOC 344) when the other state sends a response with information already on ICAR for the case participant.</p>\n<p>ICAR does not process responses to Quick Locate requests when the case is closed or redirected.</p>\n\n<hr />\n\n<h4><a href=\"?page_id=1283\">Expanded Federal Parent Locator Service (FPLS)</a></h4>\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\";i:1585861794914;s:0:\"\";i:1585861795212;s:0:\"\";i:1585861795531;s:0:\"\";i:1585861795819;s:0:\"\";i:1585861796069;s:0:\"\";i:1585861796327;s:0:\"\";i:1585861796570;s:0:\"\";i:1585861796820;s:0:\"\";i:1585861797085;s:0:\"\";i:1585861797326;s:0:\"\";i:1585861797608;s:0:\"\";}"
