                     "meta_value": {
                        "__cdata": "a:18:{i:1585941996957;s:1722:\"<p><b>Legal reference:</b> 45 CFR 303.2, 303.3, 307.10\n§ 454(8) of the Social Security Act\nIowa Code Section 252B</p>\n<p>The Federal Parent Locator Service (FPLS) is a mandated, automated national location network operated by the Office of Child Support Enforcement (OCSE). <span style=\"color: red;\">The information that we receive from the FPLS is protected. For more information on FPLS or other protected sources, see the <a href=\"https://isutrainers.hs.iastate.edu/login/index.php\" target=\"_blank\"><b>annual confidentiality training</b></a>.</span> The Federal Case Registry (FCR) provides match information for particular individuals by comparing various state requests at the national level and funneling information from external sources to the states. The National Directory of New Hires (NDNH) is a database to which State Directories of New Hires (SDNH) report all newly hired employees within their state.  See FPLS Locate Sources below.</p>\n<p>States can query FPLS for information regarding participants of child support cases.  FPLS provides address, employment, asset and SSN information on individuals to assist states in identifying and locating obligors, alleged fathers, and obligees for both IV-D and non-IV-D programs.</p>\n<p><b>Note: This chapter deals only with FPLS requests for IV-D purposes.  For information on FPLS requests for non-IV-D purposes, refer to chapter <a href=\"http://dhs.iowa.gov/sites/default/files/9-a.pdf\" target=\"_blank\"><img src=\"https://stcsruportalcli.blob.core.windows.net/csruportalwpcontent/2020/04/pdf.png\"> 9-A, GENERAL PROGRAM INFORMATION</a>.</b></p>\n<img src=\"https://stcsruportalcli.blob.core.windows.net/csruportalwpcontent/2020/04/FplsFlowchart.gif\" />\n\n\";i:1585941997466;s:86:\"<p><a href=\"https://csruportal.azurewebsites.net/\"><b>FPLS Breach Protocol</b></a></p>\";i:1585941997780;s:3878:\"<p>The expanded FPLS uses external sources to obtain information.  The following government agencies may report important location information:</p>\n<ul>\n<li><b>Social Security Administration (SSA)</b>\n<ul>\n<li>Provides verification of a Social Security Number (SSN) submitted by the State Case Registry (SCR) or OCSE,</li>\n<li>Identifies and provides an SSN if the state submits additional information,</li>\n<li>Identifies and provides multiple SSNs assigned to a person, and</li>\n<li>Makes corrections to an SSN.</li>\n</ul></li>\n<br />\n<p>This information is processed by ICAR.</p>\n<p>The SSA <span style=\"color: red;\">also</span> provides information regarding disability, retirement, or other paid benefits an individual may be receiving. <span style=\"color: red;\">See <a href=\"?page_id=1289\"><b>SVES</b></a> for details about what ICAR does with this information and the LOCDB Screens.</span></p>\n<li><b>Defense Manpower & Data Center (<a href=\"\"><i>DMDC</i></a>)</b>\n<ul>\n<li>Identifies children who are currently enrolled under a military service member’s health plan (TRICARE),</li>\n<li>Identifies children who are no longer enrolled under a military service member’s health plan,</li>\n<li>Identifies children who are eligible for enrollment under a military service member’s health plan, and</li>\n<li>Identifies the case party whose military service qualifies the child for enrollment, or</li>\n<li>Indicates a third party who qualifies the child for enrollment.</li>\n</ul></li>\n<br />\n<p>The DMDC provides this information quarterly for all children on IV-D cases as long as at least one person on the IV-D case has a verified SSN. As with other FPLS sources, the match does not provide any information for any person who has an FVI indicator.</p>\n</ul>\n<p>The following sources only return location information when you or ICAR select the payee, payor or alleged father for AutoLocate. See <a href=\"?page_id=1253\"><b>FPLS Requests</b></a>.</p>\n\n<ul>\n<li><b>Internal Revenue Service (IRS)</b>\n<ul>\n<li>Identifies and provides an SSN through the IRS-U process, and</li>\n<li>Provides home or business address and asset information of the individual.</li>\n</ul>\n<br />\n<p>IRS address information is subject to certain safeguards.</p>\n<ul>\n<li>IRS confidentiality rules require this information remain in a secured environment except when being reviewed or researched.</li>\n<li>IRS information can only be used to verify information from another source. See <a href=\"?page_id=1345\"><b>Address Sources Requiring Special Handling</b></a> for details.</li>\n</ul></li>\n<li><b>Department of Veterans Affairs (DVA)</b>\n<ul>\n<li>Provides an individual’s address, and</li>\n<li>Information pertaining to pension and military reserve status.</li>\n</ul></li>\n<li><b>Federal Bureau of Investigation (FBI)</b>\n<ul>\n<li>Provides an individual’s address,</li>\n<li>Provides employment information, and</li>\n<li>Information pertaining to employment and benefits for the individual if he/she is an employee of the FBI.</li>\n</ul></li>\n<li><b>Department of Defense (DOD)</b>\n<ul>\n<li>Provides an individual’s address,</li>\n<li>Provides employment information, and</li>\n<li>Information pertaining to employment and benefits for the individual if he/she is an employee of the DOD.</li>\n</ul></li>\n<br />\n<p>The DOD includes the Office of Personnel Management (OPM) which provides employment information on Federal employees under the departments of the Legislative, Judicial and Executive branches.</p>\n<li><b>\"Other\" Reporting Federal Agency (OTHER)</b>\n<ul>\n<li>FPLS receives information from other government agencies that have decided to limit access to their databases.  These agencies are not actually queried by FPLS, but specific information may be released by them and added to FPLS.</li>\n</ul></li>\n</ul>\n \n\n\n\";i:1585941998005;s:0:\"\";i:1585941998240;s:896:\"<p>FPLS response information is displayed on the individual’s FPLSSUM screen. Each source may update a specific piece of information on the same FPLSSUM screen. When all queried sources have responded, ICAR displays a \"Y\" in the RESPONSE COMP? field.  If all sources have not returned a response within six months after the request was initiated, ICAR automatically closes the requests and displays a \"Y\" in the RESPONSE COMP? field. This occurs only if there is no verified address or employer on the case. If a verified address or employer has been found, but the response is not complete (an \"N\" in the RESPONSE COMP? field), the FPLS REQUEST field on the LOCATE screen still displays a \"Y\".</p>\n<p>Any future FPLS request causes a new FPLSSUM screen to be created. Each screen is a unique record of a particular request.  All FPLSSUM screens are retained in ICAR and cannot be deleted.</p>\";i:1585941998457;s:1053:\"<p>Prior to submitting an FPLS request, ICAR ensures that neither parent\'s SSN matches the other. This check is necessary to avoid having information on the wrong parent relayed from FPLS.</p>\n<p>If an FPLS request is made and ICAR determines that the SSN of the obligor/alleged father matches the obligee’s SSN, a calendar flag (LOC 79) issues informing the worker to review and correct the SSN information. Once this calendar flag has been issued, the \"Y\" is no longer displayed in the FPLS REQUEST? field on the LOCATE screen. When ICAR ascertains the SSN information has been corrected, the request is sent to FPLS.</p>\n<p><b>Note:</b> Do not enter a false SSN (such as 999-99-9999) in an attempt to \"force\" the system into accepting the FPLS request. System edits prevent the acceptance of specific number sequences, and this results in an invalid request. No information is returned. Furthermore, by entering an SSN that you know to be false, you may actually initiate a request on an individual who is associated with that particular SSN.</p>\";i:1585941998685;s:608:\"<p>When a response is received from FPLS, ICAR again runs a systems check to determine if either parent\'s SSN matches that of the other. If there is a match, the information received is not updated on ICAR. Instead, a narrative (LOC 226) and calendar flag (LOC 80) issue informing the worker of the error. The worker must manually update the appropriate screens.</p>\n<p>When information is returned, an additional calendar flag (LOC 81 if an employer’s address, LOC 82 if the individual’s address) issues. The address provided is loaded onto the corresponding calendar flag for manual worker review.</p>\";i:1585941998920;s:3624:\"<p>The BYPASS AF? function on the LOCATE screen is used when it is necessary to prevent location efforts for a particular alleged father (AF). Placing a bypass on a particular AF excludes him from location efforts through FPLS, as well as updates to ICAR received from FPLS.</p>\n<p>A security class has been assigned to the BYPASS AF? field in order to prevent any unauthorized bypass of an alleged father.  Supervisors must give permission for this field to be updated by making the appropriate entry on the WORKER2 screen.</p>\n<p>It may become necessary to \"bypass\" a location search on a particular AF if he has undergone private genetic testing and has been excluded as a potential father. When this happens it would be appropriate to place a \"bypass\" on this AF via the LOCATE screen. <b>Results from private genetic tests should never be placed on ICAR</b>.</p>\n<p><b>Initiating a Bypass</b></p>\n<ul>\n<li>Access the LOCATE screen on the case for the AF you wish to bypass.</li>\n<li>Tab to the BYPASS AF? field and enter a \"Y.\" Press PF3 twice to update the record. The \"Y\" entry continues to be displayed until the bypass is ended. When a \"Y\" is entered in the BYPASS AF? field narrative (LOC 234) issues.<br />\n<p><img src=\"https://stcsruportalcli.blob.core.windows.net/csruportalwpcontent/2020/04/ParentLocatewBypassAfHighlightedY.gif\" /></p></li>\n</ul>\n<p>A bypass may <b>not</b> be placed on a particular AF when any of the following conditions exist. An online message alerts the worker of the reason the bypass cannot be initiated:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>The DECEASED field on the LOCATE screen is \"Y\" and the DATE OF DEATH field is greater than zero. This online message displays: BYPASS NOT ALLOWED – AF IS DECEASED.</li>\n<li>A payor has been established (\"Y\" in UPDATE PAYOR WITH VERIFIED NAME field on the LOCATE screen). This online message displays: BYPASS NOT ALLOWED – THERE IS AN ESTABLISHED PAYOR.</li>\n<li>There is no established payor, all other AFs on the case have a \"Y\" in the BYPASS AF? field, and you are attempting to bypass the last remaining AF. This online message displays: BYPASS NOT ALLOWED – NO PAYOR EXISTS AND ALL OTHER AF’S BYPASSED.</li>\n</ul>\n<p><b>Note:</b> If all alleged fathers have been excluded and the case is a true \"unknown\", refer to <a href=\"http://dhs.iowa.gov/sites/default/files/9-j.pdf\" target=\"_blank\"><img src=\"https://stcsruportalcli.blob.core.windows.net/csruportalwpcontent/2020/04/pdf.png\"> <b>Title 9, Chapter I, Case Closure</b></a>, <b>EXCL: Alleged Father Excluded</b>.</p>\n<p>When there is a \"Y\" displayed in the BYPASS AF? field, the LOCATE screen for that particular AF cannot be deleted. If you press PF4=DELETE, this online message displays: DELETE NOT ALLOWED – AF IS CURRENTLY BEING BYPASSED FOR LOCATION.</p>\n\n<p><b>Ending a Bypass</b></p>\n<p>A bypass placed on an AF can be ended either automatically or manually when certain criteria are met.</p>\n<p>The system automatically eliminates the bypass when:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>ACTION DISMISSED/PROCESS ENDED field on the ADPAT2 screen is \"AFEX\" <b>or</b> RESULTS RECEIVED field is greater than zero and PROBABILITY field is greater than zero and PATERNITY INDEX field is greater than zero on the PATEST2 screen <b>or</b> PROCESS ENDED (Y/N) field is \"Y\" on the PATEST3 screen.</li>\n<li>A payor is established (\"Y\" in the UPDATE PAYOR WITH VERIFIED NAME field on the LOCATE screen).</li>\n</ul>\n<p>You can also eliminate the bypass by entering an \"N\" in the BYPASS AF? field on the LOCATE screen. The above criteria do <b>not</b> need to be met in order to end the bypass manually.</p>\";i:1585941999169;s:3281:\"<p><span style=\"color: red;\">The Federal Case Registry (FCR) assigns a</span> Family Violence Indicator (FVI) <span style=\"color: red;\">to people</span> when there is reason to believe the disclosure of <span style=\"color: red;\">location</span> information may cause harm to <span style=\"color: red;\">a case participant</span>. An FVI is person, rather than case, specific and is coded on the FCR for the person identified as the victim of family violence. It does <b>not</b> identify the perpetrator. The person must be registered on the FCR in order for an FVI to be activated.</p>\n<p>In Iowa, the release-of-information procedures for an FVI are the same as that for a Disclosure Risk Indicator (DRI). Refer to chapter <a href=\"http://dhs.iowa.gov/sites/default/files/9-a.pdf\" target=\"_blank\"><b>9-A, GENERAL PROGRAM INFORMATION</b></a>.</p>\n\n<p><b>Legal Reference</b></p>\n<p>§453(b)(2) of the Social Security Act</p>\n<p>Disclosure of FPLS information is prohibited if a state determines that it has \"reasonable evidence of domestic violence or child abuse and that disclosure of such information could be harmful to the parent or the child of such a parent.\"</p>\n<p>The definitions of \"domestic violence\" and \"child abuse,\" and the evidence required to support those definitions, vary from state to state. The determination to designate a person as associated with family violence depends upon state law and the procedures developed by that state.</p>\n\n<p><b>Implications of the FVI on FPLS Responses</b></p>\n<p>When an FVI is associated with a person, the FCR returns a code to the requesting state that says disclosure is prohibited because of the presence of an FVI. No additional information is returned. An FVI prevents all matching attempts and the FCR does not process requests to FPLS locate sources. In the event that an SSN is identified or corrected as part of an FPLS request, and the person has an FVI, the SSN is still returned to the requesting state.</p>\n<p> When an FVI is returned on a person, ICAR issues a narrative (CASE 368) and displays <span style=\"color: red;\">the appropriate victim code (CH, PE, P1, AF) in the</span> FVI field on the following screens:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>CASE</li>\n<li>PAYEE</li>\n<li>PAYOR</li>\n<li>NARRCASE</li>\n<li>PAYHIST</li>\n<li>INTERSTA</li>\n<li>ADDVER/CPADDVER</li>\n<li>PAYEMP</li>\n<li>EMPVER/CPEMPVER</li>\n</ul>\n<p>Each of the screens displays the fvi field near the top of the screen. See the CASE screen example:</p>\n<p><img src=\"https://stcsruportalcli.blob.core.windows.net/csruportalwpcontent/2020/04/CaseScreen-FVI.gif\" /></p>\n<p><b>Note:</b> ICAR displays the message \"Case Participant at Risk. PF16-Details.\" at the bottom of the screen, when someone is at risk.</p>\n\n<p><b>Removal of the FVI</b></p>\n<p> States <b>cannot</b> remove an FVI placed on an individual by another state. If more than one state has placed an FVI on the same person, the FCR releases no information until all states remove the FVI. When the FVI is removed by all states, FCR again accepts and processes FPLS requests for that person. ICAR issues a narrative (CASE 371) to inform the worker of the FVI removal. An FVI is set strictly by the FCR and cannot be removed unless an automated update from the FCR does so.</p>\";i:1585941999420;s:1312:\"<p>FPLS responses received on an obligor/alleged father must pass certain criteria before being loaded to ICAR. If any of the following conditions exist, the information is <b>not</b> loaded:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>The STATUS field on the CASE screen is \"C\", \"D\", or \"H\".</li>\n<li>The case has been redirected.</li>\n<li>The CASE WRKR ID field is blank.</li>\n<li>There is an \"A\" or \"P\" in the GOOD CAUSE field on the PAYEE screen.</li>\n<li>The case account type is 17 and the CASE WRKR ID field is \"CSC\".</li>\n<li>The case account type is 17 and the only account balance greater than zero is type 17,</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p><b>or</b></p>\n\n<p>No balances exist and the CASE WRKR ID field is <b>not</b> \"AFC\", \"AAF\", or \"PLD\".</p>\n<ul>\n<li>The DECEASED field on the LOCATE screen is \"Y\" and the DATE OF DEATH field is greater than zero.</li>\n<li>The DECEASED field on the PAYOR screen is \"Y\" and the DATE OF DEATH field is greater than zero.</li>\n<li>The ACTION DISMISSED/PROCESS ENDED field on the ADPAT2 screen is \"AFEX\",</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p><b>or</b></p>\n\n<p>The RESULTS RECEIVED field is greater than zero and the PROBABILITY field is equal to zero, and the PATERNITY INDEX field is equal to zero on the PATEST2 screen,</p>\n\n<p><b>or</b></p>\n\n<p>The PROCESS ENDED (Y/N) field on the PATEST3 screen is \"Y\".</p>\";i:1585941999661;s:602:\"<p>FPLS responses received on an obligee must pass certain criteria before being loaded to ICAR. If any of the following conditions exist, the information is <b>not</b> loaded.</p>\n<ul>\n<li>The STATUS field on the CASE screen is \"C\", \"D\", or \"H\".</li>\n<li>The case has been redirected.</li>\n<li>The CASE WRKR ID field is blank.</li>\n<li>The case account type is 10, 11, 13, 16, or 18.</li>\n<li>The case account type is 16 or 17 and the CASE WRKR ID field is \"AFC\", \"AAF\", or \"PLD\".</li>\n<li>The obligee is deceased (the DATE OF DEATH field on the PAYEE2 screen is greater than zero).</li>\n</ul>\";i:1585941999910;s:5480:\"<p>FPLS may return information on the individual being sought that is neither address nor employer oriented. These responses include general information regarding the location activities being performed by FPLS.  Receipt of this information usually signifies that the case is not being updated on ICAR. The type of response, the source of the information and the corresponding narrative and calendar flag numbers are listed below:</p>\n\n[ninja_tables id=\"1404\"]\n\n<hr />\n\n<p><b>Locate Name Deceased</b></p>\n<p>ICAR processes death information received from FPLS the same as when FCR/SSA Indicates a Case Participant is deceased.</p>\n\n<p><b>FCR/SSA INDICATES A CASE PARTICIPANT IS DECEASED</b></p>\n<p>The following outline walks you through the process ICAR uses to process FCR/SSA information indicating a participant is deceased.</p>\n<ul>\n<li>If there is <b>not</b> a date of death listed on the ICAR case, \n<ol>\n<li>ICAR determines the case role of the participant.\n<ol>\n<li>If the given participant is a child and the child has a bypass reason in the EST BYPASS field other than DEC,\n<ol>\n<li>ICAR issues a calendar flag (<a href=\"\"><b><i>CLOSE 45</i></b></a>) telling the worker the FCR/SSA indicates the person is deceased but a bypass reason is already entered on the CHILD2 screen. The calendar flag recommends entering the FCR/SSA data in the COMMENTS field on the CHILD2 screen.</li>\n</ol></li>\n<li>If the participant is an alleged father, payee, payor, or a child without a bypass reason in the EST BYPASS field on CHILD2,\n<ol>\n<li>ICAR issues a calendar flag <span style=\"color: red;\">(LOC <a href=\"\"><b><i>146</i></b></a>) telling the worker the FCR/SSA indicates the person is deceased</span>.</li>\n<li>ICAR issues a narrative (<span style=\"color: red;\">LOC 364</span>) telling the reader the FCR/SSA indicates the person is deceased.</li>\n</ol></li>\n</ol></li>\n</ol></li>\n<li>If there is a date on the ICAR case, ICAR checks to see if the date the FCR/SSA provided matches the date of death on ICAR. \n<ol>\n<li>If the dates do not match:\n<ol>\n<li>ICAR issues a calendar flag (<span style=\"color: red;\">LOC <a href=\"\"><b><i>147</i></b></a></span>) telling the worker the FCR/SSA indicates the person is deceased, <span style=\"color: red;\">but shows a different date of death than ICAR</span>.</li>\n<li>ICAR also issues a narrative (<span style=\"color: red;\">LOC 364</span>) <span style=\"color: red;\">that shows the date of death and the person\'s last residence provided by the FCR</span>.</li>\n</ol></li>\n<li>If the dates do match:\n<ol>\n<li>ICAR issues a narrative (<span style=\"color: red;\">LOC 364</span>) <span style=\"color: red;\">that shows the date of death and the person\'s last residence provided by the FCR</span>.</li>\n</ol></li>\n</ol></li>\n</ul>\n<p><b>Note:</b> See <a href=\"\"><b><i>Working Location Calendar Flags</i></b></a> for directions on working each of the calendar flags mentioned in these outlines.</p>\n\n<p><b>FCR/SSA INDICATES A CASE PARTICIPANT IS NOT DECEASED</b></p>\n<p>The following outline walks you through the steps ICAR takes to process FCR/SSA information indicating a participant is not deceased. The FCR/SSA sends this information to correct previously sent information which incorrectly identified a case participant as deceased. We only receive these records when the FCR/SSA has erroneously indicated a living person is deceased.</p>\n<ul>\n<li>If there is not a date of death on ICAR and the participant is an alleged father, payee, payor, or a child without a bypass reason in the EST BYPASS field on CHILD2,\n<ol>\n<li>ICAR ignores the FCR/SSA record.</li>\n</ol></li>\n<li>If there is not a date of death on ICAR, the participant is a child, and the child has a bypass reason in the EST BYPASS field other than DEC,\n<ol>\n<li>ICAR also issues a calendar flag (<a href=\"\"><b><i>CLOSE 45</i></b></a>) telling the worker the FCR/SSA indicates the child is not deceased. The calendar flag also tells the worker the child does not have a date of death on ICAR but the child has an unrelated bypass reason on the CHILD2 screen. This calendar flag directs the worker to review the case and remove any data indicating the participant is deceased.</li>\n<li>ICAR also issues a narrative (CLOSE 92) telling the reader the FCR/SSA indicates the child is not deceased. The narrative also tells the reader the child does not have a date of death on ICAR but the child has an unrelated bypass reason on the CHILD2 screen. The narrative tells the reader that the worker will review the case and remove any data indicating the participant is deceased.</li>\n</ol></li>\n<li>If there is a date of death on ICAR for the participant and the participant is an alleged father, payee, payor, or a child without a bypass reason in the EST BYPASS field on CHILD2,\n<ol>\n<li>ICAR issues calendar flag (<span style=\"color: red;\"><a href=\"\"><b><i>LOC 148</i></b></a></span>) telling the worker the given person is not deceased and previously received information indicating the person is deceased is incorrect.</li>\n<li>ICAR issues a narrative (<span style=\"color: red;\">LOC 365</span>) telling the reader the person is not deceased and previously received information indicating the person is deceased is incorrect.</li>\n</ol></li>\n</ul>\n<p><b>Note:</b> See <a href=\"\"><b><i>Working Location Calendar Flags</i></b></a> for directions on working each of the calendar flags mentioned in these outlines.</p>\n\n\";i:1585942000145;s:5434:\"<p>FPLS may return several possible sources for address information of the individual being sought.</p>\n<p>Address information is added and displayed on either the ADDVER screen (obligor/alleged father) or the CPADDVER screen (obligee) when the following criteria are met:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>The information is no more than one year old for a new case.   If the information received is older than one year, a narrative (LOC 254) issues for the obligor/alleged father stating that ICAR was not updated.</li>\n<li>The information is no more than six months old for an ongoing case. If the information received is older than six months, a narrative (LOC 235) issues for either the obligor/alleged father or the obligee stating that ICAR was not updated.</li>\n<li>The address is not a duplicate of information already on ICAR.</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p><b>Foreign and Military Addresses</b></p>\n<p>A foreign or military (APO/FPO) address received through automated searches cannot be updated on ICAR because it is incompatible with the address fields on the ADDVER and CPADDVER screens. Therefore, when a foreign or military address is received, it is listed in a narrative (LOC 259) and is not updated on ICAR. A calendar flag (LOC 93) instructs the worker to reformat the address on ICAR and request verification.</p>\n<p>The ADDVER screen is illustrated below; the field names on the CPADDVER screen are identical.</p>\n<p><img src=\"https://stcsruportalcli.blob.core.windows.net/csruportalwpcontent/2020/04/AddverScreenFPLS.gif\" /></p>\n<p>When a new address is added, the ADDVER or CPADDVER screen also displays the following:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>A return information source code in the SOURCE OF ADDRESS field. These codes are listed below.</li>\n</ul>\n\n[ninja_tables id=\"1406\"]\n\n<p><b>Note:</b> The codes for QW and W4 are followed by a two-digit state abbreviation to indicate the state reporting the information to FPLS. For example, FPLS/QW-KS indicates that Kansas was the state reporting the quarterly wage information to the NDNH.</p>\n<ul>\n<li>The date the information was updated by the responding source in the DATE OF ADDRESS field.</li>\n<li>The date the address was updated on ICAR in the DATE ADDRESS ENTERED field.</li>\n<li>The person’s address in the ADDRESS LINE 1, ADDRESS LINE 2 and CITY/STATE/ZIP fields.</li>\n<li>A \"Y\" in the SEND P.O. LETTER field and the date the batch program ran to send the P.O. letter in the DATE SENT field.</li>\n<li>An \"M\" to denote mailing address in the HOME/MAILING field.</li>\n</ul>\n<p>Use the VEMPLOY screen on ICAR to obtain addresses for the military services. If you know the appropriate military branch, tab to the EMPLOYER NAME field and enter \"US MILITARY\". Press PF5. The EMPLOYER NAME ADDRESS SEARCH screen displays. Select the service you want and press \"Enter\". If you are not certain which military branch should be selected, tab to the EMPLOYER NAME field and enter \"Defense Finance & Acct. Service\". Press PF5 to verify and select as appropriate.</p>\n<p>To locate people employed by a base exchange (BX) or post exchange (PX) on a military installation, the location may be on the <a href=\"?page_id=1407\"><b>Employer Maintenance File</b></a>. If the address is on the Employer Maintenance File, you must choose the correct address from those listed. If the address is not on the Employer Maintenance File, format it correctly and e-mail Central Office to add the address to the employer file. See the Using the FPLSSUM Screen section for additional information.</p>\n\n<p><b>System-Initiated Address Verification Requests</b></p>\n<p>When a new address is added to ICAR from an automated source, form 470-0176, <i>Address information Request</i>, is automatically sent to the USPS to verify the individual’s address. This process is handled through a batch program. A narrative (LOC 30) issues to record the letter was sent.</p>\n<ul>\n<li>Access the appropriate ADDVER (obligor/alleged father) or CPADDVER (obligee) screen.</li>\n<li>If the address is verified as correct by the postmaster, enter a \"Y\" in the ADDRESS VERIFIED field and the date the verification was received in the DATE VERIFIED field.   Press PF3 to update.</li>\n<li>If the address is verified as <b>not</b> correct by the postmaster, enter an \"N\" in the ADDRESS VERIFIED field and the date the verification was received in the DATE VERIFIED field.  Press PF3 to update.</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p><b>New Address on the PAYOR or PAYEE Screen</b></p>\n<p>ICAR adds the new address to the corresponding PAYOR or PAYEE screen if the PAYOR or PAYEE screen previously had no address. If there is an address on the PAYOR or PAYEE screen, ICAR advances the cursor to the UPDATE ADDRESS field and asks if you want to update the address. The on-line message reads: \"Address already exists, enter \"Y\" or \"N\" into update address\".</p>\n<p>If you want to remove the existing address on the PAYOR or PAYEE screen and add the new address, enter a \"Y\" in the UPDATE ADDRESS field. ICAR adds the new address to the PAYOR or PAYEE screen and moves the former address into history on the ADDVER or CPADDVER screen.</p>\n<p>If you do <b>not</b> want to update the address on the PAYOR or PAYEE screen, enter an \"N\" in the UPDATE ADDRESS field. A narrative (LOC 11) for the obligor, or narrative (LOC 176) for the obligee issues for you to record why the address is not being updated.</p>\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\";i:1585942000381;s:0:\"\";i:1585942000623;s:672:\"<p>Group I software is used for reformatting addresses based on U.S. Postal Service (USPS) standards, and contains all current addresses recognized by the USPS for the purpose of mail delivery.  The program is updated on a quarterly basis. Using Group I, ICAR reformats new addresses prior to adding them to cases.</p>\n<p><b>Note:</b> <b>Avoid making changes to addresses that have been added through an automated source.</b> If you make changes to the address, ICAR may not be able to identify it as a \"duplicate\" if received again in the future. The address would then be added again.</p>\n<p>Addresses that cannot be reformatted by Group I are entered as received.</p>\";i:1585942000873;s:944:\"<p>The FEDERAL PARENT LOCATOR SERVICE SUMMARY (FPLSSUM) screen displays information regarding federal employees or federal benefits recipients. Employee information is available if the individual is working for one of the reporting federal agencies. A benefits recipient is an individual who receives income from the federal government (i.e. social security or veteran’s pension).</p>\n<p> FPLSSUM displays information on alleged fathers and payors only. Payees who are the subject of an FPLS request do <b>not</b> have an FPLSSUM screen. Information returned on a payee as the result of an FPLS search is displayed on the <span style=\"color: red;\">appropriate screens, such as</span> CPADDVER <span style=\"color: red;\">or CPEMPVER</span> screens.</p>\n<p><b>Note:</b> FPLSSUM is a \"view only\" screen and cannot be updated other than by automated receipt of information from FPLS.  However, you can enter information in the COMMENT field.</p>\";i:1585942001124;s:0:\"\";i:1585942001372;s:0:\"\";}"
