                     "meta_value": {
                        "__cdata": "a:19:{i:1586284950730;s:1583:\"<p>The Address verification screens act as a holding place for address information during and after the verification process. A worker or ICAR enters an address onto the address verification screens until the address can be verified as \"good\" (the case participant lives at the address) or \"bad\" (the case participant does not live at the address).</p>\n<p>Both the ADDVER and CPADDVER screens allow multiple address entries to be viewed. The most recent address is displayed when you access the screen. Use the PF7 and PF8 keys to scroll additional address information.</p>\n<p>To view a summary of addresses for this individual, press PF12 from an ADDVER screen. The ADDSUM screen displays a shortened form of the addresses. You can also use the ADDSUM screen to view addresses for this person on other, non-cross-referenced cases.</p>\n<p>A worker can request form 470-0176, <i>Address Information Request</i> (also known as P.O. letter, Postmaster Letter, address verification letter, and ADDVER letter) from the ADDVER screen. However, there are only a few circumstances during which it is appropriate to send the address verification letter. For more information, please see Worker-Initiated Address Verification Requests.</p>\n<p>CSRU does not use the address verification letter for payee location efforts.</p>\n<p>To access the Payor Address Verification screen (ADDVER), type \"ADDVER\" in the next screen field of any ICAR screen and press Enter.</p>\n<p><img src=\"https://stcsruportalcli.blob.core.windows.net/csruportalwpcontent/2020/04/AddverMainScreenExample.gif\" /></p>\";i:1586284951039;s:8139:\"<ul>\n<li><b>case number:</b> (Enter case number and press F5 to inquire)<br />\nThe maximum allowable entry in this field is seven digits. ICAR assigns this number to the case. Enter the case number, delete any remaining digits that may be displayed, and press PF5. ICAR displays the case record.</li>\n<li><b>payor/locate name:</b> ICAR displays the alleged father/obligor identified in the locate NAME field of the PARENT LOCATE screen. ICAR allows 16 characters for the last name, 15 characters for the first name, 15 characters for the middle name and 3 characters for the suffix. The suffix is used for information such as Jr., Sr., II and III.</li>\n<li><b>locate ssn:</b> ICAR displays the nine-digit SSN that is associated with the alleged father/obligor.</li>\n<li><b>date address entered:</b> ICAR displays the date in the MM/DD/CCYY format. This is the date ICAR or a worker entered the address information. ICAR automatically updates this field.</li>\n<li><b>autosource:</b> ICAR displays a one character code in this field to indicate what type of source added the address to ICAR. Valid entries for this field are:\n<ul>\n<li><b>Y</b>: ICAR loaded this address from an automated source</li>\n<li><b>N</b>: ICAR did not load this address from an automated source</li>\n<li><b>F</b>: ICAR loaded this incorrectly formatted address from an automated source so the worker copied the address from this ADDVER screen to a new ADDVER screen</li>\n<li><b>C</b>: The worker copied this improperly formatted address loaded by an automated source to a different ADDVER screen and reformatted it</li>\n</ul>\n</li>\n<li><b>source of address:</b> The maximum allowable entry in this field is ten characters. These characters may be letters or numbers. ICAR displays a system generated source of address if found through an automated search. When a previously verified address is deleted from the PAYOR screen, the source of address field is automatically populated with the source code of \"HISTORY\".</li>\n<li><b>rspn state:</b> The maximum allowable entry in this field is two characters. When you receive information from another state in a non automated manner (i.e. paper transmittal), enter that state\'s two letter state code in this field. Entering a state code in this field limits the allowable entries in the source of address field.<br />\nIf the information comes from the other state\'s IV-D agency, enter the other state\'s two letter state code in the rspn state field and enter \'IV-D\' in the source of address field.<br />\nIf the information comes from the other state\'s State Parent Locate Service, enter the other state\'s two letter state code in the rspn state field and enter \'SPLS\' in the source of address field.</li>\n<li><b>date of address:</b> The allowable entry for this field is the date in the MM/DD/CCYY format. This is the date of the address information according to the source. The date in this field may match the date displayed in the date address entered field.</li>\n<li><b>address line 1:</b> The allowable entry for this field is the address information for the alleged father/obligor.</li>\n<li><b>address line 2:</b> The allowable entry for this field is additional address information for the alleged father/obligor. Information displayed here clarifies the information contained in the address line 1 field.</li>\n<li><b>address line 3:</b> This field is not used.</li>\n<li><b>city/state/zip:</b> The allowable entries are the name of the city, the two-letter state postal abbreviation and the zip code in the 5+4 format.</li>\n<li><b>country:</b> The allowable entry in this field is the country where the alleged father/obligor resides if other than the United States.</li>\n<li><b>phone number:</b> The allowable entry in this field is a three-digit area code and seven-digit telephone number. You must make an entry in this field. ICAR does not automatically update this field.</li>\n<li><b>ext:</b> The allowable entry in this field is a four-digit extension for the telephone number.</li>\n<li><b>vrsn:</b> This is the Verification Letter Reason field. The allowable entries in this field are \'GU\', \'SP\', \'CO\', and \'IN\'. These represent the four approved reasons for sending a verification letter through the mail. In order to send the letter, you must enter the appropriate reason code in the vrsn field \n<ul>\n<li>GU: Guidelines</li>\n<li>SP: Service of Process</li>\n<li>CO: Contempt</li>\n<li>IN: Interstate</li>\n</ul></li>\n<li><b>send p.o. letter:</b> The allowable entries in this field are \"Y\", \"N\" or \"R\".\n<ul>\n<li>If the worker enters a \'Y\' in this field, ICAR generates online form 470-0176M, Address Information Request.</li>\n<li>If the worker enters an \'N\' in this field, ICAR does not generate online 470-0176M, Address Information Request.</li>\n<li>If the worker enters an \'R\' over a \'Y\', ICAR regenerates online form 470-0176M, Address Information Request.</li>\n</ul>\nYou must enter a valid reason code in the vrsn field before ICAR allows you to generate the Address Information Request (also known as the ADDVER letter, P.O. letter, and Postmaster Letter).</li>\n<li><b>date sent:</b> ICAR displays a date in the MM/DD/CCYY format. This is the date a worker generated form 470-0176, Address Information Request. For more information, see Sending the Address Verification Letter.</li>\n<li><b>home/mailing:</b> The allowable entry in this field is either \"H\" or \"M\". Enter \"H\" if the address is the alleged father/obligor’s home address (actual residence). Enter \"M\" to represent that the address is the alleged father/obligor’s mailing address. This field determines which address populates the PAYOR screen. The home address populates the home address lines on the PAYOR screen. The mailing address populates the mailing address lines on the PAYOR screen.</li>\n<li><b>address verified:</b> The allowable entry in this field is \"Y\", \"N\" or \"R\". You must have a valid entry in the send p.o. letter field before ICAR allows you to update the address verified field. \n<ul>\n<li>A \"Y\" indicates that the address is verified as valid.</li>\n<li>An \"N\" indicates that the address is verified as not valid.</li>\n<li>An \"R\" indicates new attempts are being made to verify the address and the letter is to be sent again without reentering the information.</li>\n</ul>\nNote: If the update address field on this screen is a \"Y\", this field is protected. To change this field when it is protected, you must access the PAYOR screen and press PF4 to move the address to \"history\". ICAR changes the source of address field on the ADDVER screen to \"history\". This allows you to update the address.</li>\n<li><b>date verified:</b> The allowable entry in this field is the date in the MM/DD/CCYY format. This date represents the date that the address is verified by the post office.</li>\n<li><b>BY:</b> The by field indicates whether a address was verified by a worker or by the system.<br />\nWorkers cannot update this field.<br />\nICAR automatically updates this field when a worker or automated process verifies an address by entering a \"Y\" or \"N\" in the address verified field on an ADDVER or CPADDVER screen.<br />\n<p>Valid entries for this field are:</p>\n<p><b>S:</b> The system verified the address.<br />\n<b>W:</b> A worker verified the address.<br />\n<b>blank:</b> The address is not verified.<br />\n<b>U:</b> The address was verified before the by field was available.</p><br />\nNote: Addresses displaying a \"U\" in the by field may have been verified by a worker or by the system. You can still use narratives to determine how such an address was verified.</li>\n<li><b>interstate referral:</b> The allowable entry is \"Y\". Enter \"Y\" to indicate that the case has been referred to a state other than Iowa.</li>\n<li><b>update address:</b> The allowable entry in this field is either \"Y\" or \"N\". Enter \"Y\" to instruct ICAR to update the address fields on the PAYOR screen with this address. Enter an \"N\" to instruct ICAR that the PAYOR screen should not be updated with this address. This field defaults to \"N\" if the person is not the obligor.</li>\n</ul>\";i:1586284951378;s:2569:\"<p><b>Why Address Fields are Protected</b></p>\n<p>ICAR does not allow you to modify most fields on an address loaded to a case by an automated source. It is important for any address loaded by an automated source to remain on the ADDVER screen exactly as it was originally loaded by that automated source. This is important for two reasons:</p>\n<ol>\n<li>for tracking purposes, and</li>\n<li>so the address does not get loaded to the case again.</li>\n</ol>\n<p>Addresses from automated sources display a \"Y\" in the AUTOSOURCE field.</p>\n\n<p><b>Protected Fields</b></p>\n<p>ICAR protects the following fields for all addresses loaded from automated sources.</p>\n<ul>\n<li>DATE ADDRESS ENTERED - ADDRESS LINE 1</li>\n<li>DATE OF ADDRESS - ADDRESS LINE 2</li>\n<li>AUTO SOURCE - ADDRESS LINE 3</li>\n<li>SOURCE OF ADDRESS\n<span style=\"color: red;\">(Not protected if source is IRS, FPLS/IRS, or History)*</span> - CITY/STATE/ZIP\n<span style=\"color: red;\">(Last 4 digits of ZIP code not protected)**</span></li>\n<li>COUNTRY</li>\n</ul>\n<p>If you need to reformat an address from an automated source, use the F15 copy function. Refer to F15 Copy Function for instructions.</p>\n<p>*ICAR does not protect the SOURCE OF ADDRESS when the source is IRS, FPLS/IRS, or HISTORY because it is inappropriate to verify an address as good when it displays one of these sources.  See Address Sources Requiring Special Handling for more information about IRS and FPLS/IRS addresses.</p>\n<p>**ICAR protects the first five (5) digits of the ZIP code, but does not protect the +4 suffix because the programs that check for duplicate addresses do not use the suffix. You may modify the +4 suffix on addresses from automated sources using the F3 update function.</p>\n\n<p><b>Automated Sources</b></p>\n<p><div class=\"topquicklinks\">\nICER<br />\nICER<br />\nHISTORY*<br />\nUIB MATCH<br />\nWKRCOMP<br />\nICIS<br />\nOFFS<br />\nTPL\n</div>\n<div class=\"topquicklinks\">\nBIRTH CERT<br />\nFACSM<br />\nFACSH<br />\nPATAFF<br />\nIRS<br />\nFPLS/XX<br />\nISFIDM<br />\nMSFIDM\n</div>\n<div class=\"topquicklinks\">\nAUTOLOC+XX<br />\nCSENET<br />\nIPERS<br />\nMFPRS<br />\nHCD-IDRF<br />\nEPICSWEB\n<br /><br /><br /><br />\n</div></p>\n<p>*History is included as an automated source because, when an address from an automated source moves to history, the AUTOSOURCE <span style=\"color: red;\">field does not change and the protected fields remain protected.</span></p>\n<p><b>Note:</b> All addresses moved to history before 11/1/02 are coded as coming from an automated source.</p>\";i:1586284951668;s:2343:\"<p>If an automated source loads an improperly formatted address to the ADDVER screen, <span style=\"color: red;\">correct the format before verifying the address. All addresses from automated sources display a \"Y\" in the AUTOSOURCE field.</span></p>\n<p>If you need to correct one of the protected fields in an address from an automated source, press F15 (Shift & F3) to copy that address to a new ADDVER screen. (Refer to Protected fields on addresses loaded from automated sources for a list of the protected fields.)</p>\n<p>After verifying that an address loaded by an automated source is improperly formatted, press F15 (Shift & F3) to copy that address to a new ADDVER screen. ICAR transfers everything to the new ADDVER screen except for the information in the fields below the PHONE NUMBER/EXTENSION fields. ICAR also enters the current date in the DATE ADDRESS ENTERED field and enters a \"C\' in the AUTOSOURCE field to indicate this is a copied address received from an automated source that was improperly formatted.</p>\n<p>You can now modify the necessary address fields. The following fields are protected from modification:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>DATE ADDRESS ENTERED</li>\n<li>AUTO SOURCE</li>\n<li>SOURCE OF ADDRESS</li>\n<li>DATE OF ADDRESS</li>\n</ul>\n<p>After you reformat the address, press F2 to add the properly formatted address to the case. When you press F2 to add the newly formatted address to the case, ICAR enters an \"N\' and the current date in the ADDRESS VERIFIED and DATE VERIFIED fields on the original ADDVER screen that contains the improperly formatted address. ICAR also changes the \"Y\' in the AUTO SOURCE field to an \"F\' to indicate the address loaded by an automated source was copied for improper formatting.</p>\n<p>ICAR issues a narrative (AVER 15) to record the F15 copy.</p>\n<p>Maintaining the improperly formatted address on the ADDVER screen means that ICAR does not load that address to the case in the future because it identifies the address as a duplicate address.</p>\n<p><b>Note:</b> If the improperly formatted address is verified with \"Y\' and is on the PAYOR screen when you press F15, ICAR displays this edit, \"PF15 not allowed until address deleted from payor screen.\' ICAR requires you to delete the address from the PAYOR screen before copying it to a new ADDVER screen for reformatting.</p>\n\";i:1586284951949;s:1530:\"<p>Per the US Post Office, it is <b>IMPERATIVE</b> that the address be in the correct format.</p>\n<p>There can be a difference between <b>PHYSICAL</b> address and <b>MAILING</b> address. When a customer receives their mail through a post office box, they are <b>REQUIRED</b> to use that as their mailing address. If for business reasons you also require a physical location, use both, placing the PO Box information <b>BELOW</b> the physical information. For example:</p>\n<p>Joe Smith<br />\n109 S 1ST St<br />\nPO BOX 90<br />\nAnytown, IA 50000-0090</p>\n<p>It <b>MUST</b> say \"PO\" in front of the box number; otherwise, automated processing equipment will read the address incorrectly. The mail piece will then be sent to a manual sorting area, causing delay and creating additional cost.</p>\n<ol>\n<li>If the only address information you have is a P.O. box, enter the P.O. box on address line 1. Example:<br />\nJoe Smith<br />\nPO Box 90<br />\nAnytown, IA 50000-0090</li>\n<li>If you have a P.O. box and a street address but the P.O. box does not have the same zip code as the street address:\n<ol>\n<li>For a person\'s address, enter the P.O. box on address line 1 as the <b>mailing</b> address on one ADDVER screen, and enter the street address on address line 1 as the <b>home</b> address on a second ADDVER screen.</li>\n<li>For an employer\'s address, enter the street address on address line 1 and the P.O. box on address line 2. In the zip code plus four field, enter the +4 for the P.O. box.</li>\n</ol></li>\n</ol>\";i:1586284952208;s:517:\"<p>When you receive unverified information about a case participant\'s address, you need to verify the information as either \"good\" (\'Y\' in the address verified field) or \"bad\" (\'N\' in the address verified field).</p>\n<p>When you receive information through a non-automated source, you do not generate the letter (form 470-0176M, <i>Address Information Request</i>) unless the case meets certain criteria. The high cost associated with mailing the address verification letter makes it necessary to limit it\'s use.</p>\";i:1586284952520;s:974:\"<p>There are only four circumstances when you are allowed to send an address verification letter (form 470-0176M, <i>Address Information Request</i>). These circumstances are:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>Contempt: You are proceeding with a contempt action on the person</li>\n<li>Guidelines or Review: You are attempting to establish support payment amounts</li>\n<li>Interstate: You are attempting an interstate action</li>\n<li>Service of Process: You are attempting to serve papers to the person</li>\n</ul>\n<p> If one of the four approved reasons for sending the address verification letter is not occurring on a case, you may not use the address verification letter. See Sending an Address Verification Letter.</p>\n<p><b>Note:</b> Important: Do not send an address verification letter if the address is from an IRS source (IRS or FPLS/IRS). IRS information can only be used to verify information from another source. See Address Sources Requiring Special Handling for details.</p>\";i:1586284952800;s:1011:\"<p>If you receive an address from a non-automated source and your case does not meet one of the four criteria listed under When It Is Appropriate To Send The Verification Letter, the address verification must be conducted through manual efforts. However, we have identified some non-automated sources that do not require manual verification efforts. Statistics show some of our best location sources are our customers. You should automatically verify addresses received from these sources with a ‘Y’ in the address verified field:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>Custodial parent (CP)</li>\n<li>Noncustodial parent (NCP)</li>\n<li>Case participant relatives</li>\n<li>Child Support Lien Network (CSLN)</li>\n<li>Returned Mail</li>\n</ul>\n<p>When you receive an address from these sources you should verify the address by entering a ‘Y’ in the address verified field on ADDVER upon receipt unless you have good reason to believe the information deserves follow-up or you have evidence the information is not correct.</p>\";i:1586284953074;s:1207:\"<p>When a case participant or someone associated with the case participant gives you information, you need to qualify the source of the information. For example, if the custodial parent calls to tell you he or she found an address for the NCP on the internet, you should not automatically verify this information as \"Good\". You need to follow the procedures in the <a href=\"http://intra/csruhandbooks/HANDBOOKS/Location/Contents/Addver-EmpverTraining.pdf\" target=\"_blank\"><img src=\"https://stcsruportalcli.blob.core.windows.net/csruportalwpcontent/2020/04/pdf.png\"> <b>ADDVER/EMPVER</b></a> (broken link) training to ensure the information is correct.</p>\n<p>If the information you receive is new to the case or does not directly contradict information already on the case, and the information was not collected by the CP, NCP, relative, or address through unreliable means, you must verify the address as \"good\" by entering a ‘Y’ in the address verified field.</p>\n<p>If you receive information through a phone call and it is not immediately evident how the person came across the information, you must always qualify the information by asking the caller how he or she discovered the information.</p>\";i:1586284953307;s:685:\"<p>To add a new address verified as \"good\", press PF9 (Refresh) on the ADDVER or CPADDVER screen and add the address information. Enter a ‘Y’ in the address verified field and a \"Y\" in the update address field and press PF2 (Add) to move the address to the PAYOR screen.</p>\n<p>When you do not want to update the address, enter \"Y\" in the address verified field, but enter \"N\" in the update address field of the ADDVER or CPADDVER screen. ICAR displays a narrative (LOC 176) for you to record why the address information is not being updated.</p>\n<p>The address for an alleged father cannot be updated to the PAYOR screen until the alleged father is established as the payor.</p>\";i:1586284953581;s:1019:\"<p>When you have information from a source that is not considered automatically verified \"good\", you need to use non-automated sources to verify the information. You can enter the address onto ICAR as unverified (blank in the address verified field) without sending a letter (\'N\' in the send p.o. letter field).</p>\n<p>When a worker enters an address on ICAR unverified without sending a letter, ICAR begins an address tracking process. You must verify the address within 90 days of it being added to ICAR or, if the case meets the criteria, send address verification letter. ICAR tracks the progress of the letter.</p>\n<p>You need to attempt manual verification of the address. Even if the case meets the criteria for sending form 470-0176M, <i>Address Information Request</i>, you should first attempt manual verification.</p>\n<p>For more information on manually verifying address for case participants, please refer to the Best Practices and Policies for Manually Verifying Addresses section of this handbook.</p>\";i:1586284953847;s:787:\"<p>ICAR allows you to add an address as unverified. After entering the address information, put an \'N\' in the send p.o. letter field and leave the address verified field blank.</p>\n<p>Example:</p>\n<img src=\"https://stcsruportalcli.blob.core.windows.net/csruportalwpcontent/2020/04/AddingAnAddressAsUnverifiedExample.gif\" />\n<p>When you enter an address unverified, ICAR issues a narrative (AVER 4).</p>\n<p>If you do not generate an address verification letter or verify the address within <b>45 days</b> of adding the address to the case, ICAR issues a calendar flag (AVER 3) to track that address.</p>\n<p>If you do not verify the address after 90 days, ICAR enters \"N\' in the ADDRESS VERIFIED field, the current date in the DATE VERIFIED field, and issues a narrative (AVER 6).</p>\";i:1586284954105;s:1363:\"<p>This 90 day tracking process can only be stopped if one of the following occurs:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>Circumstances on the case change and it falls into the criteria under which it is appropriate to send a verification letter. If someone enters a ‘Y’ in the send p.o. letter field, ICAR stops tracking the progress of the address and instead turns to tracking the progress of the letter. (See Sending The Address Verification Letter.)</li>\n<li>Someone makes an entry on the ADDVER screen to indicate the address is \"good\" (‘Y’ in the address verified field) or \"bad\" (‘N’ in the address verified field), or</li>\n<li>Circumstances on the case change and it is no longer valid for follow up:\n<ul>\n<li>The case is closed, in hold, or in delete status</li>\n<li>Good Cause is pending or has been approved for the payee</li>\n<li>The case is now a 17 account type with a CSC worker ID</li>\n<li>The ICAR Case worker id field on the CASE screen is blank or equal to \'AAAA\'</li>\n<li>The Bankruptcy (Y/N) and Chapter field on the PAYOR screen displays either an \"11\" or a \"13\" in the chapter section of the field</li>\n<li>The deceased field on the LOCATE or PAYOR screen is \"Y\" and the corresponding Date of Death field is greater than zero, or</li>\n<li>The address is for an alleged father who is now bypassed or has been excluded</li>\n</ul></li>\n</ul>\";i:1586284954379;s:1214:\"<p>You can send a letter on a new or existing address if a case meets the criteria under which it is appropriate to send an address verification letter (470-0176M, Address Information Request). When you send the letter, ICAR tracks the progress of the letter.</p>\n<p><b>Note:</b> <b>Do not</b> edit the postmaster address unless you know the postmaster does not accept mail at the default address.</p>\n<p>See Editing Postmaster Addresses on Address Verification Forms for more details.</p>\n<p><b>Note:</b> Even though the address verification letter is now an online form, ICAR does not enter the current date in the DATE SENT field until a batch program runs at night. (ICAR does enter the current date into the form.) This is necessary for the programs that monitor how long it has been since the address verification letter was sent as explained in the ICAR\'s follow-up tracking of the letter section. The only exceptions to this are explained in What Stops the 90 Day Letter Tracking Process?.</p>\n<p>Remember that you can only generate an address verification letter in four special situations:</p>\n<ol>\n<li>service of process</li>\n<li>interstate</li>\n<li>guidelines, or</li>\n<li>contempt</li>\n</ol>\";i:1586284954637;s:1516:\"<ul>\n<li>Press PF9 (Refresh) on the ADDVER screen and add the address information,</li>\n<li>Enter a valid verification reason in the vrsn field,\n<ul>\n<li>SP (service of process)</li>\n<li>IN (interstate)</li>\n<li>CO (contempt)</li>\n<li>GU (guidelines)</li>\n</ul></li>\n<li>Enter an \'Y\' in the send p.o. letter field, and</li>\n<li>Press PF2 (Add) twice to add the address and generate the online letter.</li>\n</ul>\n<p>ICAR displays the online form 470-0176M, <i>Address Information Request</i>. This form prints immediately at your local office printer.</p>\n<p>ICAR enters the information on this form.</p>\n<p><b>Note:</b> The case party\'s first name, middle initial, and last name pull into form 470-0176M, <i>Address Information Request</i>. Postmasters are typically unable to confirm that the person who receives mail at an address has the same middle initial as our case party. This can result in a postmaster providing verification of an address when the person who receives mail there has the same first and last name as our case party but has a different middle name. Keep this in mind when considering other information you may have on a case regarding where an individual may live.</p>\n<p><b>Note:</b> <b>Do not</b> edit the postmaster address unless you know the postmaster does not accept mail at the default address.</p>\n<p>See Editing Postmaster Addresses on Address Verification Forms for more details.</p>\n<p>ICAR Issues a narrative (LOC 71) to record that you generated the letter.</p>\";i:1586284954894;s:830:\"<ul>\n<li>Enter a valid verification reason in the vrsn field,\n<ul>\n<li>SP (service of process)</li>\n<li>IN (interstate)</li>\n<li>CO (contempt)</li>\n<li>GU (guidelines)</li>\n</ul></li>\n<li>Enter an ‘Y’ in the send p.o. letter field, and</li>\n<li>Press PF3 (Modify) twice generate the online letter.</li>\n</ul>\n<p>ICAR displays the new online form 470-0176M, <i>Address Information Request</i>. This form prints immediately at your local office printer.</p>\n<p>ICAR enters the information on this form.</p>\n<p><b>Note:</b> <b>Do not</b> edit the postmaster address unless you know the postmaster does not accept mail at the default address.</p>\n<p>See Editing Postmaster Addresses on Address Verification Forms for more details.</p>\n<p>ICAR Issues a narrative (LOC 71) to record that you generated the letter.</p>\";i:1586284955151;s:1465:\"<ul>\n<li>Enter a valid verification reason in the vrsn field unless the reason has not changed since the initial letter, \n<ul>\n<li>SP (service of process)</li>\n<li>IN (interstate)</li>\n<li>CO (contempt)</li>\n<li>GU (guidelines)</li>\n</ul></li>\n<li>Enter an \'R\' in the send p.o. letter field, and</li>\n<li>Press PF3 (Modify) twice generate the online letter.</li>\n</ul>\n<p>ICAR displays the online form 470-0176M, <i>Address Information Request</i>. This form prints immediately at your local office printer.</p>\n<p>ICAR enters the information on this form.</p>\n<p><b>Note:</b> The case party\'s first name, middle initial, and last name pull into form 470-0176M, Address Information Request. Postmasters are typically unable to confirm that the person who receives mail at an address has the same middle initial as our case party. This can result in a postmaster providing verification of an address when the person who receives mail there has the same first and last name as our case party but has a different middle name. Keep this in mind when considering other information you may have on a case regarding where an individual may live.</p>\n<p><b>Note:</b> <b>Do not</b> edit the postmaster address unless you know the postmaster does not accept mail at the default address.</p>\n<p>See Editing Postmaster Addresses on Address Verification Forms for more details.</p>\n<p>ICAR Issues a narrative (LOC 71) to record that you generated the letter.</p>\";i:1586284955385;s:417:\"<p>If it has been 45 days since you generated the letter, ICAR issues a narrative (AVER 1) and a calendar flag (AVER 1) to track return of the verification letter.</p>\n<p>When an address is not yet verified after 90 days since the first verification letter was generated, ICAR verifies the address with an \"N\' and issues narrative AVER 2 to record the address and the reason the address was verified with an \'N\'.</p>\";i:1586284955605;s:1619:\"<p>This 90 day letter tracking process can only be stopped if one of the following occurs:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>Circumstances on the case change and it falls into the criteria under which it is appropriate to send another verification letter. If someone enters an ‘R’ in the send p.o. letter field, ICAR stops tracking the progress of the first letter and instead turns to tracking the progress of the second letter</li>\n<li>After you send the letter, someone makes an entry in the address verified field on the ADDVER screen to indicate the address is \"good\" (‘Y’ in the address verified field) or \"bad\" (‘N’ in the address verified field)</li>\n<li>When you send the letter, there is already an entry of \'Y\' in the address verified field on the ADDVER screen</li>\n<li>When you send the letter, the source in the source of address field equals \'History\', or</li>\n<li>Circumstances on the case change and it is no longer valid for follow up:\n<ul>\n<li>The case is closed, in hold, or in delete status</li>\n<li>Good Cause is pending or has been approved for the payee</li>\n<li>The case is now a 17 account type with a CSC worker ID</li>\n<li>The icar case worker id field on the CASE screen is blank or equal to ‘AAAA’</li>\n<li>The bankruptcy (y/n) and chapter field on the PAYOR screen displays either an \"11\" or a \"13\" in the chapter section of the field,</li>\n<li>The deceased field on the LOCATE or PAYOR screen is \"Y\" and the corresponding date of death field is greater than zero, or</li>\n<li>The address is for an alleged father who is now bypassed or has been excluded.</li>\n</ul></li>\n</ul>\";}"
