                        "__cdata": "a:6:{i:1586527901492;s:973:\"<p>This guide will assist you in:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>Searching and selecting existing employers from the employer maintenance file.</li>\n<li>Formatting addresses & employer names according to standards when:\n<ul>\n<li>You need an employer added to the employer maintenance file; or</li>\n<li>You need an employer’s name or address corrected.</li>\n</ul></li>\n</ul>\n<p>Use this guide when adding and updating employers on the EMPVER or CPEMPVER screens or when searching for an employer on the Employer Name Address Search screen or the Employer Maintenance screens.</p>\n<p>See The Employer Maintenance File for a description of the file.</p>\n<p>The following instructions explain the proper way to format employer records, and give tips for finding employer records on the maintenance files.</p>\n<p><b>Note:</b> These formatting guidelines are the current guidelines. Older records may not conform to the guidelines. Keep an open mind when searching for employers.</p>\";i:1586527901678;s:4843:\"<p>You can search by employer FEIN from the View Employer Maintenance screen. To search by FEIN, see <b>Viewing the Employer Maintenance File</b>.</p>\n<p>Most workers search by employers by name, either using VEMPLOY, or by pressing F6 on an EMPVER screen to access the Employer Name Address Search screen.</p>\n<p>When you search for an employer by name, ICAR displays the results in alphabetical order.</p>\n<p>You may have trouble finding the employer for a number of reasons, most often because your format for the name does not match the name in the file.</p>\n<p>The following tips may help you find the employer:</p>\n<p><b>TIP:</b> Use the F7 and F8 keys to move forward and back through the results screens.</p>\n<p><b>Explanation:</b></p>\n<p>When you search for an employer, ICAR displays the best match it can identify.</p>\n<p>However, punctuation differences, unusual spellings, or slight differences in the name of the company can cause problems, especially if the original employer record is old and does not conform to current standards.</p>\n<p><b>Example:</b></p>\n<p>You hear the obligor works for McGee’s Construction.</p>\n<p>You enter MCGEE’S CONSTRUCTION on EMPVER and press F6 to search the employer maintenance file. ICAR displays a list of employers beginning with \"McGee’s Dutch Mill.\"</p>\n<p>When you press F7, you see the employer listed as MCGEE CONSTRUCTION.</p>\n<p><b>TIP:</b> Search for the employer under an alternate name or spelling.</p>\n<p><b>Explanation:</b></p>\n<p>If an employer name can be spelled different ways, try looking under each spelling.</p>\n<p><b>Example:</b></p>\n<p>You hear the obligor works for McMillan Oil.</p>\n<p>You enter MCMILLAN OIL on EMPVER and press F6.</p>\n<p>You do not see the employer, so you press CLEAR to return to EMPVER.</p>\n<p>You enter MAC MILLAN OIL as the employer name and press F6. The employer is listed as MAC MILLAN OIL.</p>\n<p><b>TIP:</b> Search for the employer under both the legal and common name.</p>\n<p><b>Explanation:</b></p>\n<p>ICAR Maintenance staff attempt to list employers under names that you’ll be able to find. However, they may not always be able to list an employer under a common name.</p>\n<p>If you find the employer under a legal name, notify the ICAR Maintenance staff. They will update the listing to make the employer easier for other workers to find.</p>\n<p><b>Example:</b></p>\n<p>You hear the obligor works for Carl’s Place. You search the employer maintenance file under CARL’S PLACE and CARLS PLACE but cannot find the employer.</p>\n<p>In talking to the employer, you find out the legal name for the business is actually AG ENTERPRISES, which is how the business is listed on ICAR.</p>\n<p>You send the common business name to the ICAR Maintenance team. They update the employer name on the record.</p>\n<p><b>TIP:</b> When searching for a chain store or restaurant, add a character to the end of the name if you want to look at the end of the list.</p>\n<p><b>Explanation:</b></p>\n<p>Certain chain stores and restaurants may have many records in ICAR—one for each location. ICAR displays these records alphabetically by the city.</p>\n<p>If you want a store towards the end of the list, it may be faster for you to work your way from the last employer location rather than the first.</p>\n<p>When you change the last letter of the employer name or add a character to the end, ICAR displays the next business.</p>\n<p>Use the F7 key to work your way backward through the list.</p>\n<p><b>Example:</b></p>\n<p>You want to find a Wal-Mart in Waterloo. You could enter WALMART, but then you would have to page through all the locations to get to Waterloo’s listing.</p>\n<p>Instead, you enter WALMARTX to start your search. When ICAR displays the first business with a listing after this spelling, you press F7 to see last of the Wal-Mart locations.</p>\n<p><b>TIP:</b> When an employer name has components that can be \"spelled\" as words or symbols, look under the name both ways.</p>\n<p><b>Explanation:</b></p>\n<p>If an employer has numbers (such as 13 or five) or special symbols (such as \"+\"), look for the employer using both symbols and words.</p>\n<p><b>Example:</b></p>\n<p>If you can’t find A+ HARDWARE, look under A PLUS HARDWARE.</p>\n<p>If you can’t find THIRTEENTH STREET CAFE, look under 13TH STREET CAFE.</p>\n<p><b>TIP:</b> Use the employer address to confirm a match.</p>\n<p><b>Explanation:</b></p>\n<p>Employers sometimes have many different locations listed on the employer maintenance file. Use the addresses to confirm if you are selecting the correct employer.</p>\n<p><b>Example:</b></p>\n<p>You are looking for a McDonald’s at 30th and Forest in Des Moines. The employer maintenance file lists many McDonald’s in Des Moines, but only one located at 3002 Forest Ave.</p>\";i:1586527902522;s:8231:\"<p><b>Estates, Trust Funds, or Trust Accounts</b></p>\n<p>For estates, trust funds and trust accounts, use the name of:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>The deceased person (for an estate); or</li>\n<li>The person who established the trust.</li>\n</ul>\n<p>Put the executor or trustee’s name and title in the first line of the address.</p>\n<p>Examples:</p>\n<ul>\n<li><b>Estate</b><br />\nSmith John Q<br />\nJoe Z Smith Executor<br />\n918 Jones Ave<br />\nHiawatha IA 52233</li>\n<li><b>Trust</b><br />\nDoe Jane Y<br />\nJennifer T Doe Trustee<br />\n726 Deer Ln<br />\nWheatland IA 52722</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p><b>Farmers Cooperatives and Elevators</b></p>\n<p>For farmer’s cooperative or elevator businesses, search for the employer by both the name your source provided and by Farmers Coop or Farmers Elevator.</p>\n<ul>\n<li>If the employer has a record in the employer list, use the record already on ICAR.</li>\n<li>If ICAR has a Farmers Coop or Farmers Elevator listing and your source gave a different name, send both names and the current employer ID to <a href=\"mailto:rfee@dhs.state.ia.us\" target=\"_blank\"><b>Roger Fee</b></a> for possible update.</li>\n<li>If the employer has two records, one under Farmers Coop or Farmers Elevator and the other under a different name, send both names and employer IDs to <a href=\"mailto:rfee@dhs.state.ia.us\" target=\"_blank\"><b>Roger Fee</b></a> for update and consolidation.</li>\n<li>If you do not find the employer on ICAR at all, enter the employer using the name the employer supplied.</li>\n</ul>\n<br />\n<ul>\n<li><b>Provided Listing</b><br />\nCargill Inc<br />\n135 Frontage Rd<br />\nAdair IA 50001</li>\n<li><b>Farmers Listing</b><br />\nFarmers Coop<br />\n135 Frontage Rd<br />\nAdair IA 50001</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p><b>Federal and State Prisons</b></p>\n<p>For prison employers, use the state or federal agency as the company name, and place the name of the facility as the first line of the address.</p>\n<p>If you see two listing for the same Iowa prison, check the first address line.</p>\n<ul>\n<li>For inmates, select the one displaying \"% INMATE ACCOUNTS.\"</li>\n<li>For regular prison employees, select the other listing.</li>\n</ul>\n<p>Examples:</p>\n<ul>\n<li><b>Federal Prisons</b><br />\n<span style=\"color: red;\">Federal Bureau of Prisons</span><br />\n% Federal Detention Ctr<br />\nPO BOX 68955<br />\nSeattle WA 98168</br />\n<span style=\"color: red;\">Federal Bureau of Prisons</span><br />\n% Federal Correctional Inst<br />\n100 Prison Rd PO Box 699<br />\nEstill SC 29918</li>\n\n<li><b>State Prisons</b><br />\n<span style=\"color: red;\">IA Dept of Corrections</span><br />\n% Inmate Accounts<br />\n406 N High St<br />\nAnamosa IA<br />\n52205-1157<br />\n<span style=\"color: red;\">IA Dept of Corrections</span><br />\n% North Central Corr Facility<br />\n313 Lanedale<br />\nRockwell City IA 50579</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p><b>Labor Unions</b></p>\n<p>Do not abbreviate the names of unions.</p>\n<p>If you know the local union number, enter the union name, then send the location union number to <a href=\"mailto:rfee@dhs.state.ia.us\" target=\"_blank\"><b>Roger Fee</b></a> by e-mail.</p>\n<ul>\n<li><b>Common Format</b><br />\nUAW<br />\n1526 Clinton<br />\nWaterloo IA 50702</li>\n<li><b>Correct Format</b><br />\nUnited Auto Workers Union<br />\n1526 Clinton<br />\nWaterloo IA 50702</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p><b>Military Employees</b></p>\n<p>Use the following employers for US military employees:</p>\n[ninja_tables id=\"1423\"]\n<p><b>Note:</b> The DFAS employer record listed above (OTHR-0107753) links to the automated DFAS income withholding process.</p>\n<p>The employer record for OTHR-190705, Defense Finance & Accounting, is available for garnishments and lump sum IWOs for DFAS employees. Refer to the enforcement process for details about when you should select this employer.</p>\n\n<p><b>National Chain Stores</b> (e.g. Department Stores and Restaurant Chains)</p>\n<p>For a store in a national chain of stores, attempt to use the local store record. If the store does not have local listing on ICAR, do the following:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>If the store is located in Iowa or a bordering city, enter the store’s location.</li>\n<li>If the store is located out of Iowa and is not in a bordering city, use the corporate office or corporate payroll address.</li>\n</ul>\n<p>Examples of Border Cities:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>Sioux Falls</li>\n<li>Jackson</li>\n<li>Omaha</li>\n<li>East Dubuque</li>\n<li>South Sioux City</li>\n<li>Albert Lea</li>\n<li>Fairmont</li>\n<li>Fulton</li>\n<li>Rock Island</li>\n<li>Prairie du Chien</li>\n</ul>\n<p>Examples: Local stores in bordering cities</p>\n<ul>\n<li><b>Department Store Location</b><br />\nKmart<br />\n3000 S Minnesota Ave<br />\nSioux Falls SD 57105</li>\n<li><b>Restaurant Chain</b><br />\nOlive Garden<br />\n7505 Dodge St<br />\nOmaha NE 68114</li>\n</ul>\n<p>Examples: Corporate/payroll offices for stores outside Iowa and bordering cities</p>\n[ninja_tables id=\"1424\"]\n\n<p><b>Postal Service Employees</b></p>\n<p>Use one of the following two employer records for postal service employees:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>Retired employees: OTHR – 268937, US Postal Ofc Of Personnel Mgmt</li>\n<li>Current employees: OTHR-0138317, US Postal Service.</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p><b>Radio and Television Stations</b></p>\n<p>List the call letters of the station first for any radio or television station employers.</p>\n<p>Examples:</p>\n<ul>\n<li><b>Radio</b><br />\nKFJB AM<br />\n123 W Main St<br />\nMarshalltown IA 50158</li>\n<li><b>Television</b><br />\nKCCI Television Inc<br />\n888 9th St<br />\nDes Moines IA 50309</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p><b>Service Contractors</b> (e.g. Food or Cleaning Services)</p>\n<p>When a person is employed by national company contracted by a local business to provide food or cleaning services, use the national company’s name. Include the local business in the first address line.</p>\n<p>Examples:</p>\n<ul>\n<li><b>Food Service</b><br />\nMarriott Food Service<br />\n% Upper Iowa College<br />\n605 Washington St<br />\nFayette IA 52142</li>\n<li><b>Cleaning Service</b><br />\nAramark Services Inc<br />\n% Rockwell Collins<br />\n400 Collins Rd NE<br />\nCedar Rapids IA 52498 1000</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p><b>Temporary Services</b></p>\n<p>Search for and add large temporary service chains, such as AccountTemps, Kelly, or Manpower, the same as you would any other national chain.</p>\n\n<p><b>Workers’ Compensation Insurance Carriers</b></p>\n<p>Workers’ compensation insurance carriers may have two records on the employer maintenance file:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>One for use when the person is an employee of the company, and</li>\n<li>One for use when the person has an open claim.</li>\n</ul>\n<p>When the person is an employee of the company, use the standard employer record for the insurance carrier.</p>\n<p>When the person has an open claim, look for the employer record where \"% WORKER’S COMP\" displays in the first address line.</p>\n<p>If you cannot find a worker’s compensation employer record on the employer maintenance file and need to add the carrier to EMPVER or CPEMPVER, do the following:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>Enter the insurance carrier’s name in the employer name field.</li>\n<li>Enter the following in the source of emp field:\n<ul>\n<li>\"CSLN\" if the Child Support Lien Network (CSLN) reported the claim.</li>\n<li>\"WORKERS COMP\" if anyone else reported the claim.</li>\n</ul></li>\n<li>Enter \"% WORKER’S COMP\" in address line 1.</li>\n<li>Complete the screen.</li>\n</ul>\n<p><b>Important:</b> You must use \"CSLN\" or \"WORKERS COMP\" for the source and \"WORKERS COMP\" for the first line of the address. When you verify the EMPVER screen with a \"Y\" in the emp verified field, ICAR notifies the ICAR Maintenance team. The ICAR Maintenance team uses the source of emp and address line 1 fields to determine how to add the employer record to the employer maintenance file—as an income provider or as an employer.</p>\n<p>Example:</p>\n<ul>\n<li><b>For employees, use...</b><br />\nACME INSURANCE CO<br />\n919 S Coyote Dr<br />\nSioux Falls SD 57001</li>\n<li><b>For claimants, use...</b><br />\nACME INSURANCE CO<br />\n% WORKER’S COMP<br />\n919 S Coyote Dr<br />\nSioux Falls SD 57001</li>\n</ul>\";i:1586527902773;s:7707:\"<p>When the person’s employer contracts with the company for payroll processing, do not use the payroll processor’s name or address in the employer record. Use the actual employer’s name and address when searching for or entering the employer.</p>\n<p>For a list of payroll processors, see <a href=\"file://intradev/csruhandbooks/HANDBOOKS/Location/Contents/IcarFormatting/Guide%2520to%2520Adding%2520Updating%2520Employers/Payroll%2520Processing%2520Companies/Payroll_Processing_Addresses.doc\" target=\"_blank\"><img src=\"https://stcsruportalcli.blob.core.windows.net/csruportalwpcontent/2020/04/word.png\"> <b>Payroll Processing Addresses</b></a>.</p>\n<p><b>Caution:</b> Do not send employer verification letters to payroll processors!</p>\n\n<p>Identifying Payroll Processing Companies (below)<br />Finding the Real Employer Information (below)</p>\n<ol>\n<li>Checking other employers on the case</li>\n<li>Checking the employer maintenance file</li>\n<li>Checking other sources</li>\n</ol>\n\n<hr />\n\n<h4>Identifying Payroll Processing Companies</h4>\n<p>Payroll processing companies names and addresses may appear on EMPVER and CPEMPVER screens from automated sources and PIEX. Automated sources try to correct these records if possible, but cannot catch all such records.</p>\n<p>The address may or may not include any indication that the address is a payroll processor company. Watch for the following:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>An \"in care of\" indicator - such as \"C/O\" or \"%\" - in the first address line. These addresses often contain payroll processing companies.</li>\n<li>Employer names that are or include a payroll processor name. Sometime sources provide the real employer name and the payroll processor name together.</li>\n<li>An employer record on the same case that already has the same address but has a different employer name.</li>\n<li>A payroll processor address.</li>\n</ul>\n<p>Review the <a href=\"http://intra/csruhandbooks/HANDBOOKS/Location/Contents/IcarFormatting/Guide%20to%20Adding%20Updating%20Employers/Payroll%20Processing%20Companies/Payroll_Processing_Addresses.doc\" target=\"_blank\"><img src=\"https://stcsruportalcli.blob.core.windows.net/csruportalwpcontent/2020/04/word.png\"> <b>Payroll Processing Addresses</b></a> document for a listing of payroll processor names and addresses by city.</p>\n\n<hr />\n\n<h4>Finding the Real Employer Information</h4>\n<p>If you get a payroll processor record, attempt to find the correct employer information.</p>\n<p>These records often contain some information about the real employer such as the employer name and/or phone number.</p>\n<p>Use this information to track down complete employer information.</p>\n<p>To do so, compare the new information with the following</p>\n<ul>\n<li>Other employers on the case,</li>\n<li>Employers on the employer maintenance file, and</li>\n<li>Other sources</li>\n</ul>\n<ol>\n<li><b>Checking other employers on the case</b>\n<p>Review the EMPVER/CPEMPVER screens for the case to see if the employer was already verified. Do not look for an exact match. Instead, compare the addresses, the names, or the phone numbers.</p>\n<p>You can use the Employer Summary (EMPSUM) screen to quickly review several employer records at the same time.</p>\n<p>If the employer is already verified on the case, verify the new employer record with an \"N\" in the emp verified field.</p>\n</li>\n<li><b>Checking the employer maintenance file</b>\n<p>If the employer is not already verified on the case, attempt to find the employer on the employer maintenance file.</p>\n<ul>\n<li>Press F6 from the EMPVER/CPEMPVER screen to access the employer list.</li>\n<li>If you don’t find the employer on the first page, use the F7 and F8 keys to move forward and back through the list.</li>\n<li>Search carefully as the business name on ICAR may vary from the new record. For example, the EMPVER screen may show the employer name of Nacho Inc., but ICAR lists the employer as Nacho Mexican Restaurant.<br />\nIf you find the actual employer on the employer maintenance file, do the following:</li>\n<li>If the employer record is from a non-automated source, verify the record with an \"N\" and create a new employer record with the correct information.</li>\n<li>If the employer record is from an automated source, press F15 to copy the record. From the new record, press F6 and select the correct employer from the employer maintenance file.<br />\nFollowing these instructions ensures ICAR will not load the payroll processor information in the future and records the correct information.</li>\n</ul></li>\n<li><b>Checking other sources</b>\n<p>If the employer is not already verified and not on the employer maintenance file, attempt to find the actual employer location, name, and address. Sources for this information may include:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>Phone books and reverse telephone lookup: The employer records often contain the employer’s actual phone number.</li>\n<li>The payroll processor company: If the phone number belongs to the payroll processing company, they may be able to give you the correct employer name.</li>\n<p>If you find the actual employer information, enter it by typing over the existing data in the EMPLOYER NAME, ADDRESS LINE 1, ADDRESS LINE 2, CITY/STATE/ZIP, and PHONE NUMBER fields. If the employer is from an automated source, press F15 to make a copy of the record first, then type over the existing data in the copy.</p>\n<p>If you are not able to find the actual location, verify the employer with an \"N.\"</p>\n</ul></li>\n</ol>\n\n<hr />\n\n<h4>F15 Copy Function</h4>\n<p>If an automated source loads an improperly formatted employer to the EMPVER screen and the employer is not in the Employer Maintenance File, you must copy the employer to a new EMPVER screen to reformat the employer and verify it. All employers not in the Employer Maintenance File that ICAR loads to EMPVER screens from automated sources display a \'Y\' in the AUTO SOURCE field.</p>\n<p>ICAR displays blanks in the AUTO SOURCE field for all employers loaded to the EMPVER screen from automated sources if the employers are in the Employer Maintenance File. You cannot perform the F15 Copy function to reformat these employers. Only Central Office staff adds, modifies, or deletes employers from the Employers listed in the Employer Maintenance File.</p>\n<p>After verifying that an employer loaded by an automated source is improperly formatted, press F15 (Shift & F3) to copy that employer to a new EMPVER screen. ICAR transfers everything to the new EMPVER screen except the information below the phone number/ext fields. ICAR also enters the current date in the DATE address entered field and enters a \'C\' in the autosource field to indicate this is a copied employer received from an automated source that was improperly formatted.</p>\n<p>ICAR issues a narrative (EVER 13) to record the F15 copy.</p>\n<p>You can now modify the necessary address fields. The following fields are protected from modification:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>DATE ADDRESS ENTERED</li>\n<li>DATE OF ADDRESS</li>\n<li>AUTOSOURCE</li>\n<li>SOURCE OF EMP</li>\n<li>FEDERAL ID</li>\n<li>EMPLOYER ID</li>\n<li>BYP EMP</li>\n<li>UIB/WAGE fields</li>\n<li>NMBA</li>\n</ul>\n<p>After you reformat the employer, press F2 to add the properly formatted employer to the case. When you press F2 to add the newly formatted employer to the case, ICAR enters an \'N\' and the current date to the emp verified and date verifd fields on the original EMPVER screen that contains the improperly formatted employer. ICAR also changes the \'Y\' in the autosource field to an \'F\' to indicate the employer loaded by an automated source was copied for improper formatting.</p>\";i:1586527903062;s:657:\"<p>When you add an employer to EMPVER/CPEMPVER, enter the local address where the person actually works.</p>\n<p>If the employer requests the Unit send IWOs to a different address or include special information in the IWO address (such as contact information), e-mail the IWO address to <a href=\"mailto:rfee@dhs.state.ia.us\" target=\"_blank\"><b>Roger Fee</b></a> when you verify the employer.</p>\n<p>If the company is a sole proprietorship and the company name begins with a proper full name, use the proper last name in the company name, but include the proper full name in the IWO address.</p>\n<p><b>Examples</b></p>\n[ninja_tables id=\"1425\"]\n\n\n\n\n\n\";i:1586533974723;s:2535:\"<p>ICAR displays the EMPLOYER NAME ADDRESS SEARCH screen when you press PF6 on the EMPVER screen. Type the company name in the employer name field of the EMPVER screen, and press PF6. A list of employers is displayed in alphabetical order beginning with the one that most closely matches the name you typed on the EMPVER screen.</p>\n<p>If an employer is located in more than one city, the cities are listed alphabetically. Use the PF7 and PF8 keys to scroll. Put an \"X\" in the SEL field displayed to the left of the name of the business and press Enter. The address of the employer you selected displays on the EMPVER or CPEMPVER screen.</p>\n<p><img src=\"https://stcsruportalcli.blob.core.windows.net/csruportalwpcontent/2020/04/SearchTheEmployerMaintDatebaseF6.gif\" /></p>\n<p>Company information is displayed as follows:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>The company name and street address display on the same line</li>\n<li>The company’s Federal Employer Identification Number (FEIN) begins the second line of information. (Note: FIN and FEIN are synonymous.)</li>\n<li>The date information was last updated in the L/U field is displayed</li>\n<li>City and state information for the employer is displayed to the right of the L/U field.</li>\n</ul>\n<p>If the employer is not on the EMPLOYER NAME ADDRESS SEARCH screen, enter the employer information on the EMPVER. Include all available information on the employer: address, telephone number, health insurance availability and the company’s Federal Identification Number (FEIN).</p>\n<p>When the employer is not found on the Employer Maintenance File, the information must be added to ICAR. Updating the Employer Maintenance File is reserved for the Iowa Centralized Employee Registry (ICER) team at Central Office.</p>\n<p>When you verify an employer that is not already linked to the Employer Maintenance File, the ICER team receives a calendar flag (LOC 33) telling them the employer needs to be added to the file.</p>\n<p>The EMPLOYER NAME ADDRESS SEARCH screen works the same way when accessed from the CPEMPVER screen.</p>\n<p><b>Note:</b> When ICER receives this calendar flag, they should not need to reformat the employer address nor should they find the employer already listed in the Employer Maintenance File. You must not verify an employer with a \'Y\' until you have thoroughly searched the Employer Maintenance File. If the employer could not be found in the file, you must reformat the employer to postal standards before entering a \'Y\' in the emp verified field.</p>\n\n\n\n\n\n\";}"
                     }
