                     "meta_value": {
                        "__cdata": "a:15:{i:1586783584466;s:1197:\"<p>For questions related to each policy area listed, please contact the following distribution lists:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>Credit Reporting - <a href=\"mailto:CSRUPolicy-CreditReporting@dhs.state.ia.us\" target=\"_blank\"><b>CSRU Policy – Credit Reporting</b></a></li>\n<li>License Sanction (LISAN) - <a href=\"mailto:csrupolicy-lisan@dhs.state.ia.us\" target=\"_blank\"><b>CSRU Policy - Lisan</b></a></li>\n<li>Income Withholding (IWO) - <a href=\"mailto:csrupolicy-iwo@dhs.state.ia.us\" target=\"_blank\"><b>CSRU Policy - IWO</b></a></li>\n<li>Medical Support -  <a href=\"mailto:CSRUPolMed@dhs.state.ia.us\" target=\"_blank\"><b>CSRU Policy - Medical</b></a></li>\n<li>Federal Offset (FED/FAO) - <a href=\"mailto:CSRUPolicy-Offsets@dhs.state.ia.us\" target=\"_blank\"><b>CSRU Policy – Offsets</b></a></li>\n<li>State Offset (STT/DOP) - <a href=\"mailto:CSRUPolicy-Offsets@dhs.state.ia.us\" target=\"_blank\"><b>CSRU Policy – Offsets</b></a></li>\n<li>Location -  <a href=\"mailto:CSRUPolicy-Location@dhs.state.ia.us\" target=\"_blank\"><b>CSRU Policy - Location</b></a></li>\n</ul>\n<p>For general bankruptcy questions, please contact <a href=\"mailto:jrueber@dhs.state.ia.us\" target=\"_blank\"><b>Janelle Rueber</b></a>.</p>\";i:1586783584730;s:382:\"<p>To find information about how bankruptcy impacts the Administrative Levy process, clink the link below and Search using the keyword “bankruptcy.”</p>\n<p><a href=\"http://dhs.iowa.gov/sites/default/files/11-a.pdf\" target=\"_blank\"><img src=\"https://stcsruportalcli.blob.core.windows.net/csruportalwpcontent/2020/04/pdf.png\"> <b>Administrative Levy Employees\' Manual</b></a></p>\";i:1586783584965;s:782:\"<p>If you have questions about how bankruptcy affects credit reporting enforcement, please contact: <a href=\"mailto:CSRUPolicy-CreditReporting@dhs.state.ia.us\" target=\"_blank\"><b>CSRU Policy – Credit Reporting</b></a>.</p>\n\n<p><b>How Bankruptcy Affects Credit Reporting Enforcement</b></p>\n<p>On the PAYOR screen, when there an active bankruptcy <span style=\"color: red;\">(any chapter)</span>, and:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>A payor has not been reported to the credit reporting agencies, the payor’s cases will be bypassed for credit reporting enforcement.</li>\n<li>A payor is currently reported to the credit reporting agencies, the payor’s cases will be <span style=\"color: red;\">deleted from credit reporting</span> until the payor no longer has an active bankruptcy.</li>\n</ul>\";i:1586783585230;s:365:\"<p>To find information about how bankruptcy impacts the LISAN process, clink the link below and Search using the keyword “bankruptcy.”</p>\n<p><a href=\"http://dhs.iowa.gov/sites/default/files/11-G.pdf\" target=\"_blank\"><img src=\"https://stcsruportalcli.blob.core.windows.net/csruportalwpcontent/2020/04/pdf.png\"> <b>License Sanction Employees\' Manual</b></a></p>\";i:1586783585488;s:248:\"<p>See the <a href=\"http://dhssp/depdir/paa/FandMDev/EmployeeManual/Documents/Manual%20PDFs/11-F.pdf\" target=\"_blank\"><img src=\"https://stcsruportalcli.blob.core.windows.net/csruportalwpcontent/2020/04/pdf.png\"> <b>IWO Employees Manual</b></a>.</p>\";i:1586783585746;s:2566:\"<p>When a payor files bankruptcy, you must complete the BANKRPTCY & CHAPTR field on the PAYOR screen. This field consists of three sections. Make the following entries:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>First section: Enter “Y”.</li>\n<li>Second section: Enter 7, 11, or 13 to indicate the type of bankruptcy filed.</li>\n<li>Third section: Enter the date the bankruptcy was filed.</li>\n</ul>\n<p>CSRU will not enforce a payor’s order to provide medical support when the payor files bankruptcy under the following conditions:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>Chapter 11 bankruptcy.</li>\n<li>Chapter 13 bankruptcy.</li>\n</ul>\n<p>CSRU will enforce a payor’s order to provide medical support when the payor files bankruptcy under chapter 7.</p>\n<p>When the children are enrolled in a health insurance policy and the payor then files for bankruptcy, keep the children enrolled in that policy. This applies whether it is a chapter 11, 13, or 7 bankruptcy.</p>\n\n<p><b>Payor Files Bankruptcy under <span style=\"color: red;\">either</span> Chapter 11 <span style=\"color: red;\">or</span> Chapter 13:</b></p>\n<ul>\n<li>When EPICS gets a calendar flag for a HI POT of \"A\" to begin medical support enforcement, do not proceed with medical enforcement until the bankruptcy ends.  \n<ul>\n<li>Enter an \"X\" in the ENR STAT field on the MEDSUM2 screen to indicate that CSRU is not proceeding with enforcement due to bankruptcy.</li>\n<li>Set a calendar flag to review the case in 3 months to determine if the bankruptcy ended.</li>\n<li>When the bankruptcy ends, retrigger the case for medical support enforcement.</li>\n</ul></li>\n<li><span style=\"color: red;\">If the employer has already been sent</span> the National Medical Support Notice (NMSN), contact the employer. Find out whether the children are enrolled in the payor’s health insurance policy.  \n<ul>\n<li>If the children are already enrolled in the health insurance policy, enter the policy on the MEDICAL screen.</li>\n<li>If the children are in the process of being enrolled, <span style=\"color: red;\">tell the employer not to enroll the child(ren)</span>. Generate and send form 470-3933, Termination of the National Medical Support Notice, to the employer to stop the enrollment process.</li>\n<li>Enter a \"5\" (temporarily ineligible) in the FORM STAT field and an “I” in the ENR STAT field on the MEDSUM2 screen. Set the calendar flag to review the case in 3 months to determine whether the bankruptcy ended.</li>\n<li>When the bankruptcy ends, retrigger the case for medical support enforcement.</li>\n</ul></li>\n</ul>\n\n\n\n\";i:1586783586057;s:463:\"<ul>\n<li><a href=\"file://hoovr3s2/csru.772/CSRUPROC/Directives/2011/PD%2011-04%20State%20and%20Federal%20Tax%20Offset%20Bankruptcy%20Changes.docx\" target=\"_blank\"><img src=\"https://stcsruportalcli.blob.core.windows.net/csruportalwpcontent/2020/04/word.png\"> <b>PD 11-04</b></a></li>\n<li>For additional questions, please contact the <a href=\"mailto:csrupolicy-offsets@dhs.state.ia.us\" target=\"_blank\"><b>CSRU POLICY – OFFSETS email address</b></a>.</li>\n</ul>\";i:1586783586271;s:463:\"<ul>\n<li><a href=\"file://hoovr3s2/csru.772/CSRUPROC/Directives/2011/PD%2011-04%20State%20and%20Federal%20Tax%20Offset%20Bankruptcy%20Changes.docx\" target=\"_blank\"><img src=\"https://stcsruportalcli.blob.core.windows.net/csruportalwpcontent/2020/04/word.png\"> <b>PD 11-04</b></a></li>\n<li>For additional questions, please contact the <a href=\"mailto:csrupolicy-offsets@dhs.state.ia.us\" target=\"_blank\"><b>CSRU POLICY – OFFSETS email address</b></a>.</li>\n</ul>\";i:1586783586537;s:265:\"<p><b>SPLS/Quick Locates</b></p>\n<p>ICAR does allow SPLS requests on payors and payees if they have filed bankruptcy.</p>\n<p>ICAR does not allow postal letter (470-0176M, Address Information Request), to be sent to a payor or payee who has filed bankruptcy.</p>\n\";i:1586783586793;s:3939:\"<p>There are four chapters of bankruptcy code available to consumers:</p>\n<p>When a payor files bankruptcy, the type of bankruptcy has an effect upon the establishment and enforcement of child support claims. If you receive notification of bankruptcy, enter the information into the bankruptcy & chaptr field on the PAYOR or PAYEE screen. If you are in doubt about what to do, please consult with your office’s attorney.</p>\n\n<p><b>Chapter 7 Bankruptcy</b></p>\n<p>The purpose of the chapter 7 bankruptcy is the straight liquidation of debts. It is designed for debtors in financial difficulty who do not have the ability to pay their existing debts. All non-exempt property owned by the debtor as of the date of filing of the petition is applied by the bankruptcy trustee to pay the creditors’ claims. The duration of the bankruptcy plan is short - generally 90 to 120 days from the filing of the petition.</p>\n<p><b>Note:</b> A debtor may initially file a chapter 7 bankruptcy which can then be converted to a chapter 13 proceeding. The reverse is also true - a chapter 13 proceeding can be converted to a chapter 7 bankruptcy. The conversion from one plan to another does not reinstate the stay if previous relief from the stay was received.</p>\n<p>The creditor should receive a notice of the chapter 7 filing and notice of whether a claim should be filed or not. No claim is to be filed if there are no assets.</p>\n<p>Generally, there is no need for CSRU to file a proof of claim since support obligations are nondischargeable and given the shortness of the bankruptcy plan. Any questions or concerns should be addressed to the office attorney.</p>\n<p>A chapter 7 bankruptcy can be filed by a debtor only once every seven years.</p>\n\n<p><b>Chapter 11 Bankruptcy</b></p>\n<p>This bankruptcy chapter is designed for debt relief for a business reorganization or for an individual with debts which exceed the chapter 13 limitations.</p>\n<p>Complete and file the claim with attachments (copy of all orders and pay records) with the bankruptcy clerk of court for chapter 11 bankruptcy. Do not file a claim when there is no balance on the case.</p>\n\n<p><b>Chapter 12 Bankruptcy</b></p>\n<p>This bankruptcy chapter is designed to allow family farmers and fishermen to repay their debts from future earning over a period of time. A chapter 12 bankruptcy is similar to a chapter 13 bankruptcy, but the eligibility requirements are restrictive, limiting its use to family farmers or commercial fishermen.</p>\n<p>Chapter 7, 11, and 13 bankruptcies can be recorded on the bankruptcy & chaptr field on the PAYOR screen. However, the chapter 12 bankruptcy should be treated as a 13 action. The payor field should show it as a 13 filing; however, a narrative should be entered confirming that this particular action is actually a 12 filing.</p>\n\n<p><b>Chapter 13 Bankruptcy</b></p>\n<p>This bankruptcy option is available to debtors with regular income and whose total debts do not exceed certain dollar amounts set forth in the bankruptcy code.</p>\n<p>In this type of bankruptcy the debtor makes regular payments to the bankruptcy trustee during the life of the plan, which generally lasts as long as 24 to 60 months. The trustee then makes the actual payment to the creditors.</p>\n<p><b>Note:</b> In most cases, the plan will be funded by payments from future wages earned or other income received by the debtor. Occasionally, however, the plan will be funded by the sale of real estate, for example, with the proceeds going to the trustee to distribute to the various creditors.</p>\n<p>Complete and file the claim with attachments (copy of all orders and pay records) with the bankruptcy clerk of court for chapter 13 bankruptcy. Do not file a claim when there is no balance on the case.</p>\n<p>Unlike chapter 7 proceedings, which can be filed only once every seven years, a debtor can file serial chapter 13 proceedings.</p>\";i:1586783587052;s:2242:\"<ul>\n<li><b>Process:</b> ENF</li>\n<li><b>Number:</b> 14</li>\n<li><b>Priority:</b> High</li>\n<li><b>Text:</b> BANKRUPTCY CLAIM IS PENDING. REVIEW THE ESTABLISHMENT AND ENFORCEMENT PROCESSES.</li>\n<li><b>Best Practice:</b></li>\n</ul>\n<p>Contact the bankruptcy court using their VCIS system (see Resources) to see if the bankruptcy is still active.  If the bankruptcy has ended, update the PAYOR screen accordingly.  If the bankruptcy has not ended, do not make any changes to the bankruptcy fields on the PAYOR screen.</p>\n<p><b>Note:</b> You cannot delete this flag. ICAR will delete it when the bankruptcy fields on the PAYOR screen are updated to show the bankruptcy has ended.</p>\n<p>ICAR issues this flag when the bankruptcy date is added to the PAYOR screen. The flag is dated 180 days after the bankruptcy date.</p>\n<p>Every three months, ICAR replaces the ENF14 flags with new ones dated 180 days into the future. This happens in January, April, July, and October.</p>\n\n<hr />\n\n<ul>\n<li><b>Process:</b> ENF</li>\n<li><b>Number:</b> 18</li>\n<li><b>Priority:</b> N/A</li>\n<li><b>Text:</b> CHAPTER 7 BANKRUPTCY CLAIM IS PENDING. DETERMINE IF THE BANKRUPTCY HAS BEEN DISCHARGED AND TAKE THE APPROPRIATE ACTION.</li>\n<li><b>Best Practice:</b>\n<ul>\n<li>The ENF 18 flag no longer issues.</li>\n<li>This flag previously issued in addition to the ENF 14 flag when a payor had a chapter 7 bankruptcy.</li>\n</ul></li>\n</ul>\n\n<hr />\n\n<ul>\n<li><b>Process:</b> FED</li>\n<li><b>Number:</b> 16</li>\n<li><b>Priority:</b> High</li>\n<li><b>Text:</b></li>\n<li><b>Best Practice:</b></li>\n</ul>\n<p>Review the details of the bankruptcy proceeding and determine, based on the date of the offset, the date of the bankruptcy, and the details of the bankruptcy, whether you may apply the FED payment or must return the payment to the payor. Consult your office’s attorney, if necessary.</p>\n<p>If you may apply the FED payment, send a request to CSC to override the reject status. After CSC enters the override, ICAR allocates the money to the certified past-due support during the nightly batch process if the payment is not rejected for some other reason.</p>\n<p>If you may not apply the payment, refund it to the payor.</p>\";i:1586783587309;s:1064:\"<p><b>Enforcement</b></p>\n<p><b>ENF 31</b><br />\n“B - - CHAPTER ____ BANKRUPTCY IS PENDING.”</p>\n<p><b>ENF 32</b><br />\n\"Y\" REMOVED FROM PAYOR BANKRUPTCY FIELD ON _______________ .”</p>\n\n<p><b>Credit Reporting</b></p>\n<p><b>CRA <span style=\"color: red;\">60</span></b><br />\n“PAYOR <span style=\"color: red;\">HAS</span> FILED BANKRUPTCY. <span style=\"color: red;\">THE CASE HAS BEEN DELTED FROM THE PAYORS CREDIT REPORT.</span></p>\n<p><b>CRA <span style=\"color: red;\">56 (This narrative has additional uses other than backruptcy)</span></b><br />\n<span style=\"color: red;\">CASE WAS NOTICED; HOWEVER, THE CASE NO LONGER MEETS THE CRITERIA FOR CREDIT REPORTING THEREFORE THE CASE WILL NOT BE REPORTED TO THE CREDIT REPORTING AGENCIES AT THIS TIME.</span></p>\n\n<p><b>Federal Tax Offsets</b></p>\n<p><b>FED29 Narrative</b><br />\nFED TAX OFFSET HAS REJECTED FROM ICAR. PAYOR IS BANKRUPT.</p>\n\n<p><b>State Tax Offsets</b></p>\n<p><b>STT43 Narrative</b><br />\nSTATE TAX OFFSET REJECTED FROM ICAR DUE TO BANKRUPTCY INFORMATION ON THE PAYOR SCREEN.</p>\";i:1586783587560;s:6895:\"<p><b>Automatic Stay:</b> The automatic stay is an injunction that automatically stops lawsuits, foreclosures, garnishments and collection activity against the debtor the moment a bankruptcy petition is filed.<sup>1</sup></p>\n<p><b>Bankruptcy:</b> A legal procedure for dealing with debt problems of individuals and businesses; specifically, a case filed under one of the chapters of title 11 of the United States Code (the bankruptcy code).<sup>1</sup></p> \n<p><b>Bankruptcy Plan:</b> A debtor\'s detailed description of how the debtor proposes to pay creditors\' claims over a fixed period of time.<sup>1</sup></p>\n<p><b>Chapter 7:</b> This chapter of the bankruptcy code provides for \"liquidation,\" (i.e., the sale of a debtor\'s nonexempt property and the distribution of the proceeds to creditors.)<sup>1</sup></p> \n<p><b>Chapter 11:</b> This chapter of the bankruptcy code provides (generally) for reorganization, usually involving a corporation or partnership. (A chapter 11 debtor usually proposes a plan of reorganization to keep its business alive and pay creditors over time. People in business or individuals can also seek relief in chapter 11.)<sup>1</sup></p>\n<p><b>Chapter 12:</b> This chapter of the bankruptcy code provides for adjustment of debts of a \"family farmer,\" or a \"family fisherman\" as those terms are defined in the bankruptcy code.<sup>1</sup></p>\n<p><b>Chapter 13:</b> This chapter of the bankruptcy code provides for the adjustment of debts of an individual with regular income. (Chapter 13 allows a debtor to keep property and pay debts over time, usually three to five years.)<sup>1</sup></p>\n<p><b>Claim:</b> A creditor\'s assertion of a right to payment from the debtor or the debtor\'s property.<sup>1</sup></p>\n<p><b>Creditor:</b> One to whom the debtor owes money or who claims to be owed money by the debtor.<sup>1</sup></p>\n<p><b>Debtor:</b> A person who has filed a petition for relief under the bankruptcy code.<sup>1</sup></p>\n<p><b>Discharge:</b> A release of a debtor from personal liability for certain dischargeable debts set forth in the bankruptcy code. A discharge releases a debtor from personal liability for certain debts known as dischargeable debts and prevents the creditors owed those debts from taking any action against the debtor to collect the debts. The discharge also prohibits creditors from communicating with the debtor regarding the debt, including telephone calls, letters, and personal contact.<sup>1</sup></p>\n<p><b>Domestic Support Obligation (DSO):</b> All debts that are owed to or recoverable by a spouse, child, guardian, responsible relative, or government unit and that are in the nature of alimony, maintenance or support (including public assistance), entered by a court or government unit. A DSO does not include debt “assigned to a nongovernmental entity, unless it was assigned voluntarily…solely for the purpose of collecting the debt.”<sup>2</sup></p>\n<p><b>Exemptions/Exempt Property:</b> Certain property owned by an individual debtor that the bankruptcy code or applicable state law permits the debtor to keep from unsecured creditors. For example, in some states the debtor may be able to exempt all or a portion of the equity in the debtor\'s primary residence (homestead exemption), or some or all \"tools of the trade\" used by the debtor to make a living (i.e., auto tools for an auto mechanic or dental tools for a dentist). The availability and amount of property the debtor may exempt depends on the state the debtor lives in.<sup>1</sup></p>\n<p><b>Liquidation:</b> A sale of a debtor\'s property with the proceeds to be used for the benefit of creditors.<sup>1</sup></p>\n<p><b>Nondischargeable Debt:</b> A debt that cannot be eliminated in bankruptcy. Examples include a home mortgage, certain taxes, debts for most government funded or guaranteed educational loans or benefit overpayments, debts arising from death or personal injury caused by driving while intoxicated or under the influence of drugs, and debts for restitution or a criminal fine included in a sentence on the debtor\'s conviction of a crime. Some debts, such as debts for money or property obtained by false pretenses and debts for fraud or defalcation while acting in a fiduciary capacity may be declared nondischargeable only if a creditor timely files and prevails in a nondischargeability action.<sup>1</sup></p>\n<p><b>Priority:</b> The bankruptcy code\'s statutory ranking of unsecured claims that determines the order in which unsecured claims will be paid if there is not enough money to pay all unsecured claims in full.<sup>1</sup></p>\n<p><b>Proof of Claim:</b> A written statement and verifying documentation filed by a creditor that describes the reason the debtor owes the creditor money. (There is an official form for this purpose.)<sup>1</sup></p>\n<p><b>Property of the Estate:</b> All legal or equitable interests of the debtor in property become the property of the bankruptcy estate and will be distributed to the debtor’s creditors.<sup>1</sup></p>\n<p><b>Secured Debt:</b> Debt backed by a mortgage, pledge of collateral, or other lien; debt for which the creditor has the right to pursue specific pledged property upon default. Examples include home mortgages, auto loans and tax liens.<sup>1</sup></p>\n<p><b>Trustee:</b> The representative of the bankruptcy estate who exercises statutory powers, principally for the benefit of the unsecured creditors, under the general supervision of the court and the direct supervision of the U.S. trustee or bankruptcy administrator. The trustee is a private individual or corporation appointed in all chapter 7, chapter 12, and chapter 13 cases and some chapter 11 cases. The trustee\'s responsibilities include reviewing the debtor\'s petition and schedules and bringing actions against creditors or the debtor to recover property of the bankruptcy estate. In chapter 7, the trustee liquidates property of the estate, and makes distributions to creditors. Trustees in chapter 12 and 13 have similar duties to a chapter 7 trustee and the additional responsibilities of overseeing the debtor\'s plan, receiving payments from debtors, and disbursing plan payments to creditors.<sup>1</sup></p>\n<p><b>U.S. Trustee:</b> An officer of the Justice Department responsible for supervising the administration of bankruptcy cases, estates, and trustees; monitoring plans and disclosure statements; monitoring creditors\' committees; monitoring fee applications; and performing other statutory duties.<sup>1</sup></p>\n\n<p><sup>1</sup> <a href=\"http://www.uscourts.gov/FederalCourts/Bankruptcy/BankruptcyBasics/Glossary.aspx\" target=\"_blank\"><b>http://www.uscourts.gov/FederalCourts/Bankruptcy/BankruptcyBasics/Glossary.aspx</b></a><p>\n\n<p><sup>2</sup> House Report 109-031, Part 1, Subtitle B. Priority Child Support</p>\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\";i:1586783587832;s:124:\"<p><a href=\"http://www.uscourts.gov/forms/bankruptcy-forms/proof-claim-0\" target=\"_blank\"><b>Proof of Claim Form</b></a></p>\";i:1586783588098;s:702:\"<ul>\n<li><a href=\"http://www.pacer.gov/phone_access.html\" target=\"_blank\"><b>Voice Case Information System (VCIS)</b></a>\n<br />\n<p>Once you have accessed this site, scroll down to the VCIS: Voice Case Information System section - approximately 1/3 of the way down the page.</p>\n<p>There is no access fee associated with the toll free telephone number service.</p></li>\n<li><a href=\"https://www.uscourts.gov/about-federal-courts/federal-courts-public/court-website-links#districtbankruptcy\" target=\"_blank\"><b>U.S. Bankruptcy Court Directory</b></a></li>\n<li><a href=\"http://www.uscourts.gov/FederalCourts/Bankruptcy.aspx\" target=\"_blank\"><b>Federal Bankruptcy Courts Homepage</b></a></li>\n</ul>\";}"
