                        "__cdata": "a:21:{i:1586789557787;s:466:\"<p>Use the Confidential Information Form (aka Information Pursuant to 598.22B &602.6111) (Form 470-3804):</p>\n<ul>\n<li>When filing new actions; and</li>\n<li>When new information needs to be transmitted to the COC. For example:\n<ul>\n<li>Adding a child to the order,</li>\n<li>Adding CP as a Respondent,</li>\n<li>Adding a caretaker to a case in a redirection,</li>\n<li>A party’s name has changed,</li>\n<li>A party’s SSN has changed.</li>\n</ul></li>\n</ul>\";i:1586789558055;s:576:\"<p>While efiling, you may discover discrepancies between CSRU and JB in the letter prefixes of docket numbers…i.e. a case may be USUS123456 on ICAR but is DRCV123456 in ICIS.</p>\n<p>If presented with a docket number change, try to verify that it is still the same court file by looking at the docket on ICIS and compare it to documents known to have been filed. If you are confident that it is the same case, then change the docket number on ICAR and narrate why the docket number has been changed. Only do this on a case by case basis….do not do a mass conversion.</p>\n\";i:1586789558288;s:727:\"<p> Documents filed by CSRU should <b>NOT</b> be rejected by the COC if the docket number does not appear on each individual document to be file stamped. This direction was provided from JUDICIAL to all e-filing COC in 2011 and has been incorporated in COC training. CSRU should <b>NOT</b> write docket numbers on documents before sending them over for filing or after the filed document has been received back from the COC.</p>\n<p>The docket number will <b>NOT</b> appear on all e-filed documents which are part of the original filing of a new action, such as a 252C. The docket number will appear on the page with the judge’s signature. This is sufficient as it provides all parties with notice of the docket number.</p>\n\";i:1586789558546;s:1952:\"<p>CSRU prefers that documents be filed through CSeF whenever possible. EDMS returns documents to CSRU as external filings. This involves extra work for the office. Filing through EDMS also links individual CSRU attorneys to cases, which requires them to have to withdraw later. An attorney who is linked will be the only one in the office receiving e-mail notices of electronic filing (NEFs), unless the office is also linked or the office’s legal e-mail address is included as an alternate address in the attorney’s EDMS profile. Depending on local accepted practice, an attorney may need to use EDMS to file on multi-caption cases in the same county and to file proposed exhibits, answers, and appearances.</p>\n\n<p><b>Accessing EDMS</b></p>\n<p>The EDMS log-in page can be accessed at <a href=\"https://www.iowacourts.state.ia.us/EFile/\" target=\"_blank\"><b>https://www.iowacourts.state.ia.us/EFile/</b></a>. This is where an account can be requested. When setting up an account, it is important to include both your individual e-mail address and your office’s legal e-mail address. This will ensure that the office is also receiving NEFs even when the office isn’t officially linked to the case. If you already have an EDMS account and would like to add your office’s legal e-mail address as an alternate, log on to EDMS and click on the My Profile link followed by the Modify User Profile link.</p>\n\n<p><b>Case conversion for e-filing</b></p>\nIn EDMS, cases must first be converted for e-filing before they can be filed on. To determine if a case has already been converted, access the link to the case on Iowa Courts Online. Clicking the link should take you to the Trial Courts Case Details page. If the case has already been converted, it will have “EDMS” in green at the far right in the dark gray Summary box. If a case still needs to be converted, you can e-mail a request to the clerk of court or call if it’s urgent.</p>\";i:1586789558804;s:493:\"<p> When efiling documents for another office, be sure to use that office’s address/phone/fax/email in your attorney signature block. Also, make sure that the Office Location and Filer Name fields on the Efile Packet tab in CSeF show the other office’s name, not your own office’s name. You may be efiling documents for another office if certain processes have been regionalized, or because the other office is handling a case in an efiling county but are not yet efiling themselves.</p>\";i:1586789559086;s:3504:\"<ul>\n<li><b>Definition of Signature</b><br />\nIowa Court Rule 16.201 defines “Signature” as a registered filer’s login and password with either a digital signature, digitized signature, electronic signature or nonelectronic signature. See <a href=\"http://dhssp/csr/projects/efiling/attorneyworkgroup/Shared%20Documents/Signature%20examples%20per%20Chapter%2016%20Rules.pdf\" target=\"_blank\"><img src=\"https://stcsruportalcli.blob.core.windows.net/csruportalwpcontent/2020/04/sharepoint.png\"> <b>Signature Examples per Chapter 16 Rules</b></a> (a handout provided at Attorney Training on Chapter 16 Rules presented by the Iowa Judicial Branch).</li>\n<br />\n<li><b>UETA and Iowa Code § 602.1614</b><br />\nIowa, like nearly every other state, has enacted the Uniform Electronic Transactions Act (UETA). Iowa’s version of UETA is found in Iowa Code chapter 554D. The primary goal of UETA is to make electronic records and signatures legally equivalent to their paper counterparts.<br />\nUnder UETA, an electronic signature generally has the same legal effect as a “wet ink” signature. A “signature shall not be denied legal effect or enforceability solely because it is in electronic form.” Iowa Code § 554D.108(1). “If a law requires a signature, an electronic signature satisfies the law.” Iowa Code § 554D.108(4). The definition of “electronic signature” in the e-filing rules mirrors the definition under UETA. Compare Iowa Ct. R. 16.201 and Iowa Code § 554D.103(8). The e-filing rules provide clear authority for CSRU to file documents containing electronic signatures.</li>\n<br />\n<li><b>Electronic signatures in non-e-filing counties</b><br />\nIn contrast to e-filing counties, which are covered by the e-filing rules, it does not appear that the court has issued rules specifically addressing a litigant’s use of electronic signatures in a non-e-filing county. Thus, by implication, an argument could be made that the Iowa Supreme Court has not authorized the use of electronic records or signatures in non-e-filing counties. It is recommended that CSRU not file documents with electronic signatures in non-e-filing counties at this time.</li>\n<br />\n<li><b>Oaths, Affirmation of Verifications</b><br />\nDocuments requiring oaths, affirmations or verifications “may be either signed nonelectronically and scanned…or may be signed by an electronic process which accurately reproduces…the required signature.” Iowa Court Rule 16.306(3). Electronic notarization is specifically authorized in UETA. See Iowa Code § 554D.113. Note, though, that electronic notarization likely requires some special steps. For instance, in Iowa before a notary can notarize an electronic document, he or she has to select a tamper-evident technology and must notify the Secretary of State as to the selected technology. See Iowa Code § 9B.20.</li>\n<br />\n<li><b>Multiples Signatures</b><br />\nIowa Court Rule 16.306(5)(a) states that “[b]y filing the document the registered filer confirms that the content of the document is acceptable to all persons signing the document and all such persons consent to having their signatures appear on the document, and that the registered filer has notified the other signatories to the document that they must be registered filers for their signatures to be valid. Signatures on documents filed by governmental agencies… will be presumed valid, even if the signatory is not a registered filer.” (emphasis added).</li>\n</ul>\";i:1586789559336;s:1188:\"<p><b>The problem:</b> With the sheer number of Event Codes that are available on CSeF, there is frequently more than one Code that can be used for any particular document that is filed. If the wrong Event Code is used, the Clerk of Court will likely reject your filing. By and large, though, if you use an Event Code that makes sense, and if the Clerk is fine with the Code you are using, then you shouldn’t worry too much as to whether the Code you are using is the CORRECT Code.</p>\n<p><b>The solution:</b> Below are links to Event Codes that you should and should not use. If your Clerk wants you to use a different Even Code, do so.</p>\n<ul>\n<li>A list of Event Codes can be <a href=\"file://polkr3s5/PUBLIC/Imaging%202008\" target=\"_blank\"><img src=\"https://stcsruportalcli.blob.core.windows.net/csruportalwpcontent/2020/04/folder.png\"> <b>found here</b></a>.</li>\n<li>A list of Event Codes that CSRU is not supposed to use can be <a href=\"http://dhssp/csr/projects/efiling/attorneyworkgroup/Lists/Announcements/AllItems.aspx\" target=\"_blank\"><img src=\"https://stcsruportalcli.blob.core.windows.net/csruportalwpcontent/2020/04/sharepoint.png\"> <b>found here</b></a>.</li>\n</ul>\";i:1586789559586;s:1248:\"<p><b>Filing of Proposed Exhibits by CSRU Attorneys</b></p>\n<p>CSeF is not currently configured for filing proposed exhibits. Some judges will accept paper exhibits; others desire they be filed through EDMS. It is important to know your judges’ preferences in advance and comply with them.</p>\n<p><b>Paper</b> – Paper submission of proposed exhibits at hearings is the method preferred by CSRU at this time because filing through EDMS links the individual attorney to the case, which requires a later withdrawal.</p>\n<p><b>EDMS</b> – Filing proposed exhibits through EDMS is the method preferred by many judges. However, the individual attorney will be linked to the case and will need to later withdraw. In order to avoid having to withdraw from many cases, the attorney may want to wait until it is certain a hearing will be held before filing proposed exhibits. Be aware that proposed exhibits may be received by CSRU as external filings.</p>\n<ol>\n<li>For Document Category, select “PROPOSED DOCUMENTS.”</li>\n<li>For Document Type, select “EXHIBIT – PROPOSED.”</li>\n<li>After you select your document and click “Add,” a window will open up where you have to enter the Exhibit # and Exhibit Description.</li>\n</ol>\n\n\";i:1586789559874;s:707:\"<p>The timing of filing of an Income Withholding Order can be handled two different ways.</p>\n<p>You can wait until the Administrative Order and Approval order are approved by the judge and filed, then e-file the Income Withholding Order.</p>\n<p><b>OR</b></p>\n<p>You can file the Income Withholding Order in the same e-file packet as the Administrative Order and Proposed Approval Order. When you do this, the Income Withholding Order will have a file-stamped date of the day you file it. The judge-signed Approval Order may have a later file-stamped date. This is acceptable as long as an income withholding order/notice doesn’t go out to an employer before the Approval Order is signed and filed.</p>\";i:1586789560165;s:3200:\"<p><b>Indexing:</b> a term used by the Courts to refer to which party or attorney receives NEFs (Notifications of Electronic Filing) on that case. In other words, if the Clerk of Court indexes a party or an attorney to a particular case, then that individual will receive an emailed NEF every time there is a filing in that case.</p>\n<p><b>The problem:</b> In the beginning of electronic filing, there was no consistency as to whether Clerks of Court offices would index a CSRU attorney or a CSRU office or both to a particular case. It was quickly determined that individual CSRU attorneys should not be indexed to cases as this would result in a flood of email NEF’s, and it could cause problems when that particular attorney left the warm comfort of government employment.</p>\n<p><b>The solution:</b> CSRU conferred with the judicial branch, which in turn sent the following memo to all Clerks of Court offices – </p>\n<ul>\n<p><b>DATE:</b> March 6, 2013<br />\n<b>FROM:</b> Betty Buitenwerf<br />\n<b>RE:</b> Indexing CSRU to Cases</p>\n<p>CSRU attorneys do not need to be indexed to cases if they are filing through the CSRU interface (CSeF). On filings from CSeF in clerk review, the filer will display as the individual CSRU office (for example Sioux City, Spencer, etc.).</p>\n<p>In the event a CSRU atty needs to be indexed to a case, the atty will file through the Filer\'s Interface (eFlex), the filer will show as the attorney name, NOT the CSRU office name, and the clerk can then index the attorney as ATCS - Attorney for CSRU. It will not be necessary to link ATCS to the CSRU office on the Litigant screen in ICIS, as this will mean BOTH the atty and CSRU get notifications AND the documents filed.</p>\n<p>This is a bit of a departure from the standard process when other attorneys are indexed on a case. The reason for this comes down to notifications. When the CSRU office is notified, the documents are also sent to CSeF, and then ultimately their internal document storage/management system. Unless the atty files using their eFlex account, only the CSRU office will be indexed. This includes administrative orders, etc.</p>\n</ul>\n<p><b>What This Means For You:</b> Individual attorneys should not be indexed to cases unless they file on that case through EFLEX (the Court’s electronic filing interface). If your Clerk of Court questions you on this, refer them to the above memo. If you are indexed to a case individually and don’t want to be, you will probably need to file a motion and proposed order to withdraw from that case, though check with your Clerks of Court office because some offices will just de-index you at your request.  NOTE: if you are indexed to a case and a CSRU office is not, you need to make sure that an office gets indexed when you withdraw. Otherwise, nobody will receive the NEFS. Here is an example of a withdrawal that addresses both issues:</p>\n<p><img src=\"https://stcsruportalcli.blob.core.windows.net/csruportalwpcontent/2020/04/IN-THE-IOWA-DISTRICT-COURT-FOR-COUNTY-COUNTY.png\" /></p>\n<p><img src=\"https://stcsruportalcli.blob.core.windows.net/csruportalwpcontent/2020/04/IN-THE-IOWA-DISTRICT-COURT-FOR-COUNTY-COUNTY2.png\" /></p>\";i:1586789560421;s:2438:\"<p>Effective 3/7/15, JB added a Terms of Service web portal to its JB Guest wi-fi access. If you are having difficulty accessing the internet since this change, you will need to take the following steps:</p>\n<ol>\n<li>Open Internet Explorer</li>\n<li>Click the Tools button, and then click Internet Options</li>\n<li>Click the Connections tab, and then click LAN settings</li>\n<li>Un-check the Use a proxy server for your LAN check box</li>\n<li>Click OK and OK</li>\n<li>Close and re-open Internet Explorer</li>\n</ol>\n\n<hr />\n\n<ol>\n<li>Log on to your computer.</li>\n<li>Enable wi-fi by pressing the wi-fi button above the keyboard. (If the light on the button is orange, it means that the wi-fi is turned off.)</li>\n<li>In the lower right hand status bar, click on the icon of vertical bars.</li>\n<li>Click on JB guest.</li>\n<li>Enter password. Note that the password is the same for all counties and it changes monthly. It is in a MON-YEAR format. For example, FEB-2015 for February of this year. Consider whether you want the computer to remember your password or enter it each time as it will need to be changed monthly.</li>\n<li><span style=\"color: red;\">Open Internet Explorer. You may need to go to a site other than CSRU’s portal page to get the JB Terms of Service web portal page to load (e.g. Google).</span></li>\n<li><span style=\"color: red;\">Accept the terms of service.</span></li>\n</ol>\n\n<p><b>Optional Instructions</b></p>\n<ol>\n<li>Log on to your computer.</li>\n<li>Click Start, then Control Panel.</li>\n<li>Click on the Connect to the Internet option under Network and Internet.</li>\n<li>Select Wireless.</li>\n<li>Select JB guest.</li>\n<li>Enter password.</li>\n<li><span style=\"color: red;\">Open Internet Explorer. You may need to go to a site other than CSRU’s portal page to get the JB Terms of Service web portal page to load (e.g. Google).</span></li>\n<li><span style=\"color: red;\">Accept the terms of service.</span></li>\n</ol>\n\n<p><b>Changing Wi-Fi Password</b></p>\n<ol>\n<li>Click on wi-fi badge at the bottom right of screen (looks like vertical bars).</li>\n<li>Select “open network sharing center.”</li>\n<li>On the left side of the window that opens, select “manage wireless networks.”</li>\n<li>Double click on “JB Guest”.</li>\n<li>Select the Security tab.</li>\n<li>Delete the info in the Network Security Key field, and then enter the new password.</li>\n</ol>\";i:1586789560671;s:5722:\"<p> There are several ways to handle multi-caption filings, but accepted practice can vary by county. There are two types of multi-caption filings: 1) where you are filing on multiple cases in the same county and 2) where you are filing on multiple cases in different counties (which may include more than one case in the same county). These can require different processes.</p>\n<p><b>Multiple cases in the same county</b></p>\n<p><b>EDMS</b> – The court’s EDMS system is the easiest way to submit multi-caption filings for the same county. The process is the same whether there is a proposed order or not. However, because the documents come back to CSRU as external filings, which create more work for the office, it is not the method preferred by CSRU. This method is also not preferred because filing through EDMS links the individual attorney to the case, requiring the attorney to later withdraw. Note that if a case hasn’t already been converted for e-filing, a conversion request will need to be submitted to the clerk so that the case can be filed on.</p>\n<p>Once logged in to EDMS, select the “Existing Case” link.</p>\n<ol>\n<li>Choose the appropriate county, enter one of the case numbers, and enter one of the case participant’s last names. Then click on the “Add this case to your list” link.</li>\n<li>Repeat step 1 for each case you are filing on.</li>\n<li>Once all of the cases you need to file on are shown, click on the “File on these Cases” link.</li>\n<li>You can then create your packet. Unlike with CSeF, only one packet will need to be created.</li>\n</ol>\n\n<p><b>CSeF</b></p>\n<ol>\n<li>A packet will need to be created for each docket number. All documents except for the proposed order should be included in each packet. The proposed order should be included in only one of the packets. (If there is not a proposed order, you simply need to create a packet for each docket number and submit it. No special notes to the clerk are needed.)</li>\n<li>For the packets that do <b>not</b> include the proposed order, in the Memo field on the E-File Packet screen notice the clerk that the proposed order is being filed in X docket number: “Clerk—The proposed order is being filed in DRCV999999. Thank you.” (This will let the clerk know the lack of a proposed order is intentional so that the clerk does not reject the packet or have to contact your office to inquire about the “missing” order.)</li>\n<li>For the packet that includes the proposed order, in the Memo field on the E-File Packet screen ask the clerk to file the order in the other docket(s) once it is signed by judge: “Clerk—Please file the order in DRCV777777 [and…] once signed by the judge. Thank you.”</li>\n<li>You or someone in your office should then follow up to make sure the signed order has been filed in all the applicable docket numbers.</li>\n</ol>\n\n<p><b>Multiple cases in different counties</b></p>\n<p><b>Paper</b> – EDMS cannot be used to file on multiple cases in different counties at this time. The court’s official stance is that a paper filing is necessary in this situation. (However, attorneys have had success using CSeF in some counties.)</p>\n<ol>\n<li>The proposed order will need to be personally signed by a judge.</li>\n<li>Your office should submit a paper packet of all the documents to each county. If a packet is sent before the signed order, be sure to include a note letting the clerk know the order will be coming once signed by the judge.</li>\n<li>Judges are not supposed to give signed orders to attorneys. They are supposed to be given directly to the clerk for filing. This means the clerk for that county, if willing, can forward the file-stamped order to the other counties for filing, or your office can forward the file-stamped order with a brief explanation that it needs to be filed in those counties. It is important to be clear on whether the clerk or your office is doing the forwarding.</li>\n<li>You or someone in your office should follow up to make sure the signed order has been filed in all of the docket numbers.</li>\n</ol>\n\n<p><b>CSeF</b></p>\n<ol>\n<li>A packet will need to be created for each docket number. All documents except for the proposed order should be included in each packet. The proposed order should be included in only one of the packets. (If there is not a proposed order, you simply need to create a packet for each docket number and submit it. No special notes to the clerk are needed.)</li>\n<li>For the packets that do <b>not</b> include the proposed order, in the Memo field on the E-File Packet screen notice the clerk that the proposed order is being filed in X docket number: “Clerk—The proposed order is being filed in Osceola Co. DRCV999999. It will be forwarded for filing in this case once signed by the judge. Thank you.” (This will let the clerk know the lack of a proposed order is intentional so that the clerk does not reject the packet or have to contact your office to inquire about the “missing” order.)</li>\n<li>For the packet that includes the proposed order, in the Memo field on the E-File Packet screen you can ask the clerk to forward the order to the other counties for filing once signed by the judge: “Clerk—Please forward the order to the Emmet Co. clerk for filing in DRCV888888 [and…] once signed by the judge. Thank you.” Some clerks are not willing to forward the signed order. In that situation, your office will need to forward it with an explanation that it should be filed in those counties.</li>\n<li>You or someone in your office should then follow up to make sure the signed order has been filed in all the necessary docket numbers.</li>\n</ol>\";i:1586789560951;s:763:\"<p>When Submitting Proposed Order to Specific Judge:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>Use the yellow post it next to the individual document for anything you want added to the docket (such as a notation that something is an “ANSWER BY CSRU” as opposed to just an “other event”). Anything in the yellow field automatically becomes part of the entry unless removed by the clerk.</li>\n<li>Use the white field at the bottom for things you don’t want added to the docket, such as “for Judge Jones from the 1/2 CSRU hearing”. When you include this notation, some counties may want you to call the judge and let the judge know the order is in the judge’s queue.</li>\n<li>In either case, it is still important to remember to keep comments neutral and limited.</li>\n</ul>\";i:1586789561225;s:754:\"<ul>\n<li>Ankeny - ANKCSRU77</li>\n<li>Burlington - BURCSRU29</li>\n<li>Carroll - CARCSRU14</li>\n<li>Cedar Rapids - CDRCSRU57</li>\n<li>Clinton - CLNCSRU23</li>\n<li>Council Bluffs - CBLCSRU78</li>\n<li>Creston - CRECSRU88</li>\n<li>Davenport - DAVCSRU82</li>\n<li>Decorah - DECCSRU96</li>\n<li>Dubuque - DUBCSRU31</li>\n<li>EPICS - EPICSCS07</li>\n<li>Fort Dodge - FTDCSRU94</li>\n<li>Foster Care - FCRUFCS77</li>\n<li>Indianola - INDCSRU91</li>\n<li>Marshalltown - MTNCSRU64</li>\n<li>Mason City - MSNCSRU17</li>\n<li>N. Des Moines - DMNCSRU77</li>\n<li>Ottumwa - OTTCSRU90</li>\n<li>Pleasant Hill - PHLCSRU77</li>\n<li>S. Des Moines - DMSCSRU77</li>\n<li>Sioux City - SIOCSRU97</li>\n<li>Spencer - SPCCSRU21</li>\n<li>Waterloo - WTRCSRU07</li>\n</ul>\";i:1586789561515;s:907:\"<p> A proof of service should be included on a document as you did before. Your proof of service can show that some parties received notice by EDMS and others received notice by regular mail. (See SAMPLE). If you have any doubt at all about whether a party or attorney is a registered filer then you should serve notice on them by regular mail. You may be aware from past experience/receipt of filings that a party or attorney is a registered filer. You can also check EFLEX to see if a party is a registered filer. After you sign in to EFLEX, under the Cases tab you may enter the case number, county and participant’s last name then click Service List. However, this is case specific, which is not useful if the other individual has not yet filed anything in the case.</p>\n<p>Sample:</p>\n<p><img src=\"https://stcsruportalcli.blob.core.windows.net/csruportalwpcontent/2020/04/proofofservice.png\" /></p>\";i:1586789561765;s:2365:\"<p>Iowa Court Rule 16.411 specifies that “an original document, such as a will, mortgage document, birth certificate, foreign judgment, or other certified or verified document” which has been e-filed must be kept “for a period of no less than two years or until the conclusion of the case or the conclusion of the appeal … whichever is later.” An exception for authorized governmental agencies was added by a Supervisory Order filed on August 15, 2014. This exception allows for CSRU to destroy the original e-filed document after making “an unaltered image or reproduction of the original document.” This applies <b>ONLY</b> to e-filed documents.</p>\n<p><b>Direction provided by CSRU (pursuant to an email from Joe Finnegan dated October 2, 2014) as to record retention:</b></p>\n<p>Based on Iowa Code section 252B.17A (CSRU\'s imaging statute), follow these document retention procedures (effective immediately):</p>\n<ul>\n<li>For documents filed in a converted (e-filing) court county, retain all originals for 30 days after the document is imaged and indexed. This ensures the original is available should there be issues with the imaged copy. After 30-days, follow standard office procedures for document destruction.</li>\n<li>If a customer requests a copy of an e-filed document which was e-filed by CSRU, print a copy of the file-stamped version of the document from PODS and provide the copy to the customer.</li>\n<li>If a customer requests a copy of an e-filed document that was not e-filed by CSRU, suggest the customer obtain the copy from the courts. If the customer rejects this suggestion, provide the copy if it is available from PODS as long as CSRU is authorized to do so*. Also notify central office of this request using the CSRU - CSEF email address. This allows us to evaluate these situations and determine if additional instructions or changes to this policy are needed.</li>\n<p><b>*Note:</b> CSRU is not allowed to provide documents from confidential (sealed) court files. Some examples of confidential filings are terminations of parental rights, juvenile custody court orders, and temporary child support orders in dissolution files, if the court has not yet entered a final dissolution decree.</p>\n</ul>\n<p>For non-e-filed documents, continue to follow your offices procedures for the retention of paper documents.</p>\";i:1586789562022;s:1916:\"<p>Efiling rules make redaction of certain information mandatory. See Iowa Rule Civil Procedure 16.601 – 16.609.</p>\n<p>See <a href=\"http://sharept2010t/csru/Procedural%20Directives/2008/PD%2008-06/PD%2008-06%20Additional%20Confidentiality%20Updates%20Resulting%20in%20Changes%20to%20Forms%20and%20Procedures%20Revised.doc\" target=\"_blank\"><img src=\"https://stcsruportalcli.blob.core.windows.net/csruportalwpcontent/2020/04/word.png\"> <b>PD 08-06</b></a> for redacting instructions.</p>\n<p>The best method for redacting is to either:</p>\n<ol>\n<li>Manually redact. Do not make redactions on an original document. Make a photocopy of the original, then manually redact the information on the photocopy using a black marker. Lastly, make another photocopy so that no information can be read through the black marker.</li>\n<li>Electronically redact, then print the document and rescan the redacted version.</li>\n</ol>\n<p>Do not use the viewer in G360 to redact. Though it may appear that the tools are redacting the confidential information, the redaction layer is stripped when the document is called to CSeF and the confidential information is exposed.</p>\n<p>If you have to redact any confidential information on a document which the law requires you to file the original copy, you need to include Form 470-4412 (“In lieu of” form) as the first page of each document that was redacted. In the past, you may have included only one Form 470-4412 for each packet you were filing. With efiling, you must include this form for each document. For example, if you have 2 financial statements that are redacted, you will include Form 470-4412 twice, once with each financial statement.</p>\n<p>When the documents with the redactions are scanned into PODS, users should attach form 470-4412 at that time and save the document as the appropriate CSRU document name, then add “redacted” in the Notes field.</p>\";i:1586789562265;s:918:\"<p>When initiating a registration, CSRU must submit the notice of registration using the event code “civil original notice” in order to obtain the COC signature page. An original notice is <b>not</b> docketed in the court file. Therefore, the notice of registration does not show on ICIS and is not available to view on Iowa Courts Online.</p>\n<p>Upon receipt of the notice of registration back from COC with the clerk’s signature page, CSRU will send for service. Once both parties are served and CSRU is ready to present the proposed order confirming registration, CSRU will prepare the efiling packet and include a proposed order confirming registration, the returns of service, and the clerk-signed notice of registration using the event code “notice.” The COC will docket the notice of registration along with the returns of service and it will be available for viewing on Iowa Courts Online.</p>\n\n\n\";i:1586789562545;s:1236:\"<p><b>The problem:</b>\n<ul>\n<li>When a Clerk of Court office rejects a filing that you made through CSeF, you will receive the packet back on your CSeF Home page, and the status will indicate that it is rejected.</li>\n<li>BUT when a judge rejects one of your <b>proposed orders</b>, this rejection will NOT come back to the CSeF Home page. Instead, the judge MAY send an email through their EFLEX system to inform you why the proposed order is being rejected.</li>\n<li>Since the case in question is likely linked to the CSRU office instead of to the attorney (see - INDEXING OR LINKING TO CASES), if a judge sends an email rejection, it will go <b>to that CSRU office’s email account</b> and you will have to wait for the keeper of that account to forward the notification to you. This can be problematic if you are dealing with a time-sensitive issue.</li>\n</ul>\n<p><b>The solution:</b> there isn’t one. CSRU has mentioned this issue to the Judicial Branch, and they may address it in the future. In the meantime, be aware of the issue, make sure that you keep track of the proposed orders that you file, and make sure that the keeper of your office’s email account forwards rejection emails to you as soon as possible.</p>\";i:1586789562795;s:443:\"<p>The NEFs sent out with each document received by the COC have a section on them indicating which parties received notice of the document by the courts auto-notification systems, and which parties were not served by EDMS. If a party was given notice of the document by EDMS, there is no need for CSRU to mail a physical copy of the document to the party. CSRU will still need to mail copies to parties who did not receive notice by EDMS.</p>\";i:1586789563037;s:375:\"<p>All CSRU attorneys have access to the <a href=\"http://dhssp/csr/projects/efiling/attorneyworkgroup/default.aspx\" target=\"_blank\"><img src=\"https://stcsruportalcli.blob.core.windows.net/csruportalwpcontent/2020/04/sharepoint.png\"> <b>Efiling Attorney Workgroup’s SharePoint</b></a>. Several documents are stored here, including minutes from recent workgroup meetings.</p>\";}"
