                     "meta_value": {
                        "__cdata": "a:19:{i:1586793735007;s:3166:\"<p>It\'s important to remember that rules for establishment/modification are not always the same as those for enforcement. Iowa Administrative Code 441 - 99.2(3) states \"Any expected health insurance premiums shall be allowed as a deduction if the parent provides verification of this anticipated expense.\" Give the deduction for any health plan premium the payor or employer supplies regardless of whether the children or payor are currently enrolled in the plan or plans.</p>\n<p>Examples:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>The payor is currently enrolled in dental or vision insurance only but lists the premium cost for family dental, vision and basic health on the financial statement.<br />\nAllow the deduction for all three plans. A health benefit plan can consist of dental, vision, basic health or other types of medical coverage. The anticipated cost to the payor is the premium cost reported by the payor or employer.<br />\nIf the premium cost on the financial statement appears questionable, you may verify the cost through other sources.</li>\n<li>The payor or employer gives the cost of the premiums and they are greater than the 50% CCPA limits allowed for the employer to withhold.<br />\nAllow the deduction for the health insurance premiums supplied by the payor or employer. Do not consider CCPA limits when determining whether to order health insurance or when calculating net income for guidelines. CCPA limits apply only after an order is established or modified.<br />\nSend any guidelines questions to the <a href=\"mailto:csrupolicy-guidelines@dhs.state.ia.us\" target=\"_blank\"><b>CSRU - Policy Guidelines distribution list</b></a>.</li>\n</ul>\n\n<hr />\n\n<p><b>Dependent Health Insurance</b></p>\n<p>A parent is allowed the health insurance premium deduction if the parent\'s spouse provides the health insurance for the child(ren) for whom you are seeking support.</p>\n<p>When the obligor is to be court ordered to provide health insurance, and the dependent is not currently enrolled, and information is provided showing the employer offers more than one plan with different costs, use the lowest cost for the deduction.</p>\n<p>Verification of dependent health insurance must be provided in writing by the employer or on the pay stub.  A fax from the employer is acceptable.  HI cost could also be found on the EMPVER screen.  Pre-taxed HI deductions should be added into the gross income prior to using the tax calculators.</p>\n<p><b>Reasonable cost</b> is determined to be the amount the employer-related plan will/does cost.</p>\n<p>If it\'s know there is health insurance available, but no verification of cost received, a statement should be added in the COMMENTS section of the Guideline worksheet to the effect: \"No deduction given for health insurance as the cost was not provided.  Calculation could be revised if verification received within time frames.\"</p>\n<p>See Title 10, <a href=\"http://dhs.iowa.gov/sites/default/files/10-h.pdf\" target=\"_blank\"><img src=\"https://stcsruportalcli.blob.core.windows.net/csruportalwpcontent/2020/04/pdf.png\"> <b>Chapter H</b></a> for additional information regarding Dependent Health Insurance Premiums.</p>\";i:1586793735423;s:1026:\"<p>ICAR <span style=\"color: red;\">gets</span> health insurance information from a number of screens and centralizes that information into a common area on ICAR. The Medical Summary screens, otherwise known as MEDSUM, were developed for this purpose.</p>\n<p>In addition to centralizing health insurance information on the MEDSUM screens, ICAR:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>Monitors case-specific changes through on-line and batch processes,</li>\n<li>Assesses the potential of an obligor to provide health insurance coverage for the <span style=\"color: red;\">children and obligee, if ordered,</span> through an employer,</li>\n<li>Generates the appropriate medical forms.</li>\n</ul>\n<p>Once a high potential for the obligor to obtain health insurance is identified, ICAR automatically identifies cases that meet criteria for establishment, <span style=\"color: red;\">modification</span> and enforcement.</p>\n<p>ICAR also monitors the obligor’s and employer’s compliance with the medical support obligation once enforcement begins.</p>\";i:1586793735681;s:12544:\"<p>The MEDSUM, MEDSUM2 and <span style=\"color: red;\">MEDSUM3</span> screens are used to review the medical support information contained within a case.</p>\n<ul>\n<li>MEDSUM is more case and court order specific.</li>\n<li>MEDSUM2 provides additional information about the children associated with the MEDSUM screen.</li>\n<li><span style=\"color: red;\">MEDSUM3 provides employer information</span>.</li>\n</ul>\n<p>MEDSUM, with the exception of the <span style=\"color: red;\">ENF MED field, is a view-only screen. MEDSUM2 allows on-line entries in -</span></p>\n<ul>\n<li>ONLINE FORM,</li>\n<li>REPRINT,</li>\n<li>FORM STAT,</li>\n<li>ENR STAT and</li>\n<li>COMMENT fields.</li>\n</ul>\n<p>The entries on these screens serve as triggers for the medical support batch programs that automate most of the medical establishment and enforcement actions. In the process of identifying data to display on the screens, ICAR monitors the obligor\'s potential to provide health insurance coverage for the children.</p>\n<p>The MEDSUM3 screen displays all currently verified employers on a case and allows you to view which employer ICAR is currently processing for medical support establishment or enforcement. The MEDSUM3 screen also allows you to retrigger an employer for medical support establishment or enforcement.</p>\n<p>Changes made to various fields on specific ICAR screens (e.g., EMPVER, PAYEE) automatically update related fields on the MEDSUM and MEDSUM2 screens.  For example, ICAR transfers the date in the DATE HI AVAIL field on the EMPVER screen to the DATE HI AVAIL field on the MEDSUM screen.</p>\n<p>If you make an entry in the NPA REQUESTS MS ENF field on the PAYEE screen, ICAR automatically displays the same entry in the npa req ms enf field on the MEDSUM screen.</p>\n<p>The affected ICAR screens include: EMPVER, PAYEMP, COURTORD, OBLIG, OBLIGDST, PAYOR, PAYEE, CHILD, MEDICAL, MEDMTQ and INTERSTA.</p>\n<p>For detailed instructions on entering data on ICAR, see <a href=\"http://dhs.iowa.gov/sites/default/files/11-I.pdf\" target=\"_blank\"><img src=\"https://stcsruportalcli.blob.core.windows.net/csruportalwpcontent/2020/04/pdf.png\"> <b>Employees Manual, Chapter 11-I, Medical Support</b></a>, <b>Recording a Medical Support Obligation</b>.</p>\n\n<hr />\n\n<h4>MEDSUM Screen</h4>\n<p><img src=\"https://stcsruportalcli.blob.core.windows.net/csruportalwpcontent/2020/04/medsum.gif\" /></p>\n<p>The MEDSUM screens draw data from a variety of screens throughout ICAR. The information pulled from the COURTORD screen helps determine the number of MEDSUM screens that display. It is possible to display up to three MEDSUM screens per case. When you access the MEDSUM screens, the on-line message that displays describes the type of screen you are viewing. For example:</p>\n<ul>\n<li><b>C.O. THAT ORDERS H.I.</b> (or on MEDSUM2, DEPEND ASSOC TO C.O. THAT ORDERS H.I.): This online message indicates that the case has an associated <b>court order that includes provisions for health insurance.</b> If more than two court orders exist meeting this criteria, ICAR highlights and displays a \"Y\" in the MORE? field.</li>\n<li><b>C.O. WITH NO H.I. ORDERED</b> (or on MEDSUM2, DEPEND ASSOC TO C.O. WITH NO H.I. ORDERED): This online message indicates that the case has an associated <b>court order that does not include provisions for health insurance.</b> If more than two court orders exist meeting this criteria, ICAR highlights and displays a \"Y\" in the MORE? field.</li>\n<li><b>NOT ASSOC TO CURRENT C.O.</b> (or on MEDSUM2, DEPEND NOT ASSOC TO CURRENT C.O.): This online message indicates that the case has children who are <b>not associated to any current court order.</b> Two examples of when this screen may display are when: 1) paternity is not established; or 2) all court ordered obligations have ended and the children have not emancipated.</li>\n</ul>\n<p>See <a href=\"http://dhs.iowa.gov/sites/default/files/11-I.pdf\" target=\"_blank\"><img src=\"https://stcsruportalcli.blob.core.windows.net/csruportalwpcontent/2020/04/pdf.png\"> <b>Employees Manual, Chapter 11-I, Medical Support</b></a>, <i>Identifying Existing Medical Support</i> for more information.</p>\n\n<hr />\n\n<h4>MED SUM 2 Screen</h4>\n<p><img src=\"https://stcsruportalcli.blob.core.windows.net/csruportalwpcontent/2020/04/medsum2.gif\" /></p>\n<p>MEDSUM2 identifies:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>Whether the obligor is court ordered to provide health insurance for each <span style=\"color: red;\">child</span> listed.</li>\n<li>Whether the obligor has a high potential of obtaining health insurance.</li>\n<li>The date medical forms first generate, the status of the generation of the forms, and the date <span style=\"color: red;\">we receive</span> medical information.</li>\n<li>The enrollment status of each child.</li>\n<li>The person providing the policy.</li>\n</ul>\n\n<h4>Fields on the MEDSUM 2 screen</h4>\n<ul>\n<li><b>HI POT:</b> ICAR selects cases with a high potential for the obligor to obtain health insurance coverage and displays an entry to indicate the potential.<br />\nRefer to Determination of High Potential for more information.</li>\n<li><b>HI ORD:</b> ICAR  displays a \"Y\" to indicate health insurance coverage is ordered for a child or an \"N\" to indicate health insurance coverage is not ordered.  ICAR transfers the entry from the HI ORDERED (Y/N/U) field on the OBLIGDST screen.  The HI ORD field is blank on MEDSUM2 until you update the HI ORDERED (Y/N/U) field on the OBLIGDST screen.</li>\n<li><b>FORM STAT:</b> Valid entries for this field are \"0\" (zero), \"2,\" \"4\" or \"5.\" (Valid worker entries are \"0\" or \"5.\"  For more information, refer to the information that follows on the ENR STAT field.)  The entry in this field identifies the status of the generation of forms used to enforce health insurance.  The valid entries for this field follow.\n<ul>\n<li><b>\"0\"</b> (no forms generate) - If you enter an \"N\" in the ENR STAT field, ICAR displays a \"0\" in the FORM STAT field.  This entry means no information is available or it is not necessary to generate medical forms.   When you add a medical record on the MEDICAL screen, ICAR displays an \"E\" in the ENR STAT field and an \"0\" in the FORM STAT field.</li>\n<li><b>\"2\"</b> (forms generate) - A \"2\" displays when forms 470-3818, National Medical Support Notice and 470-2743, Employer Medical Support Information generate for the first time. ICAR issues a narrative (MED 7) to document the generation of these forms.</li>\n<li><b>\"4\"</b>  ICAR changes the \"2\" to a \"4\" and issues a calendar flag at EPICS 30 days after ICAR established a HI POT of \"A\" telling you to contact the employer to check on the status of the children\'s enrollment in a health insurance plan.<br />\nICAR generates another calendar flag at EPICS 60 days after ICAR established a HI POT of \"A\" when a \"P\" displays in the ENR STAT field. (\"P\" = insurance pending a determination by the insurer.)</li>\n<li>\"5\" (forms generate later) - When the child is temporarily ineligible for health insurance coverage, enter the date health insurance is available in the dep hi avail field on the EMPVER screen. Next, enter a \"5\" in the FORM STAT field. ICAR allows you to enter a \"5\" in the FORM STAT field when you enter an \"I\" in the ENR STAT field. You must enter a date on the USER INPUT CALENDAR FLAG screen that displays after entering a \"5\" in the FORM STAT field. ICAR issues a narrative (MED 10) to document that health insurance coverage is available at a later date.  When the child is eligible for health insurance, based on the date in the DEP HI Avail field, ICAR generates from 470-3818, National Medical Support Notice and 470-2743, Employer Medical Support Information.</li>\n</ul></li>\n<li><b>SENT DATE:</b> This is the date form 470-3818, Medical Support Notice and form 270-2743, Employer Medical Support Information generated. This date stays in this field until medical support enforcements stops for this employer. If you regenerate the medical forms, the original date continues to display in this field. The field is blank when no forms generate for the employer.</li>\n<li><b>ENR STAT:</b> You completed this field when you receive part A or B of form 470-3818, National Medical Support Notice and form 470-2743, Employer Medical Support Information. Valid worker entries for this field are \"N\", \"W\", \"A\", \"P\" or \"I\". **   ICAR displays an \"E\" in the ENR STAT field when a medical policy is added on the MEDICAL screen and its sub screens.  Valid entries for the ENR STAT field are as follows:\n<ul>\n<li><b>N:</b> No health insurance offered through this employer.</li>\n<li><b>E:</b> The child is enrolled in health insurance coverage offered through the employer. <i>This entry cannot be manually entered</i>.</li>\n<li><b>I:</b> The child is ineligible for health insurance coverage.<br />\nWhen you enter an \"I\" in the ENR STAT field, ICAR requires you to enter a \"5\" or a \"0\" (zero) in the FORM STAT field to indicate whether the child’s ineligibility is temporary or permanent.<br />\nEnter a \"0\" when ineligibility is permanent, e.g., the child is ineligible due to a preexisting condition, or the obligor is ineligible which prevents the children from becoming enrolled.\n<br />\nEnter \"5\" when ineligibility is temporary, e.g., the child is not eligible for enrollment until the obligor has been employed for 90 days.</li>\n<li><b>W:</b> Withholding limits <span style=\"color: red;\">(50% CCPA)</span> prevent the enrollment of the child in a health insurance plan.</li>\n<li><b>A:</b> The health insurance plans offered by the employer are not accessible to the child.</li>\n<li><b>P:</b> Health insurance enrollment is pending a decision by the insurer.</li>\n</ul></li>\n</ul>\n<p>Click <a href=\"http://intra/csruhandbooks/HANDBOOKS/Medical/Screens/MEDSUM2%20Reference%20Card.doc\" target=\"_blank\"><img src=\"https://stcsruportalcli.blob.core.windows.net/csruportalwpcontent/2020/04/word.png\"> <b>here**</b></a> to access a reference chart (printable, WORD document) for updating ICAR based on responses checked on PART A or B of Form 470-3718, National Medical Support Notice.</ul>\n<ul>\n<li><b>RCVD DATE:</b> Indicates the date we received medical information. <span style=\"color: red;\">ICAR updates this field when you make an entry in the ENR STAT field.</span></li>\n<li><b>PROVIDER PA/PE/PR:</b> ICAR displays a \"Y\" in the appropriate section of this field to identify who provides health insurance coverage for the children:\n<ul>\n<li>the payor,</li>\n<li>the payee,</li>\n<li>a third party,</li>\n<li>or the payor through a private policy.</li>\n</ul></li>\n<li><b>END DATE:</b> ICAR displays the same entry in the end date field that displays on the INSURANCE DEPENDENT LIST (a subscreen of the MEDICAL screen). This field is child specific.</li>\n<li><b>COMMENT:</b> Enter comments about health insurance coverage for the children. There is a comment line for each child whose name displays on the MEDSUM2 screen.</li>\n<li><b>REPRINT?:</b> When you enter a \"Y\" in the REPRINT field, ICAR generates form 470-3818, National Medical Support Notice, and form 470-2743, Employer Medical Support Information, in batch overnight at EPICS.</li>\n<li><b>ONLINE FORM?:</b> Enter a \"Y\" to generate an online copy of form 470-3818, National Medical Support Notice, and form 470-2743, Employer Medical Support Information. You can only enter a \"Y\" after forms generate with a HI POT of \"1\".</li>\n</ul>\n\n<hr />\n\n<h4>Medical Insurance Screen</h4>\n<p><img src=\"https://stcsruportalcli.blob.core.windows.net/csruportalwpcontent/2020/04/medical.gif\" /></p>\n<p>When you enter health insurance coverage information on the MEDICAL screens, ICAR updates the information on the MEDSUM and MEDSUM2 screens. The MEDSUM2 screen displays an \"E\" in the ENR STAT field and the date you added the medical record. The screen also indicates who provides the health insurance policy (payor, payee or a third party).</p>\n<p> When health insurance terminates, enter a \"Y\" in the END DATE field. ICAR updates fields on the MEDSUM screens to reflect the change. (If the end date is in the future, ICAR does not clear the MEDSUM screens until the date arrives.)</p>\n<p>For specific instructions for entering a health insurance policy on ICAR, see <b>Employees Manual, <a href=\"http://dhs.iowa.gov/sites/default/files/11-I.pdf\" target=\"_blank\"><img src=\"https://stcsruportalcli.blob.core.windows.net/csruportalwpcontent/2020/04/pdf.png\"> Title 11, Chapter I</a>, <i>Recording Health Insurance Coverage</i></b>.</p>\";i:1586793735899;s:736:\"<p>ICAR identifies cases with a high potential for the obligor to obtain health insurance through the MEDSUM batch programs. The MEDSUM batch programs run nightly. The batch programs detect changes made to a case during the day and determines if ICAR needs to change the current HI POT code. ICAR issues a narrative (MED 16) to document when there is no longer a high potential for the obligor to obtain insurance.</p>\n<p>For additional information see <a href=\"http://dhs.iowa.gov/sites/default/files/11-I.pdf\" target=\"_blank\"><img src=\"https://stcsruportalcli.blob.core.windows.net/csruportalwpcontent/2020/04/pdf.png\"> <b>Employees Manual Chapter 11-I</b></a>, <b>Narratives</b>, and <b>Batch Processing for Medical Support</b>.</p>\";i:1586793736141;s:3124:\"<p>Cases that do not meet selection criteria are not processed for <span style=\"color: red;\">the medical process</span>. When ICAR bypasses a child for medical enforcement or establishment, either an \"N\" displays in the HI POT field on the MEDSUM2 screen, or the field is blank.</p>\n\n<ul>\n<li><b>CHILD2 screen - EST BY-PASS field</b><br />\nAn entry in the EST BY-PASS field for a child prevents that child from being processed for the medical process.  If two children display on the same MEDSUM2 screen and only one child has an entry in the EST BY-PASS field, that child is by-passed, but processing continues for the other child.</li>\n<li><b>Emancipated children</b><br />\nChildren who have an emancipation date that is the same or less than the current date do not display on the MEDSUM2 screen.</li>\n<li><b>Obligation ended</b><br />\nIf the end date for an obligation is the same or less than the current date, the court docket number appears on the MEDSUM screen.  If all obligations have ended, ICAR displays a \"Y\" in the OBLIG ENDED field on the MEDSUM screen.</li>\n<li><b>Obligation not distributed</b><br />\nThe child is not distributed to the court ordered obligation.  OBLIGDST screen displays “U” or blank space under hi ordered field. The child’s name meeting this criterion does not display on the MEDSUM2 screen.</li>\n<li><b>Iowa Workforce Development</b><br />\nWhen the only employer is Iowa Workforce Development, <span style=\"color: red;\">Defense Finance and Accounting (DFAS), or Social Security Administration (SSA),</span> medical forms will not generate and the case is not selected for high potential.</li>\n<li><b>VEMPLOY2 screen - BYPASS EMPLOYER field</b><br />\nWhen a \'Y\' displays in the bypass employer field on the VEMPLOY2 screen for an employer, ICAR bypasses cases connected to this employer for the establishment or enforcement of health insurance.</li>\n<li><b>VEMPLOY2 screen - BYPASS MEDICAL field</b><br />\nWhen a \'Y\' displays in the bypass medical field on the VEMPLOY2 screen, ICAR bypasses cases connected to this employer for the establishment or enforcement of health insurance.</li>\n<li><b>MEDMTQ screen - STAYED or GRANTED field</b><br />\nWhen a \'Y\' displays in either the stayed or granted field on the MEDMTQ screen, ICAR bypasses cases for the enforcement of health insurance. A calendar flag issues when there is an entry in either the stayed or granted field and a new employer is verified.</li>\n<li><b>EMPVER screen - NMBA field</b><br />\nThe MEDSUM process bypasses cases when an ‘N’ displays in the dep hi avail field; when a future date displays in the date hi avail field; nmba field displays ‘Y’; or the byp emp  field displays ‘Y.’</li>\n<li><b>MEDICAL screen</b><br />\nWhen the children are already enrolled in a health insurance policy, the MEDSUM process bypasses a case.</li>\n<li><b>HIUPDATE screen</b><br />\nThe health ins field on the COURTORD screen displays a ‘Y,’ review the HIUPDATE screen. MEDSUM processing is bypassed when the party ordered to provide health insurance is either the PAYEE or SHARED.</li>\n</ul>\";i:1586793736376;s:5533:\"<p>ICAR selects cases with a high potential for the obligor to obtain health insurance. The high potential identified for the case depends on which selection criteria is met.</p>\n<p>Selection criteria includes:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>The case is active and the account type is appropriate. When the case account type is 12, a \"Y\" or \"C\" must display in the NPA REQUESTS MS ENF field on the PAYEE screen.</li>\n<li>The case has a verified employer (or) the DEP HI AVAIL field on the EMPVER screen is blank or displays a \'Y\'.</li>\n<li>When there is not a verified employer, regular payments have been received equal to the child support obligation for two months previous to the current month.</li>\n<li>The case has a court order for support.</li>\n<li>Health insurance is included in the court order.</li>\n<li>The ENF MED field on the MEDSUM screen is blank or displays a \'Y\' for interstate cases when IA is the responding state.</li>\n</ul>\n<p><b>Note:</b> When an obligee provides dependent health insurance, and you enter the policy information on the MEDICAL screen, the case is not selected for high potential. The MEDSUM batch programs will not refer the case for establishment, modification or enforcement.</p>\n<p>When the batch programs run and ICAR selects a case for high potential, ICAR enters a code in the HI POT field on the MEDSUM2 screen.  When the case does not meet high potential criteria, the HI POT field remains blank.  Entry of the HI POT code either:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>Issues a calendar flag at EPICS to determine if health insurance is available and whether to generate medical forms to enforce the medical language in the order,</li>\n<li>Sends a calendar flag to the worker as notification of an action to be completed, including a referral for modification or establishment, or</li>\n<li>Generates a health insurance questionnaire to the obligor.</li>\n</ul>\n<p>For additional information, see <a href=\"http://dhs.iowa.gov/sites/default/files/11-I.pdf\" target=\"_blank\"><img src=\"https://stcsruportalcli.blob.core.windows.net/csruportalwpcontent/2020/04/pdf.png\"> <b>Employees Manual Title 11 Chapter I</b></a>, <b>Batch Processing for Medical Support</b>.</p>\n\n<hr />\n\n<p><b>HI POT Codes</b></p>\n<ul>\n<li><b>HI POT field = A:</b> An \"A\" displays when there is a verified employer and health insurance is court ordered. <span style=\"color: red;\">EPICS determines if and when to send form 470-3818, <i>National Medical Support Notice</i>.</span></li>\n<li><b>HI POT field = 1:</b> EPICS changes the entry of \"A\" to \"1\" when it is appropriate to generate and send medical enforcement forms to the employer.<br />\nWhen you enter a \"1,\" form 470-3818, National Medical Support Notice, and form 470-2743, Employer Medical Support Information, generate the next day at EPICS.<br />\nA \"2\" displays in the form stat field on the MEDSUM2 screen and the date the forms generate displays in the sent date field.</li>\n<li><b>HI POT field = 2:</b> This entry identifies cases that currently have a verified employer and an existing court order, but the provision of health insurance is not court ordered.<br />\nICAR issues a calendar flag (MED 6) telling you to review the case for a possible referral to modify the order.</li>\n<br />\n<p><b>Note:</b> You must verify whether the obligor has medical coverage available when ICAR establishes a hi pot of \"2\" or \"3\".  If health insurance is not available, enter an \'N\' in the enr stat field on MEDSUM2.</p>\n<li><b>HI POT field = 3:</b> This entry identifies cases that have a verified employer but no active court order exists.<br />\nICAR issues a calendar flag (MED 7) telling you to review the case for possible referral to establish an order.</li>\n<br />\n<p><b>Note:</b> You must verify whether the obligor has medical coverage available when ICAR establishes a hi pot of \"2\" or \"3\".  If health insurance is not available, enter an \'N\' in the enr stat field on MEDSUM2.</p>\n<li><b>HI POT field = 4:</b> This entry identifies cases that do not have a verified employer, health insurance is court-ordered and the obligor has made regular payments on the case (payments that equal current support for the 2 months previous to the current month).<br />\nWhen there is a verified address for the obligor, ICAR generates form 470-0413, Obligor Insurance Questionnaire, in overnight batch.  Send this form to the obligor.  ICAR issues a narrative (CASE 47) to document that the form was sent to the obligor, and a calendar flag (CASE 12) 15 days in the future to remind you to check for the return of the form.<br />\nWhen there is no verified address for the obligor, ICAR issues a narrative (MED 18) to document that the form was not sent.<br />\nForm 470-0413 generates once every 6 months when the criteria remains the same.</li>\n<li><b>HI POT field = N:</b> The case does not have a high potential for the obligor to obtain health insurance coverage.</li>\n<br />\n<p><b>Note:</b> The children that display on the MEDSUM2 screen may have different HI POT entries if the selection criteria is fully met for one child on the case but not met for another child. For example, an entry in the est by-pass field on the CHILD2 screen causes the child to be by-passed for high potential processing. If circumstances change so that the child who was previously bypassed now meets HI POT selection criteria, forms do not generate for that child until ICAR completes the forms cycle for the child who met the selection criteria.</p>\n</ul>\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\";i:1586793736595;s:486:\"<p>When a case meets the selection criteria for enforcement, ICAR displays an \"A\" in the HI POT field, and issues a calendar flag to EPICS. EPICS <span style=\"color: red;\">determines if and when</span> health insurance is available.</p>\n<p>If health insurance is available, EPICS enters a \"1\" in the HI POT field.  Forms 470-3818, National Medical Support Notice, and 470-2743, Employer Medical Support Information generate in batch overnight at EPICS and are sent to the employer.</p>\";i:1586793736829;s:2387:\"<p>The definition of insurance coverage is fairly broad. Iowa Code section 252E.1 defines a health benefit plan as a policy for the purpose of covering medical expenses. \"These expenses may include but are not limited to hospital, surgical, major medical insurance, dental, optical, prescription drugs, office visits, or any combination of these or any other comparable health care expenses.\"</p>\n\n<p><b>Plan Selection</b></p>\n<p>Once the National Medical Support Notice issues to an employer, an employer may ask about selecting a plan or plans for the children. Determine whether the payor is enrolled in employment-related health insurance that also offers dependent coverage.</p>\n<ul>\n<li>When the payor is enrolled in employment-related health insurance that offers dependent coverage:\n<ul>\n<li>The employer enrolls the children in the same insurance. If the payor is enrolled in only a dental or vision policy, the employer enrolls the children in the same policy. CSRU cannot instruct the employer to enroll the children in a basic health insurance policy instead of or in addition to the other plan. If the employer mentions that the children will be enrolled in a basic health insurance plan, tell the employer we will note that on the case.</li>\n</ul></li>\n<li>When the payor is not enrolled in any health insurance plan and:\n<ul>\n<li>The employer offers only one plan in which dependent coverage is available, the employer enrolls the children, and payor if necessary, in that plan.</li>\n<li>The employer offers more than one plan in which dependent coverage is available, determine if more than one plan is accessible. If not, the employer enrolls the children in the one plan that is accessible.</li>\n<li>The employer offers more than one plan in which dependent coverage is available and accessible, the employer determines which plan offers basic coverage at the lowest cost to the payor. The employer enrolls the children in that plan.</li>\n<li>The employer offers more than one plan in which dependent coverage is available and accessible, the employer has determined that more than one plan provides basic coverage, the plans providing basic coverage do not differ in cost to the payor, EPICS contacts the payee to determine which plan the payee prefers. See When the Payee Must Select a Health Insurance Plan for more information.</li>\n</ul></li>\n</ul>\";i:1586793737063;s:349:\"<p><a href=\"http://intra/csruhandbooks/HANDBOOKS/Medical/Contents/SelectionOfHealthInsPlan/Selecting%20a%20Health%20Insurance%20Plan%20Flowchart%20(Enforcement).doc\" target=\"_blank\"><img src=\"https://stcsruportalcli.blob.core.windows.net/csruportalwpcontent/2020/04/word.png\"> <b>Enforcement - Selecting a Health Insurance Plan Flowchart</b></a></p>\";i:1586793737299;s:2037:\"<p>The payee is asked to select a plan when the payor is not enrolled in health insurance and the payor’s employer offers more than one plan in which:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>dependent coverage is available and accessible,</li>\n<li>the employer has determined that more than one plan provides basic coverage, and</li>\n<li>the plans providing basic coverage do not differ in cost to the payor.</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p><b>Example</b></p>\n<p>The following example explains one situation in which the payee must choose a plan. Because Plan A and Plan B meet all the criteria including no difference in cost to the payor (no cost in this example), the payee is asked to choose.</p>\n[ninja_tables id=\"1464\"]\n<p>The payee must select between Plan A and Plan B.</p>\n\n<p><b>Step 1:</b></p>\n<p>EPICS sends a <i><b>letter</b></i> with the health insurance plan descriptions to the payee to select between Plan A and Plan B.</p>\n<ul>\n<li>If there is no mailing address for the payee but a telephone number is available, contact the payee to get the mailing address.</li>\n<li>If there is no mailing address or telephone number for the payee, narrate that the Unit is unable to contact the payee. Contact the plan administrator to enroll the dependents and payee, if ordered, in the employer’s default plan, if any, or the plan with the lowest deductibles and co-payments.</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p><b>Step 2:</b></p>\n<p>Set a calendar flag ten business days from the date the letter is sent to the payee to determine whether the payee responded.</p>\n\n<p><b>Step 3:</b></p>\n<p>If there is no response from the payee, call the payee to identify the plan selected.</p>\n<ul>\n<li>If the payee chose a plan, contact the plan administrator to enroll the children and payee, if ordered, in the plan selected.</li>\n<li>If there is no response from the payee, contact the plan administrator and tell them to enroll the children and payee, if ordered, in the employer’s default plan, if any, or the plan with the lowest deductibles and co-payments.</li>\n</ul>\";i:1586793737556;s:970:\"<p><a href=\"http://intra/csruhandbooks/HANDBOOKS/Medical/Contents/ContestingTheEnforcement/Contesting%20Medical%20Support%20Enforcement%20Flowchart.doc\" target=\"_blank\"><img src=\"https://stcsruportalcli.blob.core.windows.net/csruportalwpcontent/2020/04/word.png\"> <b>Contesting Medical Support Enforcement Informal Conference and Motion to Quash Flowchart</b></a></p>\n\n<p><a href=\"http://intra/csruhandbooks/HANDBOOKS/Medical/Contents/ContestingTheEnforcement/sample%20affidavit.doc\" target=\"_blank\"><img src=\"https://stcsruportalcli.blob.core.windows.net/csruportalwpcontent/2020/04/word.png\"> <b>Sample affidavit for plan administrators</b></a></p>\n\n<p><a href=\"http://intra/csruhandbooks/HANDBOOKS/Medical/Contents/ContestingTheEnforcement/Health%20Insurance%20Policy%20Information%20Worksheet.doc\" target=\"_blank\"><img src=\"https://stcsruportalcli.blob.core.windows.net/csruportalwpcontent/2020/04/word.png\"> <b>Health Insurance Information Worksheet</b></a></p>\";i:1586793737798;s:4376:\"<h4>Policy Clarification</h4>\n<p>The Medical team in Central Office has received a number of questions regarding how to update the hi ordered (y/n/u) field on the OBLIGDST screen when a payor is ordered to pay cash medical support (MS). Procedural Directive 09-07 provided instructions on how to update the COURTORD screen and HIUPDATE screen when a parent is ordered to provide cash MS. However, it did not address how to update the hi ordered (y/n/u) field on the OBLIGDST screen when adding the MS obligation to the OBLIG screen. The following instructions to clarify this for you.</p>\n<p>When <b><i>neither</i></b> parent is ordered to provide a <b>health benefit plan</b> (HI), but the <b>payor</b> is ordered to pay <b>cash medical support</b> (MS), take the following steps:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>On the COURTORD screen, update the hi/ms ordered field with a \"Y\".</li>\n<li>On the HIUPDATE screen, enter a \"N\" in the health ins (y/n) field, and enter a \"Y\" in the cash med support (y/n) field. Place a \"Y\" next to PAYOR under the party ordered to pay casH medical support? field.</li>\n<li>On the OBLIG screen, enter the cash MS obligation.</li>\n<li>On the OBLIGDST screen, update the hi ordered (y/n/u) field with an \"N\" for the children included in the order. Distribute the cash MS obligation amount according to the language in the court order.</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>When a <b>payee</b> is ordered to provide a <b>health benefit plan</b> (HI), and the <b>payor</b> is ordered to pay <b>cash medical support</b> (MS), take the following steps:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>On the COURTORD screen, update the hi/ms ordered field with a \"Y\".</li>\n<li>On the HIUPDATE screen, enter a \"Y\" in the health ins (y/n) field and enter a \"Y\" in the cash med support (y/n) field. Place a \"Y\" next to PAYEE under the party ordered to provide health ins? field.  Place a \"Y\" next to PAYOR under the party ordered to pay casH medical support? field.</li>\n<li>On the OBLIG screen, enter the cash MS obligation.</li>\n<li>On the OBLIGDST screen, update the hi ordered (y/n/u) field with an \"Y\" for the children included in the order. Distribute the cash MS obligation amount according to the language in the court order.</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>When a <b>payor</b> is ordered to provide a <b>health benefit plan</b> (HI), and the payor is also ordered to pay <b>cash medical support</b> (MS), take the following steps:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>On the COURTORD screen, update the hi/ms ordered field with a \"Y\".</li>\n<li>On the HIUPDATE screen, enter a \"Y\" in the health ins (y/n) field and enter a \"Y\" in the cash med support (y/n) field. Place a \"Y\" next to PAYOR under the party ordered to provide health ins? field. Place a \"Y\" next to PAYOR under the party ordered to pay casH medical support? field.</li>\n<li>On the OBLIG screen, enter the cash MS obligation.</li>\n<li>On the OBLIGDST screen, update the hi ordered (y/n/u) field with an \"Y\" for the children included in the order. Distribute the cash MS obligation amount according to the language in the court order.</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>When a <b>payor</b> is ordered to provide a <b>health benefit plan</b> (HI), and the <b>payee</b> is ordered to pay <b>cash medical support</b> (MS), take the following steps:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>On the COURTORD screen, update the hi/ms ordered field with a \"Y\".</li>\n<li>On the HIUPDATE screen, enter a \"Y\" in the health ins (y/n) field and enter a \"Y\" in the cash med support (y/n) field. Place a \"Y\" next to PAYOR under the party ordered to provide health ins? field. Place a \"Y\" next to PAYEE under the party ordered to pay casH medical support? field.</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>When a <b>payee</b> is ordered to provide a <b>health benefit plan</b> (HI), and the <b>payee</b> is ordered to pay <b>cash medical support</b> (MS), take the following steps:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>On the COURTORD screen, update the hi/ms ordered field with a \"Y\".</li>\n<li>On the HIUPDATE screen, enter a \"Y\" in the health ins (y/n) field and enter a \"Y\" in the cash med support (y/n) field. Place a \"Y\" next to PAYEE under the party ordered to provide health ins? field. Place a \"Y\" next to PAYEE under the party ordered to pay casH medical support? field.</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>As always, if you have questions about this clarification please contact the <a href=\"mailto:csrupolmed@dhs.state.ia.us\" target=\"_blank\"><b>Medical Policy Team via e-mail</b></a>.</p>\";i:1586793738054;s:5450:\"<p>The OTHER field under “PARTY ORDERED TO PROVIDE HEALTH INS?” on the HIUPDATE screen was designed for orders requiring someone other than the payor or payee to provide health insurance. Because an entry in the OTHERfield stops the Medsum program from attempting to enforce health insurance through the payor’s employer, the OTHERfield has also become a “work around” for orders that contain health insurance language that CSRU is unable to enforce. This page describes the situations in which the OTHERfield can be used as a “work around.” Refer to the “Entries to make on ICAR when using the “OTHER” field” section at the bottom of this page for the specific ICAR entries.</p>\n\n<p><b>No Party Ordered to Enroll the Child(ren)</b></p>\n<p>Some orders explain how the expense of a policy will be divided or the circumstances under which someone is to provide the coverage, but do not specifically identify the party ordered to enroll the child(ren). If a specific person is not ordered to enroll the child(ren) in a health insurance policy, CSRU cannot enforce the health insurance part of the order.</p>\n\n<p><b>Examples:</b></p>\n<ul>\n<li>\"The respondent shall be responsible for one half of the cost of obtaining health insurance for the minor child.\"</li>\n<li>\"Each parent shall determine what is the most reasonable insurance cost available for coverage of their minor children. That additional cost of coverage of medical insurance to maintain the minor children on either party’s policy shall be considered an expense that will be shared by the parties and either parent who is not making the insurance payment shall reimburse the other parent for one half of the cost of the insurance to cover the minor children.\"</li>\n</ul>\n<p><b>Note:</b> <i>Though the parents are ordered to determine “the most reasonable insurance cost,” neither parent is ordered to enroll the child(ren). CSRU does not have to attempt to determine the meaning of “the most reasonable insurance cost.”</i></p>\n\n<p><b>“Either Party” Ordered to Enroll the Child(ren)</b></p>\n<p>When “either party,” “either parent,” or “whichever party,” is ordered to enroll the child(ren), CSRU cannot enforce the order. This type of language is not specific enough to enforce against the payor.</p>\n<p><b>Examples:</b></p>\n<ul>\n<li>“Should either party obtain employment where health insurance is available at a reasonable cost, they shall be required to obtain the medical insurance coverage for the children.”</li>\n<br />\n<p><b>Note:</b> “Reasonable cost” was also not defined in this 2010 order.</p>\n<li>“Health insurance (including medical, dental and vision) for the benefit of (child) shall be carried by whichever parent has the ability to cover (child) under either a private or group policy.”</li>\n</ul>\n<p>Keep in mind that orders must be read holistically. Other sentences in the order may clarify the meaning of phrases like “either party.” If other language in the order clarifies when a specific party is ordered to enroll the children, do not use the OTHER field when entering the order on the HIUPDATE screen.</p>\n<p><b>Note:</b> The In-Depth Medical Training material from 2007 and part of 2008 contained an example which instructed workers to consider an order stating “either party” was ordered to provide health insurance as an order requiring both parents to provide health insurance. That instruction is no longer valid.</p>\n\n<p><b>“Best” Insurance</b></p>\n<p>Some orders state that the party with the best insurance is to enroll the child(ren). Policies can vary greatly in the services that are covered, the out-of-pocket costs, the network providers available, etc. CSRU is unable determine what policy is \"best.\"</p>\n<p><b>Example:</b></p>\n<ul>\n<li>“The party having the best available insurance shall provide medical insurance for the minor child.”</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p><b>No Dollar Amount of Reasonable Cost</b></p>\n<p>When a private order filed after 7/1/09 requires a payor to provide health insurance when it becomes available at “reasonable cost,” but does not state the reasonable cost dollar amount in the order, CSRU cannot enforce the payor\'s requirement to provide health insurance because the court ordered limitations are unclear.</p>\n\n<p><b>Entries to make on ICAR when using the “OTHER” field</b></p>\n<p>When there is health insurance language in the order but CSRU cannot enforce it for the reasons already described on this page, make the following entries on ICAR.</p>\n<p>COURTORD Screen:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>Enter “Y” in the HI/MS ORDERED field.</li>\n</ul>\n<p>HIUPDATE Screen:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>Enter “Y” in the HEALTH INS (Y/N) field.</li>\n<li>If no cash medical support is ordered, enter “N” in the CASH MED SUPPORT (Y/N) field.</li>\n<li>Enter “Y” in the OTHER field under “PARTY ORDERED TO PROVIDE HEALTH INS?”.</li>\n</ul>\n<p>MEDINFO Screen:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>Make an entry in the OTHER PERSON ORDERED TO PROVIDE HI/MS field that explains why the OTHER field was entered. For example, depending on the language in the order you might enter one of the following:\n<ul>\n<li>“no party ordered to enroll children”</li>\n<li>“either party”</li>\n<li>“reasonable cost not defined”</li>\n<li>etc.</li>\n</ul></li>\n<li>Enter the language from the order in the HEALTH INSURANCE LANGUAGE field.</li>\n</ul>\";i:1586793738320;s:4633:\"<p>Below is a copy of the e-mail sent by Diane Tegtmeyer on May 21, 2012 regarding Health Insurance Flags, or Health Insurance Flags that no longer issue as of 5/21/12.</p>\n<p>From: Tegtmeyer, Diane S.<br />\nSent: Monday, May 21, 2012 10:09 AM<br />\nTo: CSRU Policy Information<br />\nSubject: Health Insurance Flags</p>\n<p>***Please forward as appropriate.***</p>\n<p>Many calendar flags asking workers to obtain health insurance information are changing effective today. Most of these flags will no longer issue. EPICS will work one flag differently. These changes are due to a variety of factors, including field input and the expectation of new federal regulations regarding medical support enforcement in the future.</p>\n\n<p><b>Flags that no longer issue:</b></p>\n<p>The flags listed below will no longer issue.  If you have unworked flags in this list, you may delete them.  The medical team will work with IT to eventually delete any unworked flags that issued prior to today.</p>\n<ul>\n<li><b>CASE 109:</b> (related to entry in the date hi avail field on the CPEMPVER screen)<br />\nDEPENDENT HEALTH INSURANCE IS NOW AVAILABLE TO THE OBLIGEE THROUGH THE OBLIGEE\'S EMPLOYER. VERIFY IF THE OBLIGEE IS ENROLLING THE CHILD(REN).</li>\n<li><b>INTER 137:</b> (issued to EPICS and often referred to the field)<br />\nCSENET INDICATES THAT THE FOLLOWING STATE HAS ADDED MEDICAL INSURANCE. THE STATE, CASE NUMBER, CARRIER NAME AND POLICY NUMBER ARE LISTED BELOW:</li>\n<li><b>INTER 138:</b> (issued to EPICS and often referred to the field)<br />\nCSENET INDICATES THAT THE FOLLOWING STATE HAS DELETED MEDICAL INSURANCE. THE STATE, CASE NUMBER CARRIER NAME AND POLICY NUMBER ARE LISTED BELOW:</li>\n<li><b>LOC 119:</b> (issued if we sent a locate request and the response included HI policy information)<br />\nCSENET RETURNED THE FOLLOWING INSURANCE INFORMATION.  VERIFY COVERAGE AND ENTER ONTO ICAR APPROPRIATELY.</li>\n<li><b>MED 28:</b><br />\nPAYEE HEALTH INSURANCE POLICY ENDED ON THE MEDICAL SCREEN. A CHILD MAY BE BYPASSED ON THE CHILD2 SCREEN. REVIEW CASE TO DETERMINE IF BYPASS CODE SHOULD BE REMOVED TO BEGIN MEDICAL SUPPORT ENF.</li>\n<li><b>MED 30:</b> (issued to EPICS)<br />\nSECOND EMPLOYER VERIFIED. DETERMINE IF MEDICAL SUPPORT ENF IS APPROPRIATE BY CONTACTING THE EMPLOYER THAT RECEIVED MEDICAL SUPPORT ENF FORMS. UPDATE THE MEDSUM2 SCREEN AS NEEDED.</li>\n<li><b>Additional Information:</b><br />\nThe Medsum program automatically moves on to a second employer if the first employer does not respond to the National Medical Support Notice (NMSN) within 75 days.</li>\n<li><b>MED 31:</b> (issued to EPICS)<br />\nMEDICAL SUPPORT ENFORCEMENT BEGAN 30 DAYS AGO. CONTACT THE FOLLOWING EMPLOYER TO VERIFY DEPENDENT HEALTH INSURANCE ENROLLMENT:</li>\n<li><b>MED 33:</b> (issued to EPICS)<br />\nOBLIGOR BEGAN COBRA-RELATED HEALTH INSURANCE 6 MONTHS AGO.  VERIFY THAT THE OBLIGOR CONTINUES ENROLLMENT. IF NO LONGER ENROLLED, ENTER A DATE IN THE END DATE FIELD ON THE MEDICAL SCREEN.</li>\n<li><b>MED 35:</b> (issued to EPICS)<br />\nOBLIGOR BEGAN COBRA-RELATED HEALTH INSURANCE 18 MONTHS AGO.  VERIFY THAT THE OBLIGOR CONTINUES ENROLLMENT. IF NO LONGER ENROLLED, ENTER A DATE IN THE END DATE FIELD ON THE MEDSUM2 SCREEN.</li>\n<li><b>MED 49:</b> (issued to EPICS)<br />\nPAYOR\'S MEDICAL SATISFACTION FORMS GENERATED 15 DAYS AGO. IF NO OTHER COURT ORDER FOR HI, CHECK FOR END DATE OF MEDICAL POLICY(IES) WITH THE FOLLOWING EMPLOYER:</li>\n<li><b>MED 50:</b>\nPAYOR\'S MEDICAL SATISFACTION FORMS GENERATED 15 DAYS AGO. CHECK IF PRIVATE POLICY(IES) ARE PROVIDED BY THE PAYOR. IF NO OTHER COURT ORDER FOR HI, CHECK FOR END DATE OF POLICY(IES).</li>\n<li><b>MED 51:</b>\nPAYEE\'S MEDICAL SATISFACTION FORMS GENERATED 15 DAYS AGO. IF NO OTHER COURT ORDER FOR HI, CHECK FOR END DATE OF PAYEE\'S MEDICAL POLICY(IES).</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p><b>EPICS will work the following flag differently:</b></p>\n<ul>\n<li><b>MED 34:</b> (issues to EPICS)<br />\nOBLIGOR BEGAN COBRA-RELATED HEALTH INSURANCE 12 MONTHS AGO.  VERIFY THAT THE OBLIGOR CONTINUES ENROLLMENT. IF NO LONGER ENROLLED, ENTER A DATE IN THE END DATE FIELD ON THE MEDSUM2 SCREEN.<br />\n<b>How EPICS will work the flag:</b> EPICS will enter the date this flag issues in the end date field on the MEDICAL screen.  Though COBRA policies can last up to 18 months, most policies do not last more than a year.</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>If you have questions, please send them to the <a href=\"mailto:CSRUPolMed@dhs.state.ia.us\" target=\"_blank\"><b>CSRU Policy – Medical</b></a> distribution list.</p>\n\n<p>Thank you.</p>\n\n<p>Diane Tegtmeyer<br />\nDHS/BOC<br />\n(515) 281-8151</p>\";i:1586793738554;s:1773:\"<p><a href=\"http://intra/csruhandbooks/HANDBOOKS/Medical/Contents/ContestingTheEnforcement/Contesting%20Medical%20Support%20Enforcement%20Flowchart.doc\" target=\"_blank\"><img src=\"https://stcsruportalcli.blob.core.windows.net/csruportalwpcontent/2020/04/word.png\"> <b>Contesting the enforcement of Health Insurance</b></a></p>\n\n<p><a href=\"http://intra/csruhandbooks/HANDBOOKS/Medical/Flowchart/Gathering%20HI%20info%20flowchart.pdf\" target=\"_blank\"><img src=\"https://stcsruportalcli.blob.core.windows.net/csruportalwpcontent/2020/04/pdf.png\"> <b>Gathering Information from the Obligee to Complete Health Insurance Enrollment Forms </b></a></p>\n\n<p><a href=\"http://intra/csruhandbooks/HANDBOOKS/Medical/Flowchart/MedicalEnforcementFlowchart10-07.pdf\" target=\"_blank\"><img src=\"https://stcsruportalcli.blob.core.windows.net/csruportalwpcontent/2020/04/pdf.png\"> <b>Medical Support Enforcement </b></a></p>\n\n<p><a href=\"http://intra/csruhandbooks/HANDBOOKS/Medical/Flowchart/Medical%20Establishment%20Flowchart%2012-5-03.doc\" target=\"_blank\"><img src=\"https://stcsruportalcli.blob.core.windows.net/csruportalwpcontent/2020/04/word.png\"> <b>Medical Establishment</b></a></p>\n\n<p><a href=\"http://intra/csruhandbooks/HANDBOOKS/Medical/Flowchart/Medical%20Motion%20to%20Quash%20Flowchart.doc\" target=\"_blank\"><img src=\"https://stcsruportalcli.blob.core.windows.net/csruportalwpcontent/2020/04/word.png\"> <b>Medical Motion to Quash</b></a></p>\n\n<p><a href=\"http://intra/csruhandbooks/HANDBOOKS/Medical/Contents/SelectionOfHealthInsPlan/Selecting%20a%20Health%20Insurance%20Plan%20Flowchart%20(Enforcement).doc\" target=\"_blank\"><img src=\"https://stcsruportalcli.blob.core.windows.net/csruportalwpcontent/2020/04/word.png\"> <b>Selection of Health Insurance plan</b></a></p>\";i:1586793738766;s:28408:\"<h4>Best Practices for Determining Comparable Coverage</h4>\n<p><b>Updated: 10-25-18</b></p>\n\n<p><b>Scenario #1:</b></p>\n<p>EPICS sends the National Medical Support Notice to the employer. The payor and child are not currently enrolled in the employment-related health insurance plan. The payor provides information for a health insurance policy in which the child is currently enrolled (e.g., private policy, policy through the payor’s new spouse’s employer, payee-provided <i>hawk-i</i>, etc.).</p>\n<p><b>Field Office procedures:</b></p>\n<ul>\n<li>Contact the payor to get information about the health insurance policy. Allow the payor 10 days from the date the <i>National Medical Support Notice</i> generated to the employer (offices may be flexible with this timeframe based on case circumstances) to provide information about the private health insurance policy or <i>hawk-i</i> coverage, such as a copy of the health insurance card, coverage information or a way to verify enrollment and health insurance information. Narrate this information on the case.</li>\n<li>Contact the employer to delay enrollment of the child (and payor) in the employment-related health insurance policy.</li>\n<li>Set a calendar flag based on the timeframe provided to the payor to review the case and determine if the payor provided information about the private health insurance policy. When the calendar flag date arrives, review the case and take the following actions: \n<ul>\n<li>If the private health insurance policy or <i>hawk-i</i> information is not on ICAR, contact the employer to resume the process of enrolling the child in an employment-related health insurance policy. Narrate contact with the employer.</li>\n<li>If the payor brings information about the private health insurance policy into the local office or EPICS, add the policy to the MEDICAL screen. Narrate the payor provided the private policy information. Refer to <a href=\"http://dhs.iowa.gov/sites/default/files/11-I.pdf\" target=\"_blank\"><img src=\"https://stcsruportalcli.blob.core.windows.net/csruportalwpcontent/2020/04/pdf.png\"> <b>Employee Manual Title 11, Chapter I, MEDICAL SUPPORT</b></a>, for information on completing the MEDICAL screen. Generate and send form 470-3933, <i>Termination of the National Medical Support Notice</i>, to the employer.</li>\n</ul></li>\n</ul>\n\n<p><b>Scenario #2:</b></p>\n<p>EPICS sends the National Medical Support Notice to the employer. The payor and child are not currently enrolled in the employment-related health insurance plan. The payor wants to enroll the child in another health insurance plan (e.g., private policy, policy through the payor’s new spouse’s employer, payee-provided <i>hawk-i</i>, etc.).</p>\n<p><b>Field Office procedures:</b></p>\n<ul>\n<li>Contact the payor to find out what steps the payor is taking to enroll the child in a private health insurance policy. Allow the payor 10 days from the date the National Medical Support Notice generated to the employer (offices may be flexible with this timeframe based on case circumstances) to provide proof of application in a private health insurance policy. Narrate this information on the case.</li>\n<li>Contact the employer to delay enrollment of the child (and payor) in the employment-related health insurance policy.</li>\n<li>Set a calendar flag based on the timeframe provided to the payor to review the case and determine if the payor provided proof of application for a private health insurance policy. When the calendar flag date arrives, review the case and take the following actions:\n<ul>\n<li>If the payor provides proof of application, enter a “P” in the enr stat field on the MEDSUM2 screen for each child that displays a date in the sent date field on the MEDSUM2 screen and press F3 twice. Narrate this information on the case.</li>\n<li>If the payor does not provide proof of application within the timeframe, narrate this information on the case and contact the employer to resume the process of enrolling the child in an employment-related health insurance policy.</li>\n</ul></li>\n<li>When you receive proof of application, allow the payor 20 days (offices may be flexible with this timeframe based on case circumstances) to provide proof of enrollment in a private health insurance policy. Narrate this information on the case.</li>\n<li>If the payor provides information about the private health insurance policy, such as a copy of the health insurance card and coverage information, into the local office, add the policy to the MEDICAL screen. Narrate this information on the case. Refer to <a href=\"http://dhs.iowa.gov/sites/default/files/11-I.pdf\" target=\"_blank\"><img src=\"https://stcsruportalcli.blob.core.windows.net/csruportalwpcontent/2020/04/pdf.png\"> <b>Employee Manual Title 11, Chapter I, MEDICAL SUPPORT</b></a>, for information on completing the MEDICAL screen. Generate and send form 470-3933, Termination of the National Medical Support Notice, to the employer.</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p><b>Scenario #3:</b></p>\n<p><b>EPICS no longer receives a flag 30 days after the NMSN is sent so there is no follow-up done.</b></p>\n<p>EPICS sends the National Medical Support Notice to the employer and the payor and child are not currently enrolled in the employment-related health insurance plan. The plan administrator enrolls the child in the employment-related health insurance plan. The payor wants or has enrolled the child in another plan (e.g., private plan, policy through the payor’s new spouse’s employer, payee-provided <i>hawk-i</i>, etc.).</p>\n<p>We may learn of this situation through a variety of sources, e.g., the payor may call or stop by the local office or the payor’s employer may call EPCIS.</p>\n<p><b>Steps to determine whether health insurance is comparable:</b></p>\n<p><b>Step 1:</b> Tell the person (payor, employer, etc.) that state law requires the employer to receive proof that the other health insurance policy is comparable to the employment-related policy before they can end enrollment. The employer needs information about the other health insurance plan to determine if this plan is comparable to the plan the employer offers.</p>\n<p><b>Step 2:</b> If the employer refuses to review the plan and determine if the plan is comparable, EPICS or the field office sends the employer the state statute requirement (252E.5(6)).</p>\n<p><b>Step 3:</b> If the employer still refuses, ask if the insurance benefit person can review the policy. If not, contact the payor. Tell the payor to ask the company or employer offering the other health insurance plan to determine if the policy offered is comparable to the payor’s employment-related policy. <b>NOTE:</b> If they still refuse and the plan is a hawk-i plan, send an email to <a href=\"mailto:CSRUPolMed@dhs.state.ia.us\" target=\"_blank\"><b>CSRU Policy-Medical</b></a>. Central office will review the case.</p>\n<p>If the company determines the plan is comparable, the company or employer <span style=\"color: red;\">offering the other health insurance</span> must provide written evidence to the payor’s employer that the policy is comparable to the employment-related policy.</p>\n<p>The employer needs to contact either EPICS or the field office by phone or in writing to let them know the outcome of the comparable coverage determination.</p>\n<p><span style=\"color: red;\">If the plan is comparable</span> the payor <span style=\"color: red;\">must</span> provide the health insurance policy information to the field office. The CSRU field office will send form 470/3729, Discontinuation of Health Insurance Enforcement, to the payor’s employer.</p>\n<p>The payor’s employer can then end the employment-related health insurance plan. The payor’s employer must send us the date health insurance ends.</p>\n<p>The CSRU ends the employment-related health insurance policy using the end date provided by the payor’s employer. The CSRU adds the new health insurance policy to ICAR.</p>\n<p><b>Step 4:</b> If the company or employer which offers the other health insurance plan refuses to determine if the plan is comparable, the employment-related plan remains in place.</p>\n<p><b>Note:</b> Staff should only use the comparable coverage steps outlined in scenarios 4 & 5 in limited circumstances, for example red dot or complaint cases. Staff should review all cases with the office supervisor before proceeding with these steps.</p>\n\n<p><b>Scenario #4</b></p>\n<p>EPICS sends the National Medical Support Notice to the employer. The payor and child are not currently enrolled in the employment-related health insurance plan. The payee contacts CSRU to report that the payor’s employment-related insurance doesn’t cover the doctors the child needs to see. The child is on Medicaid due to special medical needs and the payee wants us to stop medical enforcement.</p>\n<p><b>Field Office procedures:</b></p>\n<ul>\n<li>Check WISE to confirm the child is receiving Medicaid.</li>\n<li>Contact the employer to verify that they have not enrolled the child in the employment-related insurance.</li>\n<li>If the child is not enrolled yet, let the employer know that they do not need to proceed.  Generate and send form 470-3933, Termination of the National Medical Support Notice, to the employer.</li>\n<li>Enter \"B\" in the medical field on the CASESTAT screen to bypass medical enforcement on the case. Calendar flag MED 69 issues one year after the worker enters the \"B\". The worker needs to review the case at that time to determine if the bypass is still appropriate.</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p><b>Scenario #5</b></p>\n<p>EPICS sends the National Medical Support Notice to the employer. The payor and child are not currently enrolled in the employment-related health insurance plan. The plan administrator enrolls the child in the employment-related health insurance plan. The payee contacts CSRU to report that the payor’s employment-related insurance doesn’t cover the doctors the child needs to see. The child is on Medicaid due to special medical needs and the payee wants us to stop medical enforcement.</p>\n<p><b>Steps to determine whether the Medicaid health care coverage is comparable:</b></p>\n<p><b>Step 1:</b> Tell the person (payor, payee, employer, etc.) that state law requires the employer to receive proof that the other health care coverage is comparable to the employment-related insurance before they can end enrollment. The employer needs information about the Medicaid health care coverage to determine if the coverage is comparable to the plan the employer offers. This may include the managed care member ID card and coverage information.</p>\n<p>Here’s a link to the current Medicaid Managed Care Provider information:<br />\n<a href=\"https://dhs.iowa.gov/iahealthlink/resources/member-specific\" target=\"_blank\"><b>https://dhs.iowa.gov/iahealthlink/resources/member-specific</b></a></p>\n<p><b>Step 2:</b> If the employer refuses to review the plan and determine if the plan is comparable, EPICS or the field office sends the employer the state statute requirement (252E.5(6)).</p>\n<p><b>Step 3:</b> If the employer still refuses, ask if the employer’s insurance benefit person can review the information. If they still refuse, send an email to CSRU Policy – Medical. Central office will review the case.</p>\n<p><b>Step 4:</b> If the Medicaid coverage is determined to be comparable, the CSRU field office will send form 470/3729, Discontinuation of Health Insurance Enforcement, to the payor’s employer.</p>\n<p>The payor’s employer can then end the employment-related health insurance plan. The payor’s employer must send us the date health insurance ends. The CSRU ends the employment-related health insurance policy on ICAR using the end date provided by the payor’s employer.</p>\n<p><b>Step 5:</b> The CSRU worker enters “B” in the MEDICAL field on the CASESTAT screen to bypass medical enforcement on the case. Calendar flag MED 69 issues one year after the worker enters the “B.” The worker needs to review the case at that time to determine if the bypass is still appropriate.</p>\n\n<hr />\n\n<h4>Changing Medical Policy Numbers on ICAR</h4>\n<p>The policy number field on the MEDICAL screen can only be revised on the same day the policy was entered. When attempting to revise the policy number field for a policy added on a previous date, the following edit message will display.</p>\n<p>“MUST END POLICY AND ADD NEW ONE. POLICY NUMBER CANNOT BE CHANGED.”</p>\n<p>When a worker finds that the policy number entered on a previous date is incorrect, the worker will need to take the following actions.</p>\n<ol>\n<li>Print or record the policy information from the following screens.\n<ul>\n<li>MEDICAL</li>\n<li>MEDICAL COVERAGE (F6 from the MEDICAL screen)</li>\n<li>INSURANCE DEPENDENT LIST (F14 from the MEDICAL screen)</li>\n</ul></li>\n<li>Enter a date in the end date field on the MEDICAL screen.</li>\n<li>Add the policy to the MEDICAL screen using the correct policy number and the policy information previously printed or recorded.</li>\n</ol>\n\n<hr />\n\n<h4>Health Insurance Premium Limits</h4>\n<p>A growing number of orders now include a premium limit on the payor’s cost of employment-related health insurance for the child(ren). EPICS has received numerous referrals from CSRU offices in the past few months when a payor complained that the employer enrolled the children in a plan that exceeds the ordered premium limit. Do not make a referral to EPICS in this situation. The procedure to follow when an employer overlooks an ordered premium limit is explained below.</p>\n\n<p><b>How Employers are Informed of a Premium Limit</b></p>\n<p>An entry in the REAS COST or TOTAL COST field on the HIUPDATE screen causes the appropriate premium limit information to print on form 470/3818, <i>National Medical Support Notice (NMSN)</i>. When there is no entry in the REAS COST or TOTAL COST fields, language will print on the NMSN stating that there is no premium limit in the order. Employers can find this “Exception” language in bold print at the bottom of page 1 of Part A.</p>\n<p>For additional information about the REAS COST and TOTAL COST fields or the “Exception” language on the <i>NMSN</i>, see <a href=\"file://hoovr3s2/CSRU.772/CSRUPROC/Directives/2009\" target=\"_blank\"><img src=\"https://stcsruportalcli.blob.core.windows.net/csruportalwpcontent/2020/04/folder.png\"> <b>Procedural Directive #09-11, DRA of 2005 – Changes to NMSN and HIUPDATE Screen</b></a>.</p>\n\n<p><b>EPICS Receives the NMSN</b></p>\n<p>When an employer returns policy information with the <i>NMSN</i>, EPICS enters the policy information on the MEDICAL screen. EPICS <b>does not</b> contact the employer to determine if the policy cost exceeds the ordered premium limit.</p>\n\n<p><b>Payor Challenges Enrollment due to Cost</b></p>\n<p>If the payor reports that the employer enrolled the child(ren) in a plan that exceeds the ordered premium limit without the payor’s consent, confirm that there is a premium limit in the order and take the following steps.</p>\n<p>Check the entries in the REAS COST and TOTAL COST fields on the HIUPDATE screen.</p>\n<ul>\n<li>If the REAS COST and TOTAL COST fields were entered correctly, take the following steps.\n<ul>\n<li>Contact the employer.</li>\n</ul></li>\n<li>Explain the premium limit. Point out that the <i>NMSN</i> already included the information about the ordered premium limit.</li>\n<li>If the children are enrolled in a plan that exceeds the premium limit:</li>\n<li>Explain that the employer does not need any additional notice from CSRU to disenroll the child(ren) since doing so is in compliance with the premium limit information already provided on the <i>NMSN</i>.</li>\n<li>If the cost of another plan is within the ordered premium limit, ask the employer to enroll the child(ren) in that plan. Follow up with the employer to obtain the policy information and enter it on the MEDICAL screen.</li>\n<li>If the employer will need to disenroll the child(ren), ask the employer for the date the coverage will end and enter the date in the END DATE field on the MEDICAL screen.</li>\n<li>If the REAS COST and TOTAL COST fields were NOT entered correctly, fix the entries and take the following steps.\n<ul>\n<li>Manually generate form 470-3818, <i>NMSN</i>, and form 470-2743, <i>Employer Medical Support Information</i>, from FORMVIEW. Make the appropriate entries when generating the <i>NMSN</i> to ensure the correct “Exception” language prints on the form.</li>\n<br />\n<p><b>Note:</b> These steps assume an NMSN was previously sent to the employer and the employer then enrolled the child(ren). If an NMSN was not sent recently and you are unsure if one needs to be sent now, contact the <a href=\"mailto:CSRUPolMed@dhs.state.ia.us\" target=\"_blank\"><b>Medical team</b></a>.</p>\n<li>Contact the employer.</li>\n</ul></li>\n<li>Explain the premium limit.</li>\n<li>Tell the employer you are sending an updated <i>NMSN</i>.</li>\n<li>If the employer will need to disenroll the child(ren), ask the employer for the date the coverage will end and enter the date in the END DATE field on the MEDICAL screen.</li>\n<li>If the child(ren) is currently enrolled in a plan that is within the ordered premium limit, make sure the plan is entered on the MEDICAL screen. Ask the employer to respond to the updated <i>NMSN</i> as they normally would.</li>\n<li>If the child(ren) is enrolled in a plan that exceeds the premium limit, but another plan is available that does not exceed the premium limit, ask the employer to enroll the child(ren) in that plan. Ask the employer to provide the policy information, as they normally would after receiving the updated <i>NMSN</i>.</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p><b>DRA Enforcement Q & A</b></p>\n<p>The <a href=\"file://hoovr3s2/CSRU.772/CS_TRAIN/DRAEnf-2009\" target=\"_blank\"><img src=\"https://stcsruportalcli.blob.core.windows.net/csruportalwpcontent/2020/04/folder.png\"> <b>DRA Enforcement Q & A document</b></a> contains two questions, #3 and #4, that address EPICS procedures related to premium limits and the NMSN. Those two questions are copied below.</p>\n<p>3. <b>At what point will EPICS not pursue medical? For example, on the cases where it is ordered that the premium cannot cost anything and the employer gives us a premium amount over the cost of single coverage, do we automatically update to NOT send the NMSN during the EMPVER process, or only if HI POT “A” runs?</b></p>\n<p>In this case situation, do not make an entry on the EMPVER screen to signify an employer doesn’t have health insurance. When working a HI POT of “A” flag, EPICS will check the HIUPDATE screen to see if a premium limit exists for the court order. When contacting the employer, EPICS will ask if they offer any health insurance plan within the premium limit. If the employer does not, EPICS will not send the NMSN and EPICS will narrate the findings.</p>\n<p>Until a new code is developed for this specific scenario, EPICS will enter the current code of “X” in the ENR STAT field on the MEDSUM2 screen to stop the NMSN from issuing.</p>\n<ul>\n<li>X – Medical support enforcement forms not sent because this employer does not offer health insurance.</li>\n</ul>\n<p>The procedures for determining accessibility have not changed. Accessibility, as well as reasonable cost, is determined at the time of the establishment or modification action, not at the time of enforcement. EPICS will not determine accessibility before sending the NMSN.</p>\n<p>4. <b>Will review need to be done when the NMSN is returned to see if the premium amount provided on the NMSN by the employer exceeds the limitations on the HIUPDATE exceptions, or will the medical information just get added?</b></p>\n<p>The COURT ORDER PREMIUM LIMIT field (the COURT ORDER PREMIUM LIMIT field was replaced by the REAS COST and <i>TOTAL COST</i> fields) on the HIUPDATE screen is not a new field. EPICS will follow their current practice of reviewing this field when an NMSN is returned. If the employer does not implement the order as provided by CSRU, it will be the payor’s responsibility to challenge it.</p>\n<p><b>Note:</b> EPICS will have no way of knowing if the employer truly didn’t follow the NMSN as written or if the employee asked the employer to enroll a child in a higher priced health insurance plan.</p>\n\n<hr />\n\n<h4>How Bankruptcy Affects Medical Enforcement</h4>\n<p>When a payor files bankruptcy, you must complete the BANKRPTCY & CHAPTR field on the PAYOR screen. This field consists of three sections. Make the following entries:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>First section: Enter “Y”.</li>\n<li>Second section: Enter 7, 11, or 13 to indicate the type of bankruptcy filed.</li>\n<li>Third section: Enter the date the bankruptcy was filed.</li>\n</ul>\n<p>CSRU will not enforce a payor’s order to provide medical support when the payor files bankruptcy under the following conditions:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>Chapter 11 bankruptcy.</li>\n<li>Chapter 13 bankruptcy.</li>\n</ul>\n<p>CSRU will enforce a payor’s order to provide medical support when the payor files bankruptcy under chapter 7.</p>\n<p>When the children are enrolled in a health insurance policy and the payor then files for bankruptcy, keep the children enrolled in that policy. This applies whether it is a chapter 11, 13, or 7 bankruptcy.</p>\n<p><b>Payor Files Bankruptcy under <span style=\"color: red;\">either</span> Chapter 11 <span style=\"color: red;\">or</span> Chapter 13:</b></p>\n<ul>\n<li>When EPICS gets a calendar flag for a HI POT of \"A\" to begin medical support enforcement, do not proceed with medical enforcement until the bankruptcy ends.\n<ul>\n<li>Enter an \"X\" in the ENR STAT field on the MEDSUM2 screen to indicate that CSRU is not proceeding with enforcement due to bankruptcy.</li>\n<li>Set a calendar flag to review the case in 3 months to determine if the bankruptcy ended.</li>\n<li>When the bankruptcy ends, retrigger the case for medical support enforcement.</li>\n</ul></li>\n<li><span style=\"color: red;\">If the employer has already been sent</span> the National Medical Support Notice (NMSN), contact the employer. Find out whether the children are enrolled in the payor’s health insurance policy.  \n<ul>\n<li>If the children are already enrolled in the health insurance policy, enter the policy on the MEDICAL screen.</li>\n<li>If the children are in the process of being enrolled, <span style=\"color: red;\">tell the employer not to enroll the child(ren)</span>. Generate and send form 470-3933, <i>Termination of the National Medical Support Notice</i>, to the employer to stop the enrollment process.</li>\n<li>Enter a \"5\" (temporarily ineligible) in the FORM STAT field and an “I” in the ENR STAT field on the MEDSUM2 screen. Set the calendar flag to review the case in 3 months to determine whether the bankruptcy ended.</li>\n<li>When the bankruptcy ends, retrigger the case for medical support enforcement.</li>\n</ul></li>\n</ul>\n\n<hr />\n\n<h4>NMSN - When & How to Manually Generate</h4>\n<p>ICAR will not automatically generate a <i>National Medical Support Notice (NMSN)</i>, 470/3818 to the court ordered payor’s employer if the MEDICAL screen is coded to show that the child(ren) are covered by health insurance. This includes coverage provided by the payor, payee and private coverage.</p>\n<p>CSRU may become aware that a payor has enrolled the child(ren) in the payor’s employer health insurance coverage without the issuance of an NMSN. The medical screens are updated with this information.</p>\n<p>Without receipt of an NMSN:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>The plan administrator is not advised to provide policy information to the payee.</li>\n<li>The employer is not aware that the health insurance enrollment is court ordered and the child(ren) must remain enrolled.</li>\n</ul>\n<p>For these reasons, it is essential that an NMSN be sent to the employer even when the payor is ordered to provide health insurance and the children are already enrolled.</p>\n<p>Examples of events that require the manual generation of an NMSN <span style=\"color: red;\">are listed below. The examples only apply when Iowa is enforcing.  If Iowa is not enforcing, do not manually generate the NMSN.</span></p>\n<ul>\n<li>Payor’s health insurance information is provided during establishment or modification action <b>prior</b> to the entry of a court order including medical enforcement.\n<ul>\n<li>Update ICAR medical screens with payor health insurance information.<br />\nOnce the order is obtained for medical enforcement, manually generate the NMSN.<br />\nEnter the EPICS address for the employer’s return of the document.</li>\n</ul></li>\n<li>Payor ordered to provide health insurance calls with new employment and health insurance information.\n<ul>\n<li>Add the employer to ICAR.</li>\n<li>Allow MEDSUM to run overnight.</li>\n<li>Check the case two days later to ensure the NMSN was sent to the employer.</li>\n<li>Update ICAR medical screens with employment related health insurance information if sufficient information was obtained from the payor to accurately update ICAR. Example: payor provided copy of employment related health insurance card. If only partial information was provided, a call to the employer may be necessary to ensure timely update of the medical screens.</li>\n<li>Upon return of the NMSN, EPICS will compare the information on the NMSN to the information on the medical screens for accuracy.</li>\n<br />\n<p>--OR--</p>\n<li>Add the employer to ICAR and update the medical screens with the payor’s health insurance information.<br />\nManually generate the NMSN. Enter the EPICS address for the employer’s return of the document.</li>\n</ul></li>\n<li>Payee asks CSRU to enforce health insurance available to the payor through an employer. The payee is currently providing health insurance and the payor is court ordered to provide health insurance for the children.\n<ul>\n<li>Update ICAR medical screens with payee health insurance information.</li>\n<li>Upon payee request for enforcement, manually generate the NMSN. Set calendar flag to monitor for return of the NMSN.</li>\n<li>Document payee request on the MEDINFO screen.</li>\n</ul></li>\n<li>Employer or Plan Administrator requests duplicate or updated copy of NMSN.\n<ul>\n<li>Check the MEDSUM2 screen. If the hipot field is “1,” use the ONLINE FORM or the REPRINT field.</li>\n<li>If the hipot field is not a “1,” manually generate the NMSN.</li>\n</ul></li>\n<li>Premium limit for enrolling a child in a health benefit plan changes due to the modification of an existing order. This includes a change from no premium limit to a premium limit, a change from one premium limit to another premium limit, or a change from an existing premium limit to no premium limit.\n<ul>\n<li>Update the reas cost or total cost fields on the HIUPDATE screen to reflect the current premium limit. The premium limit must be in the decretal part of the order. You will enter this premium limit when you manually generate the NMSN.</li>\n</ul></li>\n</ul>\n<p>Manually generate the NMSN to the employer by entering FORMS in the NEXT SCREEN function on ICAR. Have the following information available when manually generating the NMSN (470-3818) and the Employer Medical Support Information form (470-2743):</p>\n<ul>\n<li>Case number.</li>\n<li>Payor’s name, address, and SSN.</li>\n<li>Payee’s name and address (If a DRI or FVI display on the PAYEE or CHILD screen, use EPICS’ address instead of payee’s address.)</li>\n<li>Names, SSNs and DOB of the children.</li>\n<li>Employer name, address and FEIN (Use the medical mailing address from VEMPLOY2 if listed. From the EMPVER screen, you can use F14 to get to the VEMPLOY screen, and then use F11 to get to the VEMPLOY2 screen.)</li>\n<li>Court order number, order date, county of filing.</li>\n<li>EPICS mailing address—501 Sycamore Ste 500, Waterloo, IA 50703-4651.</li>\n<li>The current premium limit displaying in the reas cost or total cost fields on the HIUPDATE screen.</li>\n</ul>\n<p>Send the NMSN to the employer. If the employment-related health insurance has not been entered into ICAR, set an ICAR calendar flag to monitor for return of the NMSN from the employer in thirty days.</p>\";i:1586793739016;s:2084:\"<p><b>Commonly Asked Questions:</b></p>\n<ul>\n<li>from <a href=\"?page_id=1468\"><b>payees/payors</b></a></li>\n<li>from <a href=\"?page_id=1470\"><b>employers</b></a></li>\n<li>from <a href=\"?page_id=1472\"><b>field staff</b></a></li>\n</ul>\n\n<p><b>Medical Enforcement Training Questions and Answers</b></p>\n<p>Most of the following links will take you to a folder in the <b>CS_TRAIN share</b>. Look for the Q&A document in the folder.</p>\n<ul>\n<li><a href=\"file://hoovr3s2/CSRU.772/CS_TRAIN/HI_Premium_Limit-2010\" target=\"_blank\"><img src=\"https://stcsruportalcli.blob.core.windows.net/csruportalwpcontent/2020/04/folder.png\"> <b>Health Insurance Premium Limits (2010)</b></a><br />\nSee <a href=\"file://hoovr3s2/CSRU.772/CSRUPROC/Directives/2009\" target=\"_blank\"><img src=\"https://stcsruportalcli.blob.core.windows.net/csruportalwpcontent/2020/04/folder.png\"> <b>PD 09-11 Changes to NMSN and HIUPDATE Screen</b></a> for more information.</li>\n<li><a href=\"file://hoovr3s2/CSRU.772/CS_TRAIN/DRAEnf-2009\" target=\"_blank\"><img src=\"https://stcsruportalcli.blob.core.windows.net/csruportalwpcontent/2020/04/folder.png\"> <b>DRA Enforcement (2009)</b></a><br />\nSee <a href=\"file://hoovr3s2/CSRU.772/CSRUPROC/Directives/2009\" target=\"_blank\"><img src=\"https://stcsruportalcli.blob.core.windows.net/csruportalwpcontent/2020/04/folder.png\"> <b>PD 09-07 Medical Screen Changes and MEDSUM Changes</b></a> for more information.</li>\n<li><a href=\"file://hoovr3s2/CSRU.772/CS_TRAIN/Medical_Satisfaction_2009\" target=\"_blank\"><img src=\"https://stcsruportalcli.blob.core.windows.net/csruportalwpcontent/2020/04/folder.png\"> <b>Medical Satisfaction (2009)</b></a><br />\nSee <a href=\"file://hoovr3s2/CSRU.772/CSRUPROC/Directives/2009\" target=\"_blank\"><img src=\"https://stcsruportalcli.blob.core.windows.net/csruportalwpcontent/2020/04/folder.png\"> <b>PD 09-08 Medical Satisfaction</b></a> for more information.</li>\n<li><a href=\"?page_id=1475\"><b>In-Depth Medical Training (September & October of 2007)</b></a></li>\n<li><a href=\"?page_id=1477\"><b>Medical Training 7/25/06</b></a></li>\n</ul>\";i:1586793739250;s:3448:\"<ul>\n<li><a href=\"?page_id=1515\"><b>Certificate of Coverage - HIPAA</b></a></li>\n<li><a href=\"?page_id=1523\"><b>hawk-i</b></a></li>\n<li><a href=\"?page_id=1535\"><b>HIPP (Health Insurance Premium Payment) Information</b></a>\n<ul>\n<li><a href=\"?page_id=1539\"><b>Using MMIS TO verify HIPP Insurance</b></a></li>\n</ul></li>\n<li><a href=\"?page_id=1556\"><b>Insurance Companies on ICAR</b></a>\n<ul>\n<li><a href=\"?page_id=1557\"><b>Adding an Insurer to the Company List</b></a></li>\n<li><a href=\"http://intra/csruhandbooks/HANDBOOKS/Medical/Contents/Resources/InsuranceCompanyDoNotUseConversionFile.xls\" target=\"_blank\"><img src=\"https://stcsruportalcli.blob.core.windows.net/csruportalwpcontent/2020/04/excel.png\"> <b>Insurance Company DO NOT USE Conversion File (by company number)</b></a></li>\n<li><a href=\"http://intra/csruhandbooks/HANDBOOKS/Medical/Contents/Resources/InsuranceCoNameConversionList.xlsx\" target=\"_blank\"><img src=\"https://stcsruportalcli.blob.core.windows.net/csruportalwpcontent/2020/04/excel.png\"> <b>Insurance Company Name Conversion File (by company name)</b></a></li>\n</ul></li>\n<li><a href=\"?page_id=1565\"><b>Insurance Repricing Companies</b></a></li>\n<li><a href=\"https://dhs.iowa.gov/iahealthlink/resources/member-specific\"><b>Medicaid Managed Care provider information</b></a>\n<ul>\n<li><a href=\"https://dhs.iowa.gov/sites/default/files/Comm486.pdf\"><img src=\"https://stcsruportalcli.blob.core.windows.net/csruportalwpcontent/2020/04/pdf.png\"> <b>Sample MCO ID Cards - Comm. 486</b></a></li>\n</ul></li>\n<li><a href=\"?page_id=1569\"><b>Seeking Medical Benefits from the Military</b></a>\n<ul>\n<li><a href=\"http://intra/csruhandbooks/HANDBOOKS/Medical/Contents/Resources/DEERS%20Letter.docx\"><img src=\"https://stcsruportalcli.blob.core.windows.net/csruportalwpcontent/2020/04/word.png\"> <b>DEERS Letter</b></a>\n</ul></li>\n<li><b>TRICARE/DEERS</b>\n<ul>\n<li><a href=\"http://www.tricare.mil/\" target=\"_blank\"><b>TRICARE</b></a> is the Department of Defense’s worldwide health care program for active duty and retired uniformed services members and their families.</li>\n<li><a href=\"http://www.military.com/benefits/tricare/defense-enrollment-eligibility-reporting-system-deers.html\" target=\"_blank\"><b>DEERS</b></a> is a computerized database of military sponsors, families and others worldwide who are entitled under the law to TRICARE benefits. DEERS registration is required for TRICARE eligibility.</li>\n</ul></li>\n<li><a href=\"?page_id=1572\"><b>United States Postal Employees - Medical Support</b></a></li>\n<li><b>Wellmark</b>\n<ul>\n<li><b>Obtaining Wellmark Policy Information</b><br />\nWhen possible, attempt to get policy information from a case party or employer.  You may also contact the Wellmark toll free customer service number below.  If you already use a different Wellmark toll free number, you may continue to use that number.<br />\n1-800-676-2583</li>\n<li><b>Entering Wellmark Policy Numbers on ICAR</b><br />\nInclude the alpha prefix (the letters at the beginning of the number) when entering the policy number on the MEDICAL screen in ICAR. These letters tell Medicaid which state program the plan is through.</li>\n<li><a href=\"http://intra/csruhandbooks/HANDBOOKS/Medical/Contents/Resources/AlphaPrefixes.xlsx\"><img src=\"https://stcsruportalcli.blob.core.windows.net/csruportalwpcontent/2020/04/excel.png\"> <b>Insurance Policy Prefix by Location</b></a></li>\n</ul></li>\n</ul>\";i:1586793739500;s:3598:\"<p><b>Forms:</b> For instructions on completing the forms, see <a href=\"http://dhs.iowa.gov/sites/default/files/11-i-app.pdf\" target=\"_blank\"><img src=\"https://stcsruportalcli.blob.core.windows.net/csruportalwpcontent/2020/04/pdf.png\"> <b>Employees Manual, Title 11, Chapter I, Appendix</b></a>.</p>\n\n<hr />\n\n<h4>Medical Enforcement Reference Guide</h4>\n<p><b>Note:</b> Use this guide to answer questions from obligors, obligees and employers.</p>\n\n<p><b>References</b></p>\n<ul>\n<li><a href=\"http://www.ecfr.gov/cgi-bin/ECFR?page=browse\" target=\"_blank\"><b>Code of Federal Regulations</b></a> 303.30, 303.31 & 303.32: Securing and enforcing medical support obligations.</li>\n<li><a href=\"http://search.legis.state.ia.us/nxt/gateway.dll/ic?f=templates&fn=default.htm\" target=\"_blank\"><b>Code of Iowa</b></a> - use SEARCH in the upper right corner and search for Chapter 252E.</li>\n<li><a href=\"http://dhs.iowa.gov/sites/default/files/11-I.pdf\" target=\"_blank\"><img src=\"https://stcsruportalcli.blob.core.windows.net/csruportalwpcontent/2020/04/pdf.png\"> <b>CSRU Employee’s Manual 11-I</b></a></li>\n<li><a href=\"https://www.legis.iowa.gov/law/administrativeRules/chapters?pubDate=04-07-2010&agency=441\" target=\"_blank\"><b>Iowa Administrative Code, 441</b></a> - 98 Medical Support Enforcement.</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p><b>Types of court orders/obligations</b></p>\n<ul>\n<li>HI (Health Insurance): One or both parties are ordered to provide health insurance for the dependents.</li>\n<li>HO (Health Only): One of the parties is ordered to provide health insurance only for the children and obligee, if ordered.</li>\n<li>MS (Medical Support): One of the parties is ordered to provide a set dollar amount toward medical support. This is paid on a regular frequency (usually weekly or monthly).</li>\n<li>MR (Medical Reimbursement): One of the parties is ordered to pay a lump sum toward medical expenses.</li>\n<li>Reduction of Medical Support to a Dollar Amount: see below.</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p><b>Important aspects of <a href=\"http://search.legis.state.ia.us/nxt/gateway.dll/ic?f=templates&fn=default.htm\" target=\"_blank\"><b>Iowa Code 252E</b></a></b></p>\n<ul>\n<li>252E.1(13) \"Order\" also includes</li>\n<li>252E.5(2) Plan must be accessible if more than one plan is offered (important if employer offers an HMO and the child lives out of state).</li>\n<li>252E.5(3) Employer shall withhold premiums from employee’s wages.</li>\n<li>252E.5(1) Allow enrollment regardless of enrollment seasons.</li>\n<li>252E.7(1) Insurer authorization (CSRU employee or obligee can sign enrollment forms).</li>\n<li>252E.8(2) Release of information (Employer shall make available claim forms or identification cards.)</li>\n<li>252E.5(9) Requirements for the employer and plan administrator when the National Medical Support Notice issued to enforce health insurance.</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p><b>Qualified Medical Child Support Orders (QMCSO)</b></p>\n<p>The National Medical Support Notice, when appropriately completed, is deemed a QMCSO.</p>\n\n<p><b>Reduction of Medical Support to a Dollar Amount</b></p>\n<p>A court order may require the obligor to pay a percentage of unreimbursed medical expenses. The payee is responsible for providing an itemized list of expenditures with receipts or other written proof of expenses claimed. As time permits, the Unit may reduce these types of non-dollar specific unreimbursed medical expenses to a specific dollar judgment. The Unit will collect these medical expenses regardless of whether the judgment has been obtained through a private action or the Unit.</p>\n\n\n\";}"
