                        "__cdata": "a:12:{i:1582230543844;s:1819:\"The administrative levy process is an administrative tool used to identify and encumber (levy) the financial assets of obligors with a child support delinquency. Since this is an administrative process, the Child Support Recovery Unit (Unit) has the authority to pursue this type of enforcement action without the need for an additional court order. The obligor or joint owner may challenge the administrative levy process administratively through the Unit as well as through the district court.\n\nIowa Code Chapter 252I authorizes the Unit to use an administrative levy to collect delinquent support payments by executing, attaching or placing levies against obligors’ accounts maintained in Iowa financial institutions and in out-of-state financial institutions accepting direct levies from Iowa. Using the interstate referral process, the Unit may also place levies against obligors’ accounts maintained in out-of-state financial institutions not accepting direct levies.\n\nAsset information may be received through several sources, the primary source being the automated financial institution data-match (FIDM). The FIDM process has two parts:\n<ul>\n \t<li>In-state (ISFIDM) matching provides account information from financial institutions within the state of Iowa.</li>\n \t<li>Multi-state (MSFIDM) matching provides account information from financial institutions throughout the United States and its territories.</li>\n</ul>\nAsset information may also be received through contact with the obligee or other interested third party.\n\nThe administrative levy process is semi-centralized. EPICS staff handles the identification of assets, review of asset information, the initiation of administrative levies and monitoring cases for payment. Field staff handles challenges to the administrative levy process.\";i:1582231395579;s:698:\"ICAR selects cases for administrative levy based on certain criteria. Nightly, the ICAR case delinquency program selects delinquent obligors on ICAR. Through the batch asset load program, ICAR compares delinquent obligors’ case information to account information ICAR stores in the electronic asset file. When the delinquent obligors’ assets on the file pass the program criteria, ICAR loads the asset information to the ASSET screen.\n\nSee <a href=\"http://dhs.iowa.gov/sites/default/files/11-a.pdf\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\"><img src=\"https://stcsruportalcli.blob.core.windows.net/csruportalwpcontent/2020/02/pdf.png\" /> Title 11-A</a>, <b>Initiating the Administrative Levy, <i>Administrative Levy Case Selection Criteria</i></b>.\";i:1582231537856;s:15132:\"Refer to <a href=\"http://dhs.iowa.gov/sites/default/files/11-a.pdf\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\"><img src=\"https://stcsruportalcli.blob.core.windows.net/csruportalwpcontent/2020/02/sharepoint.png\" /> Title 11-A</a>, <b>Challenges to the Administrative Levy Process</b>, for a detailed explanation of these steps.\n\nThe challenge process is an important piece of the administrative levy process. Challenges allow the obligor/joint owner due process in resolving issues related to the administrative levy placed against the obligor’s/joint owner’s assets.\nThere are two types of challenges to the administrative levy process: administrative and district court. The Unit handles the administrative challenge internally. The outcome of this challenge is decided administratively without court involvement. If the party wishes to challenge the decision of the administrative challenge, the party may file a district court challenge. The district court decides the outcome of this challenge.\n\n<hr />\n\n<b>Who can submit a challenge?</b>\n\n<b>Legal reference: Iowa Code section 252I.8(1); 441 IAC 98.97(252I)</b>\n\nA challenge to the administrative levy process must be submitted by or on behalf of the obligor or joint owner. A joint owner is considered to be any person having a direct interest in the asset being levied, whether or not the person received notice of the administrative levy action by the Unit. If the joint owner is a minor, an adult having a direct interest in the minor’s welfare may submit the challenge on the minor’s behalf.\n\n<hr />\n\n<b>What is considered a “written” challenge?</b>\n\n<b>Legal reference: Iowa Code section 252I.8(2); 441 IAC 98.97(252I)</b>\n\nIowa Code requires all challenges to the administrative levy process to be in <b>writing</b>. Consider <b>any</b> written communication from the obligor or joint owner received by the Unit after the issuance of the Administrative Levy Notice to Obligor or Administrative Levy Notice to Joint Owner as a challenge. “Written communication” includes:\n<ul>\n \t<li>Letter or note.</li>\n \t<li>E-mail.</li>\n \t<li>Fax.</li>\n</ul>\nIf the obligor/joint owner states over the telephone or in person his or her intent to challenge the administrative levy and does <b>not</b> provide a written document to that effect within the specified timeframe, then no challenge is received.\n\n<hr />\n\n<b>What are the timeframes for submitting a challenge?</b>\n\n<b>Legal reference: Iowa Code section 252I.8(2); 441 IAC 98.97(252I)</b>\n\nBoth the administrative and district court challenges must be submitted <b>in writing</b> and <b>received</b> by the Unit within 10 working days of a previous action by the Unit (described below). Iowa Code section 252I.1(10) defines “working days” as “Monday, Tuesday, Wednesday, Thursday, and Friday, but excluding the holidays specified in section 1C.2, subsections 1 through 9.”\n\n<hr />\n\n<b>Administrative Challenges</b>\n\n<b>All administrative challenges must be in writing and physically received by the Unit within 10 working days of the date on form 470-3338, Administrative Levy Notice to Obligor, or form 470-3207, Administrative Levy Notice to Joint Owner.</b>\n\nTo determine whether the administrative challenge is timely:\n<ol>\n \t<li>Review the date displayed in the levy notice to obligor proof of service sent field on the ADMLEVY screen.</li>\n \t<li>Review the case narratives for the date the notices were mailed (in case the notices were mailed on a date other than the date displayed in the levy notice to obligor proof of service sent field).</li>\n \t<li>Count 10 days from the day <b>after</b> the date on the form or the date of mailing, whichever is most recent.\n<b>Example:</b> The date displayed in the levy notice to obligor proof of service sent field indicates that you mailed the Administrative Levy Notice to Obligor on Thursday, August 11th. Start counting from Friday, August 12th. The 13th, 14th, 20th and 21st are <b>weekend</b> days and are not counted in the 10 days. To be considered timely, you must receive the challenge on or before August 26th.</li>\n</ol>\n\n<hr />\n\n<b>Information for challenges to the Administrative Levy process</b>\n\nIf a payor has multiple ICAR cases, all of the payor’s case numbers display on form 470-3338, <i>Notice of Challenge to Admin Levy</i> and form 470-3208, <i>Notice of Decision Regarding Admin Levy Challenge</i>, <b>even when a case did not qualify for a levy</b>. Sometimes FIs use the case numbers from these forms when sending in the levy payment, causing money to distribute to a case in error.\n\nIf you receive a challenge to an administrative levy (from either the payor or the joint owner) and the payor has multiple ICAR cases, you need to verify which cases qualified for that levy. To verify which of the payor’s cases qualified for that levy, you can:\n<ol type=\"a\">\n \t<li>Use Global 360 to review form 470-3189, <i>Administrative Levy Notice to Financial Institution</i> or form 470-3188, <i>Administrative Levy Notice to Obligor</i>. Both of these forms should display the case numbers that qualified for this levy.</li>\n</ol>\nMake sure you view the forms with the correct FI and the correct date of the levy.\n\n<b>OR</b>\n<ol type=\"a\">\n \t<li>Review the narratives on <b>all</b> of the payor’s ICAR cases to locate the narrative (LEVY 17: CASE HAS MET ADMINISTRATIVE LEVY CRITERIA). This narrative must be dated closely before this FI was added to the case. If a case does not have the narrative (LEVY 17) before this FI was added to the case, the case did not qualify to be levied at that time.</li>\n \t<li>When you have verified which of the payor’s cases qualified for this levy, complete the CHALLENGE FILED DATE field and the corresponding TYPE field (on the ADMINISTRATIVE LEVY screen). ICAR will begin generating the <i>Notice of Challenge to Admin Levy</i>.\n<ol type=\"i\">\n \t<li>When the form is generating, remove the case numbers that did not qualify for this levy from the ICAR CASE NUMBERS FIELD ON THE FORM VIEW screen. After you edit the case number information, press F3 to update the changes.</li>\n \t<li>Then print the form.</li>\n \t<li>Verify that only the case numbers which qualified for this levy are on the form.</li>\n \t<li>Do this for each copy of the <i>Notice of Challenge to Admin Levy</i> (for the FI, the payor, and the joint owner).</li>\n \t<li>Image the copies.</li>\n</ol>\n</li>\n \t<li>After you have held the administrative levy challenge and have entered the information in the N.O.D. TO OBLIGOR &amp; FI (R/U): field (on the ADMINISTRATIVE LEVY screen), ICAR will begin generating the <i>Notice of Decision Regarding Admin Levy Challenge</i>.\n<ol type=\"i\">\n \t<li>When the form is generating, remove the case numbers that did not qualify for this levy from the CASE NUMBERS FIELD on the FORM VIEW screen. After you edit the case number information, press F3 to update the changes.</li>\n \t<li>Then print the form.</li>\n \t<li>Verify that only the case numbers which qualified for this levy are on the form.</li>\n \t<li>Do this for each copy of the Notice of Decision Regarding Admin Levy Challenge (for the FI, the payor, and the joint owner).</li>\n \t<li>Image the copies.</li>\n</ol>\n</li>\n</ol>\n\n<hr />\n\n<b>Reviewing the Facts of a Challenge</b>\n\n<b>Legal reference: Iowa Code section 252I.8(3); 441 IAC 98.97(1)</b>\n\nIowa law requires you to contact the challenging party to discuss the facts of the challenge when you receive a timely challenge. The challenging party has a right to a review of the facts of the case prior to you determining the outcome of the challenge and sending the Notice of Decision Regarding Administrative Levy Challenge.\n\n<b>When you receive a challenge that is not timely, still review the basis for the challenge to determine whether the Unit has made a mistake of fact. This is especially important when the challenge involves jointly held assets.</b>\n\nWhen you receive an <b>un-timely</b> challenge that involves jointly held assets, treat the challenge as if it were timely and proceed with contacting the challenging party to schedule a conference to review the facts of the case.\n\n<hr />\n\n<b>What is a “Mistake of Fact”?</b>\n\n<b>Legal reference: Iowa Code section 252I.8(3); 441 IAC 98.97(1)</b>\n\nThe determination of whether you uphold or release an administrative levy is based on the challenging party’s ability to prove the Unit made a “mistake of fact” regarding the levy. The definition of “mistake of fact” is based in <b>law</b>.\n\nAs defined in Iowa Code and the Iowa Administrative Code, a “<b>mistake of fact</b>” is a mistake <b><i>including but not limited to</i></b>, a mistake in the identity of the obligor or a mistake in the amount of delinquent support due; policy further extends this definition to a mistake in the amount of the asset or a mistake in the information reported to the Unit by the financial institution. The language “<b>including but not limited to</b>” means that <b>any</b> reason pertaining directly to the levy, above-stated or otherwise, the party provides as the basis for the challenge <b>must</b> be accepted as a <b>mistake of fact</b>. Until disproved by the Unit, you <b>cannot</b> deny a challenge because the challenge does not meet one of the specific above-named criteria.\n\nWhen you receive a challenge (whether or not it is timely) from a joint owner or involving a jointly-held asset, <b>accept the challenge</b> and ask the challenging party to provide verification of whose funds are deposited in the account. This information helps you determine whether to uphold or release the levy.\n\nSupervisory approval is required to release an administrative levy for any reason other than a mistake in identity, incorrect delinquency, or overpayment of balance. See <a href=\"http://dhs.iowa.gov/sites/default/files/11-a.pdf\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\"><img src=\"https://stcsruportalcli.blob.core.windows.net/csruportalwpcontent/2020/02/pdf.png\" /> <b>Employees Manual 11-A</b></a>, <b>Challenges to the Administrative Levy Process</b>.\n\n<b>Examples:</b>\n<ol>\n \t<li style=\"list-style-type: none;\">\n<ol>\n \t<li>You receive a timely challenge from the obligor. The challenge states in its entirety, “I disagree with you taking my money.” The obligor has cited a <b>mistake of fact</b>, as a mistake of fact is any reason, pertaining to the levy, the challenging party cites as the basis for the challenge.<b>Action:</b>\nSchedule a conference with the obligor to discuss the issues related to the levy.\n<b>Outcome:</b>\nRelease, revise or uphold the levy depending upon the information presented during the conference.<b>Update ICAR with the decision:</b>\n<ul>\n \t<li>If <i>upholding</i> or <i>revising</i> the levy:<b>DO NOT COMPLETE</b> the levy released date field.\n<ul>\n \t<li>Code the n.o.d. to obligor &amp; fi (r/u) field,</li>\n \t<li>Check for payment after 30 days,</li>\n \t<li>Once the payment is received, code the process ended date field.</li>\n</ul>\n</li>\n \t<li>If <i>releasing</i> the levy:\n<ul>\n \t<li>Code the levy released date field, <b>and</b></li>\n \t<li>Code the process ended date field.</li>\n</ul>\n</li>\n</ul>\n</li>\n</ol>\n</li>\n</ol>\n&nbsp;\n<ol>\n \t<li style=\"list-style-type: none;\">\n<ol>\n \t<li>You receive a timely challenge from the obligor. The challenge states the account in question belongs to the obligor’s minor daughter and that the obligor’s name is on the account due to the daughter’s age. The obligor has cited a <b>mistake of fact</b>, as the account does not really belong to the obligor.<b>Action:</b>\nSchedule a conference with the obligor to discuss the issues related to the levy. During the conference, the obligor states the daughter is saving her babysitting money to buy a new bicycle. Request the obligor provide proof of the deposits/withdrawals.\n<b>Outcome:</b>\nIf the only deposits/withdrawals are those made by or on behalf of the daughter, <b>release</b> the levy.</li>\n</ol>\n</li>\n</ol>\n&nbsp;\n<ol>\n \t<li>You receive an un-timely challenge from the joint owner. The joint owner is the obligor’s elderly mother. The challenge states that the obligor’s mother placed the obligor’s name on her account for when she passes away. The joint owner has cited a <b>mistake of fact</b>, as the account does not really belong to the obligor.<b>Action:</b>\nSchedule a conference with the joint owner to discuss the issues related to the levy. During the conference, the obligor’s mother states the obligor has no knowledge of the account and has not made any deposits to or withdrawals from the account. Request the joint owner provide proof of the deposits/withdrawals.\n<b>Outcome:</b>\nIf the only deposits/withdrawals are those made by the obligor’s mother, release the levy.</li>\n</ol>\n\n<hr />\n\n<b>District Court Challenges</b>\n\n<b>All district court challenges must be in writing and physically received by the Unit within 10 working days of the date on form 470-3338, <i>Notice of Decision Regarding Administrative Levy Challenge</i>.</b>\n\nTo determine whether the district court challenge is timely:\n<ol>\n \t<li>Review the date displayed in the n.o.d. to obligor &amp; fi (r/u) field on the ADMLEVY screen.</li>\n \t<li>Review the case narratives for the date the <i>Notice of Decision Regarding Administrative Levy Challenge</i> was mailed (in case the notice was mailed on a date other than the date in displayed in the n.o.d. to obligor &amp; fi (r/u) field.</li>\n \t<li>Count 10 days from the day <b>after</b> the date on the form or the date of mailing, whichever is most recent.</li>\n</ol>\nIf the obligor or joint owner contacts you by telephone or in person regarding a challenge, remind the obligor/joint owner that all challenges must be in writing and received within 10 working days of the date on the <i>Administrative Levy Notice to Obligor</i> or <i>Administrative Levy Notice to Joint Owner</i>. If possible, try to resolve the challenge issues pro-actively and avoid the necessity of a conference. If the obligor/joint owner calls you ensure that the case selection criteria are correct and that the asset can be levied.\n\nThe challenge process begins when the obligor/joint owner <b>actually submits a written challenge</b>. Do not notify the financial institution of a challenge after a telephone conversation or a walk-in conversation unless the person actually submits a <b>written</b> challenge to the Unit. If the person takes the written challenge with him/her, the challenge is not actually submitted to the Unit.\n\n<b>Example:</b>\n\nThe obligor requests a telephone call from you. You call the obligor and answer the obligor’s questions about the administrative levy. Specifically remind the obligor that any challenge has to be in writing and received by the Unit within 10 working days. Narrate this reminder and do <b>not</b> generate form 470-3338, <i>Notice of Challenge to Administrative Levy</i>, to the financial institution, or form 470-3208, <i>Notice of Decision Regarding Administrative Levy Challenge</i>, to the obligor/joint owner.\";i:1582231562545;s:2706:\"<b>Questions from the Obligor/Joint Owner</b>\n\n<b>Q.</b> What authority do you have to levy my accounts?\n<b>A.</b> Iowa Code, <a href=\"http://search.legis.state.ia.us/nxt/gateway.dll/ic?f=templates&amp;fn=default.htm\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\">Chapter 252I</a>.\n\n<b>Q.</b> How did you find out where I bank?\n<b>A.</b> Through automated sources or other confidential sources.\n\n<b>Q.</b> If I change financial institutions, will you be able to find my account?\n<b>A.</b> Yes.\n\n<b>Q.</b> Do you care if I need the money for living expenses?\n<b>A.</b> We will only take up to 50% of the account. The remaining balance is available for your use.\n\n<b>Q.</b> How often can you levy my account?\n<b>A.</b> As often as your case meets the criteria.\n\n<b>Q.</b> Can I close the account?\n<b>A.</b> Not until the money is taken.\n\n<b>Q.</b> Can I write checks on the account?\n<b>A.</b> Yes, you may write checks on any balance remaining after the financial institution freezes up to 50% of your accounts.\n\n<b>Q.</b> My notice says you won’t take the money for 15-20 days, but the financial institution already took it.\n<b>A.</b> The financial institution immediately freezes up to 50% of the funds in the account, and does not remit the funds until the 15- to 20-day timeframe is up. This allows time for you to challenge the levy.\n\n<b>Q.</b> Can I enter into a payment agreement to avoid or stop the administrative levy?\n<b>A.</b> An administrative payment agreement does not stop a levy already in progress. To avoid an administrative levy, pay the full amount of your support plus something on the delinquency each month.\n\n<hr />\n\n<b>Questions from Financial Institutions</b>\n\n<b>Q.</b> Do I have to send the payment in this envelope?\n<b>A.</b> Yes, in order for our Collection Services Center to properly process the payment, you must send the payment in the envelope provided.\n\n<b>Q.</b> How will you notify us (the financial institution) if the obligor challenges the levy?\n<b>A.</b> We will call the financial institution and fax or mail form 470-3338, Notice of Challenge to Administrative Levy.\n\n<b>Q.</b> Does our customer know about this levy?\n<b>A.</b> Yes, we provided the obligor notice of the levy action.\n\n<b>Q.</b> When do I need to send in the money?\n<b>A.</b> Refer to the Administrative Levy Notice to Financial Institution you received for the specific timeframes. It is approximately 15-20 days from receipt of the notice.\n\n<hr />\n\nIf you have a frequently asked question and cannot find the answer here, please refer the question to the Enforcement CORE team, and the question and answer will be added to the frequently asked questions section.\";i:1582231563233;s:1851:\"As previously mentioned, the identification of assets occurs primarily through an automated process. However, there are instances when information provided by a party to the case requires further verification.\n\nWhen the obligee or third party contacts the Unit with information regarding the obligor’s assets, attempt to verify the information. When the obligee/third party provides limited information and you are unable to verify an asset, you may be able to obtain additional asset information by reviewing the following documents in the case file:\n<ul>\n \t<li>Form 470-0188, <i>Application for Non-assistance Support Services</i></li>\n \t<li>Form 470-0204, <i>Financial Statement</i></li>\n</ul>\nYou may also:\n<ul>\n \t<li>Review the Case Payment History (PAYHIST) screen to see if a recent payment has applied to the case and if so, use the Check Viewer software to review the payment for a possible source of the account. Contact the Collection Services Center (CSC) for more up-to-date payment information. To contact CSC, e-mail the CSC worker assigned to the case based upon the last name of the obligor (refer to the Unit telephone directory).</li>\n \t<li>Contact the obligee or third party for additional information. If you are unable to verify the asset information and the source has a Release of Information (ROI) on file, send the source a status/letter explaining that you were unable to verify the asset information.</li>\n</ul>\nYou may obtain information from any source; however, due to confidentiality laws, you may only provide information to parties of the case, attorneys of the parties, or persons with an ROI on file. See the confidentiality manual, <a href=\"http://dhs.iowa.gov/sites/default/files/9-a.pdf\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\"><img src=\"https://stcsruportalcli.blob.core.windows.net/csruportalwpcontent/2020/02/pdf.png\" /> Title 9-A</a>, for details.\";i:1582231563634;s:1052:\"<b>Payments Made by the Obligor</b>\n\nUpon receipt of form 470-3188, <i>Administrative Levy Notice to Obligor</i>, the obligor may offer to pay the delinquency in return for a withdrawal of the administrative levy.\n\nNormally, when the obligor makes a cash-remittance payment, the payment is credited on ICAR as a regular or \"REG\" payment. However, when the obligor makes a REG payment in direct response to an administrative levy action, it is important to count the payment as a levy or \"LVY\" payment. This is because the funds available to pay the Iowa financial institutions for the FIDM asset information are based on the state\'s share of the PA levy collections.\n\nWhen you receive a REG payment from an obligor as a result of administrative levy notification, mark the payment as an <i>administrative levy</i> payment and forward it to CSC. This allows CSC to credit the payment to the administrative levy process.\n\nIf a levy payment is already on ICAR with a fund source \"REG\", CSC will no longer change the fund source from \"REG to \"LVY\".\";i:1582231564304;s:1634:\"When you receive form 470-3170, <i>Asset Verification Request</i>, from the financial institution:\n\n<b>Active Accounts:</b>\n<ul>\n \t<li>Locate the corresponding ASSET screen on ICAR.</li>\n \t<li>Enter a “Y” in the assets verified field.</li>\n \t<li>Update the information about the account number (acct nbr), amount (amt), account type (acct. type) and joint owner (joint) as needed.</li>\n \t<li>Press F3 twice to update the screen. ICAR changes the existing “N” entry in the admin levy (y/n/h) field to an \"H\".</li>\n \t<li>Narrate as necessary.</li>\n</ul>\nDo not immediately proceed with the levy. After updating the ASSET screen, you must wait until the administrative levy case selection program runs and ICAR issues a calendar flag (LEVY 5) when the case meets criteria.\n\n<b>Closed Accounts/Accounts With a Negative Balance:</b>\n<ul>\n \t<li>Locate the corresponding ASSET screen on ICAR.</li>\n \t<li>Enter a “Y” in the assets verified field.</li>\n \t<li>Enter “1.00” in the amt field.</li>\n \t<li>Press F3 twice to update the screen.</li>\n \t<li>Narrate as necessary.</li>\n</ul>\n<b>No Account at Financial Institution:</b>\n<ul>\n \t<li>Locate the corresponding ASSET screen on ICAR.</li>\n \t<li>Enter an “N” in the assets verified field.</li>\n \t<li>Press F3 twice to update the screen.</li>\n \t<li>Narrate as necessary.</li>\n \t<li>Review asset information for any possible mismatch.</li>\n</ul>\n<b>Blank Form Returned:</b>\n<ul>\n \t<li>Contact the financial institution by telephone.</li>\n \t<li>Re-send the <i>Asset Verification Request</i> (by fax or first-class mail), if necessary.</li>\n</ul>\";i:1582231564839;s:2725:\"The Unit notifies the financial institution to encumber (levy) funds in the obligor’s account by sending form 470-3189, <i>Administrative Levy Notice to Financial Institution</i>. Before initiating the levy, you may need to review additional information pertaining to the FIDM process, such as whether the financial institution accepts direct levies; or if an interstate referral is required, what type of UIFSA Transmittal is required by the state in which the <b>asset</b> is located.\n\nUpon receipt of the <i>Administrative Levy Notice to Financial Institution</i>, a multi-state financial institution may refuse to honor the levy. This may occur when the financial institution does not have a physical location in Iowa. Iowa law requires financial institutions operating within Iowa’s borders to honor an administrative levy from the Unit. However, federal or state law does <b>not</b> require financial institutions operating outside of Iowa’s borders to honor a levy from Iowa, unless the financial institution is registered to do business in Iowa.\n\nIf the financial institution refuses to honor the administrative levy and it is not an Iowa-operating financial institution, determine if the financial institution has a registered agent in Iowa as follows:\n<span class=\"small\">(Suggestion: print or read all of the steps in the example below before beginning)</span>\n<ol>\n \t<li>Access the <a href=\"http://www.sos.state.ia.us/corp/corp_search.asp\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\">Iowa Corporation Search Web site</a> (broken link).</li>\n \t<li>Type an entry in either the \"Submit Entry\" or \"Submit Number\" fields, and click the appropriate button.\nExample of Submit Entry: <b>Capital One</b>\nEnter <b>Capital One</b> and click \"Submit Entry\".</li>\n \t<li>Click on the <b>Corp#</b> to open the next page.</li>\n \t<li>The Registered Agent or Reserving Party in Iowa for Capital One is:\nPRENTICE HALL CORPORATION SYSTEM\n729 INSURANCE EXCHANGE BLDG\nDES MOINES, IA 50309\nThis information appears in the third set of informational boxes.</li>\n</ol>\nThe above-referenced company is the registered agent to which you may send the <i>Administrative Levy Notice to Financial Institution</i>.\n\nNarrate all steps taken when using a registered agent. You may wish to add the registered agent to your personal resource list for future reference.\n\nSee <a href=\"http://dhs.iowa.gov/sites/default/files/11-a.pdf\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\"><img src=\"https://stcsruportalcli.blob.core.windows.net/csruportalwpcontent/2020/02/pdf.png\" /> <b>Title 11-A</b></a>, EPICS’ Review of Cases Meeting Levy Criteria, Result of EPICS’ Review; Notice to Financial Institution and Account Holder, Sending the Administrative Levy Notice to the Financial Institution.\";i:1582231565719;s:810:\"<p>You must notify the obligor of an administrative levy action within two working days of sending form 470-3189, <i>Administrative Levy Notice to Financial Institution</i>, to the financial institution.</p>\n\n<p>You satisfy this requirement by sending form 470-3188, <i>Administrative Levy Notice to Obligor</i>, to the obligor’s last known address. This form tells the obligor that an administrative levy notice was sent to the financial institution and provides the obligor information on how to file an administrative challenge.</p>\n\n<p>See <b><a href=\"http://dhs.iowa.gov/sites/default/files/11-a.pdf\" target=\"_blank\"><img src=\"https://stcsruportalcli.blob.core.windows.net/csruportalwpcontent/2020/02/pdf.png\"> Title 11-A</a>, Notice to Financial Institution and Account Holder, Sending the Administrative Levy Notice to the Obligor</b>.</p>\n\";i:1582231566055;s:2569:\"<p>Statute requires the Unit to notify any party known to have an interest in an account of the administrative levy action.  The FIDM program does not provide address information for individuals identified as the joint owner of an asset. Therefore, it is important that you utilize the information that is provided by the financial institution (e.g., joint owner’s name and/or SSN) to locate the joint owner’s address and send form 470-3207, <i>Administrative Levy Notice to Joint Owner</i>.</p>\n\n<p>Conduct location work for the joint owner’s address, utilizing the approved sources as outlined in the manual.</p>\n\n<p>Federal and state laws strictly limit the Unit’s use of certain sources for the location of non-case participants, such as joint-account owners.</p>\n\n<p>When using any of the Unit’s location sources to locate a joint owner not listed on ICAR, ask your supervisor how to document the reasons for your accessing these sources. See <a href=\"http://intra/csruhandbooks/Handbooks/Admin%20Levy/Contents/LOCATION%20Trak.xls\" target=\"_blank\"><img src=\"https://stcsruportalcli.blob.core.windows.net/csruportalwpcontent/2020/02/excel.png\"> sample tracking sheet</a>.</p>\n\n<p><b>Unable to Determine the Joint Owner’s Address</b></p>\n<p>If no SSN is provided for the joint owner, and you cannot find an address or be certain that the address you have found is actually that of the joint owner, enter the obligor’s address from the PAYOR screen in the joint owner address field on the ASSET screen.</p>\n\n<p><b>Updating Joint Owner Information on the ASSET Screen</b></p>\n<p>When ICAR displays a “Y” in the joint field on the ASSET screen for an asset, ICAR allows you to enter information into the joint owner name and joint owner address fields. <b>Note:</b> Joint owner information (if available) must be entered into these fields before proceeding with the levy. Once you enter the information and update the screen, ICAR protects these fields and you cannot edit them.</p>\n\n<p>See <b><a href=\"http://dhs.iowa.gov/sites/default/files/11-a.pdf\" target=\"_blank\"><img src=\"https://stcsruportalcli.blob.core.windows.net/csruportalwpcontent/2020/02/pdf.png\"> Title 11-A</a>, Financial Institution Data Match Information, Joint Accounts; EPICS’ Review of Cases Meeting Levy Criteria, <i>Joint Owners Who Are Minors</i>; Notice to Financial Institution and Account Holder, <i>Sending the Administrative Levy Notice to Joint Owner</i>;</b> and <b>Challenges to the Administrative Levy Process, <i>Joint Owner Identified During Challenge Process</i>,</b> for definitions and procedures for handling jointly held assets.</p>\";i:1582231572664;s:8795:\"<p>CSRU is sending administrative levies on Thrift Savings Plan (TSP) accounts.</p>\n<p>TSP is a retirement savings and investment plan for Federal civilian employees and members of the uniformed services. It is a defined contribution plan that offers the same types of savings and tax benefits that many private corporations offer their employees under “401(k)” plans.</p>\n<p>Levies on a TSP account are similar to levies on a financial institution (FI) account with the following exceptions:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>A levy on a TSP account is faxed to the institution (not mailed).</li>\n<li>The timeframe from faxing a levy on a TSP account through receiving the levy payment will be approximately <span style=\"color: red;\">3 – 4 months</span>.</li>\n<li>The payor’s TSP account is frozen for the entire time the levy is being processed.</li>\n<li>10% of the levy amount is withheld for the payor’s tax purposes.</li>\n<li>The levies to TSP use a different set of levy forms other than the ICAR generated forms. Since the TSP levies are generated and processed by a special team at EPICS, they have the correct forms available to them.</li>\n<li>It is ok to levy TSP accounts if the payor is on active duty in the Military.\n<ul>\n<li>CSRU has no restrictions or policies against levying an account at a regular FI for an active military member. However, a payor who is on active duty may not be able to timely challenge a levy on a TSP account.</li>\n<li>If the payor (or joint owner) files a challenge to a levy on a TSP account, contact the Policy Unit at <a href=\"mailto:CSRUPolicy-Levy@dhs.state.ia.us\" target=\"_blank\"><b>CSRU Policy - Levy</b></a> for instructions on how to proceed.</li>\n</ul></li>\n<li>It is ok to levy TSP accounts if the payor is receiving federal VA benefits that are not attachable through income withholding.</li>\n<li>It is ok to levy multiple TSP accounts for one ICAR payor.\n<ul>\n<li>If the payor has more than one TSP account, the Administrative Levy Notice to Financial Institution must specify how much money is to be levied from each TSP account. The amounts on the TSP cover letter must also match the amounts identified on the levy form. (The TSP account codes are listed on the TSP’s ASSET screen with a code in the ACCT NBR: field.) The codes are:\n<ul>\n<li>U = Uniformed Services</li>\n<li>C = Civilian Employee</li>\n<li>BPAU = BPA Uniform</li>\n<li>BPAC = BPA Civilian</li>\n</ul></li>\n</ul></li>\n<li>Before releasing a levy on a TSP account, contact the Policy Unit at CSRU Policy - Enforcement for a case review.</li>\n</ul>\n<p>A levy to TSP is a lengthy process and will possibly take a <b>minimum</b> of <span style=\"color: red;\">3 – 4 months</span> to receive the payment from the levy (and possibly longer). Do not contact TSP to ask when a payment will be received. If you have questions on when a payment will be received, contact <a href=\"mailto:CSRUPolicy-Levy@dhs.state.ia.us\" target=\"_blank\"><b>CSRU Policy - Levy</b></a> for a case review.</p>\n\n<hr />\n\n<p><b>Question and Answers (Q +A) for TSP Account Levies</b></p>\n<p><b>Q.</b> What is a TSP account?<br />\n<b>A.</b> It is a retirement savings and investment plan for Federal civilian employees and members of the uniformed services. It is a defined contribution plan that offers the same types of savings and tax benefits that many private corporations offer their employees under “401(k)” plans.</p>\n\n<p><b>Q.</b> How do I recognize a TSP account on ICAR?\n<b>A.</b> On the ASSET screen, this information will display:</p>\n<br />\n<p>FEDERAL ID:           521529691001<br />\nASSET PROVIDER:   THRIFT SAVINGS PLAN<br />\nADDRESS LINE 1:    TSP LEGAL PROCESSING UNIT<br />\nADDRESS LINE 2:    CODIS - PO BOX 4390<br />\nCITY/STATE/ZIP:    FAIRFAX VA 22038 4390\n</p>\n<p>The ACCOUNT NBR: field displays a code that identifies the type of account the payor has at TSP.</p>\n<ul>\n<li>U = Uniformed Services</li>\n<li>C = Civilian Employee</li>\n<li>BPAU = BPA Uniform</li>\n<li>BPAC = BPA Civilian</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p><b>Q.</b> How do I submit a levy on a TSP account?<br />\n<b>A.</b> There is a special team in the EPICS office who generates and processes levies on the TSP accounts.</p>\n<p><b>Q.</b> How do I submit a modified levy to TSP?<br />\n<b>A.</b> If you view a case where the balance due is significantly less than the amount stated in the original TSP levy and the payment from the TSP levy will cause a large overpayment if it is applied to the payor’s ICAR case, contact the Policy Unit at <a href=\"mailto:CSRUPolicy-Levy@dhs.state.ia.us\" target=\"_blank\"><b>CSRU Policy - Levy</b></a> for a case review.</p>\n<p><b>Q.</b> What if I receive a challenge to the levy on a TSP account?<br />\n<b>A.</b> If you receive a challenge to the levy on a TSP account, immediately contact the Policy Unit at <a href=\"mailto:CSRUPolicy-Levy@dhs.state.ia.us\" target=\"_blank\"><b>CSRU Policy - Levy</b></a> for instructions on how to proceed.</p>\n<p><b>Q.</b> How do I submit a release or revision for a levy on a TSP account?<br />\n<b>A.</b> The TSP Levy Team at EPICS will process all releases or revisions on TSP levies. However, if you view an ICAR case where a levy has been faxed to TSP and</p>\n<ol>\n<li>The balance due on the case is now zero <b>and</b></li>\n<li>Narratives do not show that a release or revision of the levy has been faxed to TSP,</li>\n<li>Send an e-mail referral to the EPICS mailbox with “URGENT - TSP” in the subject line of the e-mail. Include the ICAR case number, the payor’s name, and a comment that the ICAR account balance is zero and a release or revision for the TSP levy may need completed.</li>\n</ol>\n<p>The TSP Levy Team will review the ICAR case. If a release or revision is needed, the TSP Levy Team will issue one with the forms that are specific to the TSP levies.</p>\n<p><b>Q.</b> What is the timeline for the TSP Levy process?<br />\n<b>A.</b> The TSP processes a levy in four steps:</p>\n<ol>\n<li>As soon as possible after TSP receives an order to withhold, the payor’s account will be “frozen.”</li>\n<li>TSP will then evaluate the documents to ensure completeness. If it is not complete, TSP will send a written request for complete documents. TSP will remove the freeze if a complete copy is not received within 30 days of TSP’s written request.</li>\n<li>When TSP receives a complete order to withhold, TSP will evaluate it to determine whether it is a qualifying levy.</li>\n<li>TSP will mail a decision letter to the payor and provide a copy to all other parties having an interest in the action. The decision letter will describe the effect the levy will have on the payor’s account and state when the freeze will be removed from the account. If the levy does not qualify, the decision letter will explain why. If the levy qualifies and requires a payment from TSP, the letter will also explain how the payment amount will be calculated and when the payment will be made.</li>\n</ol>\n<p>The timeframes in a TSP levy:</p>\n<ol>\n<li>After TSP receives the levy form, it may take <span style=\"color: red;\">30-60 days</span> to review it and generate a decision letter. (See steps 1-4 above.)</li>\n<li>The payment date will generally be set 30 calendar days from the date of the decision letter.</li>\n</ol>\n<p>If a TSP account was frozen upon receipt of an order to withhold, the freeze will be removed:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>upon receipt of an order removing the freeze,</li>\n<li>after payment pursuant to a qualifying order to deliver, or</li>\n<li>as soon as possible, after TSP informs the parties in writing that the document is not a qualifying levy.</li>\n</ul>\n<p><b>Q.</b> Will CSRU levy a TSP account more than once?<br />\n<b>A.</b> The TSP Levy Team will generate and process a levy for any ICAR case that meets the administrative levy criteria. However, because a levy on a TSP account can take a minimum of <span style=\"color: red;\">3 – 4 months</span> to complete, there may be a circumstance where the TSP account has re-matched the same ICAR case before CSRU has received the payment from the previous TSP levy.</p>\n<p>The TSP Levy Team reviews the ICAR case for previous TSP levies. If a levy was previously generated and processed on a TSP account, payments will be reviewed to see if CSRU has received the payment from the previous TSP levy. If the TSP levy payment has applied to the ICAR case, the TSP Levy Team will generate and process a new levy. If no TSP levy payment has applied, the TSP Levy Team will not fax a new levy to TSP at this time and will monitor the case for the incoming TSP levy payment. After the TSP levy payment applies, if the case still meets the criteria for an administrative levy, a new levy will be generated and processed.</p>\";i:1582231619231;s:3062:\"<p>Identification of an asset is the very first step in the administrative levy process. See <b><a href=\"http://dhs.iowa.gov/sites/default/files/11-a.pdf\" target=\"_blank\"><img src=\"https://stcsruportalcli.blob.core.windows.net/csruportalwpcontent/2020/02/pdf.png\"> Title 11-A</a>, Entering and Verifying Asset Information.</b></p>\n\n<p>ICAR considers asset information received through FIDM as automatically verified. ICAR issues a calendar flag (LEVY 5) to the EPICS worker when asset information is received and the case passes the administrative levy criteria. This prompts you to review the case and determine whether to pursue an administrative levy.</p>\n\n<p><b>The Financial Institution (FI): Wells Fargo</b><br />\nWells Fargo no longer accepts our form 470-3170, <i>Asset Verification Request</i>.</p>\n\n<p>If the ASSET screen displays this FI and you are reviewing the case for an administrative levy:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>Do not send form 470-3170, <i>Asset Verification Request</i> to <b>any</b> Wells Fargo FIs.</li>\n<li>Instead, proceed with an administrative levy on the account and send to this FI form 470-3189, <i>Administrative Levy Notice to Financial Institution</i>.\n<ul>\n<li>Even if no amount displays in the AMT: field.</li>\n<li>Even if the asset is not verified.</li>\n</ul></li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>Use any of the following to verify non-FIDM assets, or to re-verify FIDM-provided assets:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>Generate batch form 470-3170, Asset Verification Request, using the ASSET screen. Refer to <b><a href=\"http://dhs.iowa.gov/sites/default/files/11-a.pdf\" target=\"_blank\"><img src=\"https://stcsruportalcli.blob.core.windows.net/csruportalwpcontent/2020/02/pdf.png\"> Title 11-A</a>, Entering and Verifying Asset Information, <i>Adding Asset Information Manually</i></b>, for procedures to add an asset.</li>\n<li>Fax the <i>Asset Verification Request</i> to the financial institution.</li>\n<li>Telephone the financial institution. \n<p>Use one of these options when:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>The financial institution fails to reply to a previously sent <i>Asset Verification Request</i>.</li>\n<li>The information received, either through FIDM or in the <i>Asset Verification Request</i>, is incomplete or vague.</li>\n</ul></li>\n</ul>\n<p>You may wish to fax or telephone the financial institution when an immediate response is needed.</p>\n<ul>\n<li>Develop your own resource list, which may include the names, addresses, telephone numbers and contact names of frequently contacted financial institutions. You may wish to create your list in an Excel spreadsheet so that it can be easily updated.</li>\n<li>If you find a contact for an out-of-state financial institution, forward the contact information to the appropriate individual in Central Office. When you are verifying an asset, be aware that not all assets can be levied. Refer to <b><a href=\"http://dhs.iowa.gov/sites/default/files/11-a.pdf\" target=\"_blank\"><img src=\"https://stcsruportalcli.blob.core.windows.net/csruportalwpcontent/2020/02/pdf.png\"> Title 11-A</a>, EPICS’ Review of Cases Meeting Levy Criteria</b>.</li>\n<li>If no asset exists, review the case for the next enforcement step to be taken.</li>\n</ul>\";}"
